<HEAD>Storm Strands Two Climbers on Half Dome</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YOSEMITE NATIONAL PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two climbers trapped overnight by a storm completed their ascent up Half Dome with the help of rescuers and then hiked 8 miles to the <LOCATION> Yosemite </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> floor, a park spokeswoman said. <PERSON> Charley </PERSON> <PERSON> Hampson </PERSON>, 33, and <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Enger </PERSON>, 32, both of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, were 4,200 feet above the valley when they called for help about 10 a.m. Sunday, spokeswoman <PERSON> Mallory </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said Monday. The men, who began a two-day climb of the rock's northwest face on Saturday, shouted to climbers above them to get help because the storm, which dumped rain and snow on them and froze their ropes overnight. A <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> helicopter lowered fresh ropes, sleeping bags, warm clothes and food by about 5 p.m. Sunday, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. It then lowered two rescue climbers who helped the two climb the remaining 600 feet to safety.
