<FIRST>r i PM-SouthSeasTurmoil     05-31 0846</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Seas Turmoil,0873</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disorders And Ethnic Tensions Bring Turmoil To South Seas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD BILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Political disorders, ethnic tensions, poverty and international disputes are churning up the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seas </LOCATION> in an arc curving sharply northward from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> and back down to <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Vanuatu </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fiji </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tahiti </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Papua </LOCATION> <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tonga </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Samoa </LOCATION>, even <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> themselves, have had a taste of trouble in the past year. Most recently it was rioting in <LOCATION> Vanuatu </LOCATION> over land claims, and in the French territory of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION> 19 native Kanaks were killed in a shootout with <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> troops in ethnic and political disorders. <LOCATION> Fiji </LOCATION> has seen two coups in the past year, and the former British island remains unstable in the aftermath. <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> is concerned about what it sees as the speading influence of <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>'s Col. <PERSON> Moammar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON> in the area and the inroads made by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in what long has been seen as an `` American lake.'' A commentator in the <ORGANIZATION> Sydney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> newspaper said the image of a South Seas paradise may have been permanently tarnished. The past year also has seen riots in <LOCATION> Tahiti </LOCATION> and political upheaval in <LOCATION> Papua </LOCATION> <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION> over the alleged corruption of Cabinet ministers. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> faces racial unrest as indigenous Maoris press the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> government of Prime Minister <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lange </PERSON> with a battery of land and fisheries claims. In <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, aborigines are using this year's bicentennial celebrations to highlight grievances they say grew out of European settlement 200 years ago. In early May, bloody violence erupted over territorial and French presidential elections in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION>, culminating in the rescue of French hostages held in caves by Melanesian separatists; 21 people were killed. On May 16, a drunken mob ran riot through <LOCATION> Vanuatu </LOCATION>'s capital, <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vila </LOCATION>, looting shops and smashing office windows. One man died, nine others were injured and police arrested 30 people in the rioting over land claims. <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> responded to the crisis by airlifting riot-control gear to <LOCATION> Vanuatu </LOCATION> at Prime Minister <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Lini </PERSON>'s request Prime Minister <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawke </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> linked <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> to the rioting and said <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> could not stand by as a friendly country's government is undermined by what he called a non-democratic process. `` There is no doubt about a <LOCATION> Libyan </LOCATION> connection in <LOCATION> Vanuatu </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Hawke </PERSON> said. `` In a city with a population of less than 20,000 it is clear that these disturbances have been on a very serious scale.'' <LOCATION> Vanuatu </LOCATION>, formerly the <LOCATION> British-French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hebrides </LOCATION>, shocked the generally pro-Western <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> with its decision in 1986 to establish diplomatic relations with <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Since then, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has sought fishing agreements with <LOCATION> Papua </LOCATION> <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION> and impoverished <LOCATION> Kiribati </LOCATION>, creating concern in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> as well as <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> about Soviet inroads in the region. More recently, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has approached <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> for fishing access to Australian ports for refueling purposes and to Australian airports for fishing crews in transit. <PERSON> Hawke </PERSON> said he would treat the request with caution. Elsewhere in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>, such nations as <LOCATION> Tonga </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Samoa </LOCATION> face poverty, overcrowding and unemployment. Many of the islanders have migrated to <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> in search of jobs. `` All these are turning the once tranquil <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> into an increasingly complex set of real and potential troublespots,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Sydney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> said. The <ORGANIZATION> Sydney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> echoed that concern, calling the situation a powderkeg. `` The multiple problems of these islands has led to a rising discontent,'' the Telegraph said. `` <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> has been making big efforts to gain a stronger foothold in every island group through fishery deals and aid.'' Racial and ethnic divisions remain a major underlying problem of many <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> islands, where populations are mainly Melanesian. <LOCATION> Fiji </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION> are examples. <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> is the major power in the region and its largest aid donor. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON> has expressed concern about Libyan activities, going as far as to close down <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>'s diplomatic mission in <LOCATION> Canberra </LOCATION> last year after an incident involving the aboriginal activist <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Mansell </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mansell </PERSON> had returned from <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> saying <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON> was prepared to bankroll a black revolution in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. The scattered violence in the South Seas has no single connective thread, although in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Polynesia </LOCATION> the crises erupted after <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> refused to follow the regional pattern of decolonization and independence. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> already suffers a major image problem in the South Seas with the bombing of the <ORGANIZATION> Greenpeace </ORGANIZATION> vessel Rainbow Warrior in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> in 1985 and its continued underground nuclear testing on the Mururoa atoll over the objections of almost every island state in the region. The island states, supported by <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, have declared the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> a nuclear-free zone. In a major turnaround, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1986 designated the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> an area of concern because of a buildup of the Soviet Pacific fleet. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials believe the Soviet fleet consists of 755 ships and patrol craft, including 141 submarines.
</TEXT>
