<FIRST>r a PM-WelfareEntrepreneurs     05-31 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Welfare Entrepreneurs,0728</SECOND>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Welfare Recipients Become Entrepreneurs in Pilot Projects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A program targeted at low-income women in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> is helping welfare recipients create their own jobs and build successful businesses, and promoters hope its success will spread to the rest of the country. `` A lot of people told me this was going to fail miserably,'' said <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Keeley </PERSON>, president of the 5-year-old Women's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which was graduating its first class of 18 fledgling entrepreneurs today Under the plan, welfare recipients receive training and then continue receiving public assistance while receiving subsidized loans to help them start businesses ranging from cleaning companies to hair-styling salons. `` The first hurdle we had to cross in this area was skepticism. Can poor women do it?'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>. The organization began its first class for welfare entrepreneurs in March under the federal Self Employment Investment Demonstration. <PERSON> Keeley </PERSON> said she hopes 90 people will graduate by the end of the year. <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> is the first of five states to launch the program, which is coordinated by the private, nonprofit <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> said. The other states are <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. The corporation persuaded federal officials to waive regulations which reduce or eliminate benefits when recipients get jobs, <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> said. Participants continue receiving assistance even after they start their own businesses so they can re-invest profits. At the Women's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, recipients devise a business plan, learn about marketing, financial management and other skills and are encouraged to start thinking like entrepreneurs. They can borrow up to $ 5,000, to be loaned in small increments as their businesses progress at 1 percent above the prime lending rate, said <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> <PERSON> Yamamoto </PERSON>, who directs the organization's pilot project known as the Self Employment Training Opportunities Program. Once a month for at least a year, recipients are required to work with the organization's accountant to do bookkeeping. `` The whole point of that is to get them off on the right foot,'' Ms. <PERSON> Yamamoto </PERSON> said. Women's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> received nearly all its current annual budget of $ 600,000 from foundations and other private sources, Ms. <PERSON> Keeley </PERSON> said. Organizers hope to help other states begin similar projects, she said. An aspiring filmmaker, one of the few men to complete the program, said welfare recipients face challenges other entrepreneurs do n't. `` Most of us who have been down and out have had our self-esteem shattered. They realized it was important to build that up,'' he said of the program, asking not to be identified for fear it might hurt his business. Promoters point out that the program is n't a cure-all for welfare problems. `` People get poor for different reasons. They are going to escape in different ways,'' <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> reasoned. Only 10 percent to 15 percent of <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>'s 57,000 AFDC recipients are likely candidates for the program, said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON>, planning director for the state Office of Jobs Policy. Nationally, the percentage is 2 percent to 5 percent, he said. A forerunner to the current program was launched three years ago. In that time, 22 women started businesses and three have already repaid their loans, Ms. <PERSON> Keeley </PERSON> said. `` They do n't hand the business to you. You have to work for it,'' said <PERSON> Ellie </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, who has cleaned homes and businesses most of her life and started a janitorial service in late 1986. `` They give you the right contacts. If you do n't follow through, it's your fault.'' Ms. <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, who had been on and off assistance for 30 years, is self-supporting now and employs about 10 people. `` I'm glad I'm off Welfare makes you feel depressed and down,'' she said. Before the pilot program ends in 1992, <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> hopes to persuade federal officials to waive permanently regulations that bar welfare recipients who turn a business profit from keeping their benefits while they get their companies off the ground. `` We need the federal government to let go a little to let it succeed,'' <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> said. `` I must say the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> has been very cooperative, but right now the waiver process is onerous.''
</TEXT>
