<FIRST>r p PM-Wilder     05-31 0819</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wilder,0840</SECOND>
<HEAD>Home Of Confederacy May Produce Nation's First Black Governor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When Lt. Gov. <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> was growing up in this former Confederate capital, he waited on tables at political dinners in the city's segregated clubs and hotels. Next year, <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> could land a job in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s Executive Mansion as the host of such dinners _ and the nation's first elected black governor. The 57-year-old <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>, whose grandparents were slaves, already is the highest-ranking black elected state official in the country. Although he has not yet announced his candidacy, he would be the favorite to win the Democratic nomination for governor next summer. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Rozell </PERSON>, a political scientist at <ORGANIZATION> Mary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Fredericksburg </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> has no strong opposition within the party and, among potential <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> opponents next November, only Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Trible </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> seems at this point to pose a major threat to <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>'s election. <PERSON> Trible </PERSON> is not seeking re-election to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> this year and has not said whether he will run for governor in 1989. <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>, the youngest of eight children, grew up in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>. He studied chemistry at <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, then enlisted in the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> and won a <ORGANIZATION> Bronze </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> for bravery in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. He went to law school at <ORGANIZATION> Howard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and opened a law practice here in 1959. Ten years later, he ran for a <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> vacancy when other local black leaders showed no interest. He became the first black to sit in the chamber since Reconstruction. In the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> was recognized as a skilled debater who quickly learned the rules of parliamentary procedure. Although his early image was that of a firebrand, he was never considered a militant. <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> was instrumental in the state's adoption of a holiday honoring slain civil rights leader <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr </PERSON>. He also lobbied unsuccessfully to change lyrics that blacks found offensive in the state song, `` Carry Me Back to <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> combined the role of maverick with that of an insider. In 1982, he single-handedly scuttled the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> ambition of fellow Democrat <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickett </PERSON> because <PERSON> Pickett </PERSON> dared to invoke the name of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s conservative leader, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> senator who left the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in 1970 to become an independent. The Byrd organization had dominated the state for 50 years. Two years later, in July 1984, <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> announced for the Democratic nomination for lieutenant governor. No serious opposition arose within the party during the next year, and he was nominated in June 1985. When <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> Democrats also nominated a woman for attorney general, there were predictions that the party was headed for disaster. But <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> played down his race and offered the image of a moderate native son in the tradition of then-Democratic Gov. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robb </PERSON>. A combination of <PERSON> Robb </PERSON>'s popularity, mistakes by <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> opponent and a tour of the state by <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> helped turn the predicted disaster into the second straight Democratic sweep of the state's top three offices. <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>'s performance in the administration of Gov. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baliles </PERSON>, who can not by law succeed himself, has been mostly low-key. However, <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> engaged in a well-publicized feud with <PERSON> Robb </PERSON> during his first year in office over how much credit <PERSON> Robb </PERSON> deserved for the 1985 victory. <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> also has criticized the administration's tax increases for road construction and made a show this year of pushing, over <PERSON> Baliles </PERSON>' objections, for a repeal of the sales tax on over-the-counter drugs. The lieutenant governor's major prospective competitor for the gubernatorial nomination stepped aside in March when Attorney General <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Sue </PERSON> <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> announced that she would seek another term in office. <PERSON> Baliles </PERSON> acknowledged this month in a college commencement address that <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> could make history next year by becoming the first black to lead the state's Democratic ticket. <PERSON> Baliles </PERSON>' office said no endorsement was intended, but observers said the comment amounted to a warning to potential rivals to stay out of <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>'s way. <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON> is expected to announce his political plans this summer. According to <PERSON> Rozell </PERSON>, <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>'s race may not prevent him from becoming governor of the Old Dominion because of changes over the past 20 years in the state's population and its attitudes. About 20 percent of Virginians are black, and the state also has a large, progressive-minded population in the northern corridor adjoining the nation's capital. No black has ever been elected governor in this country. In 1986 <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>' Democratic Mayor <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON>, a Republican county executive in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, both were nominated by their parties but lost the election. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> also had failed in his first race for governor in 1982. The only black to serve as a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> governor was <PERSON> Pinckney </PERSON> B.S. <PERSON> Pinchback </PERSON>, the lieutenant governor of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> who became acting governor for six weeks in 1872-1873 after the governor was impeached.
