<SECOND>PM-China-Arson,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Shopkeepers Sentenced to Death for Arson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four shopkeepers have been sentenced to death for arson and 49 <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> members disciplined for helping the merchants defraud insurance companies, an official report said today. The <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> said the four merchants, in two cities of the northeastern <LOCATION> Heilongjiang </LOCATION> province, set fire to their shops after taking out large insurance policies obtained through bribes to local officials. Five people were killed in one of the fires. The newspaper said two brothers, <PERSON> Lu </PERSON> <PERSON> Guangcai </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lu </PERSON> <PERSON> Guangde </PERSON>, falsified documents in <LOCATION> Qitaihe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> to insure their stationery store and restaurant for $ 224,000. Two days later, they set fire to a bag filled with gasoline, starting a blaze that killed five people and caused $ 27,000 in damage, the paper said. The report said <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Shuli </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Yichun </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> took out insurance worth $ 192,000 on a hardware store he managed after the store lost $ 72,000 over a 10-month period as a result of waste and mismanagement. And it said <PERSON> Yu </PERSON> <PERSON> Xibin </PERSON> rented a storehouse from <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> and insured it for $ 84,000, although it had only two counters and a sofa. The two set fire to the stores five times in May and June of last year, damaging six nearby stores and causing $ 24,000 in losses, the report said. The four provided local officials with high-quality cigarettes, wine, refrigerators, motorcycles and other goods to obtain contracts for the stores and the expensive insurance policies, it said. The report did not say if the death sentences had been carried out.
