<FIRST>r i PM-Summit-WarRemembered Bjt   05-31 0977</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Summit-War Remembered, Bjt,970</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Gorbachev and His Countrymen, War Is an Ever-Present Memory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VOLGOGRAD, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was 19 when he saw this city, and it was in ruins. It was then called <LOCATION> Stalingrad </LOCATION>, and it had been the scene of one of the bloodiest and most savage battles of the Second World War. It left an impression that was still vivid in <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s mind more than three and a half decades later. `` I went to study at <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, and I traveled through <LOCATION> Stalingrad </LOCATION>, which had been destroyed, through <LOCATION> Voronezh </LOCATION>, which had been destroyed,'' he told an interviewer in 1986. `` Nothing but ruins everywhere ... the whole country was in ruins.'' World War II divided <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s family and devastated much of his home region in southern <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>. By the time he saw <LOCATION> Stalingrad </LOCATION>, in 1950, war for the budding law student was no vague or distant concept, but a terrible reality that had hit close to home. Today, more than four decades after the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> struggled and defeated the invading <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> armies, the war continues to haunt the collective Soviet soul, and perhaps <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> himself. For Soviets, the conflict they call the `` Great Patriotic War'' is simultaneously a glorious chapter in their country's history, proof of the superiority of socialism, a convenient alibi when things go wrong, and a tragedy whose scars are felt even today. The wartime alliance between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> against the Axis is also cited by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, as proof that the superpowers need not be adversaries, but can be allies. `` When the time posed the question acutely, irrevocably and that question had to be answered, the Soviet and American peoples united,'' he told a group of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> schoolchildren who visited the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> earlier this month. `` The present time ... also makes vast demands, above all on our two great peoples.'' Virtually every Soviet family, including <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s, was touched by the four years of bitter fighting that ranged throughout the western <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and claimed the lives of 20 million Soviet soldiers and civilians. After the German armies drove across the Soviet border in June 1941, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s father, <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON>, a tractor driver, was called to the front, and served for four years. <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> was 10 years old when the fighting broke out. His native <LOCATION> Stavropol </LOCATION> region, 300 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Volgograd </LOCATION>, was overrun by the German 40th <ORGANIZATION> Panzer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> for seven months beginning in August 1942, just as the battle for <LOCATION> Stalingrad </LOCATION> was raging. From just one collective farm in the <LOCATION> Stavropol </LOCATION> region, in the village of <LOCATION> Beshpagir </LOCATION>, 417 young men and women went away to fight, and were killed in battle. The grip of World War II on the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> mind, and the use made of the memories by authorities, are nowhere more evident than in the city once called <LOCATION> Stalingrad </LOCATION>. In the titanic battle that raged here, as many as 1 million Soviets may have perished and 1.5 million Germans were killed, wounded or taken prisoner. In this city situated on a bend in the <LOCATION> Volga </LOCATION> river 600 miles south of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, 90 percent of the buildings in the industrial and residential center were devastated by artillery strikes, dive bombing raids and months of dogged house-to-house fighting. President <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> said the eight-month battle that ended in February 1943 with the surrender of encircled <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> units had marked `` the turning point in the war of the Allied Nations against the forces of aggression.'' At former Soviet battlefield sites like <LOCATION> Volgograd </LOCATION>, every day is Memorial Day. About 3 million Soviets visit a gigantic memorial complex here each year, many of them veterans returning to see the place where many of their comrades were killed. `` You feel a great weight in your soul,'' said <PERSON> Amazas </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Arutunyan </PERSON>, 63, an Armenian who served as a private in the 93rd Artillery Regiment until he was badly wounded. `` So many men fell in combat, some screaming, others just falling in silence, like leaves.'' The war medals worn by the wizened man thumped against his chest as he slowly climbed a half-mile to the top of <PERSON> Mamayev </PERSON> <PERSON> Kurgan </PERSON> hill, where a huge statue of <LOCATION> Mother </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>, slightly larger than the Statue of Liberty, brandishes a sword and calls on her children to smite the invader. In a cavernous hall dominated by an enormous white stone hand holding a blazing torch, 34 dipped red banners record the names of more than 7,000 Soviet men and women who died defending <LOCATION> Stalingrad </LOCATION>. A recording of solemn music plays over and over. The effect is overpowering. `` You can not come here without tears,'' said <PERSON> Nadezhda </PERSON> <PERSON> Denisova </PERSON>, 61, a Volgograder, who was 19 when the Battle of <LOCATION> Stalingrad </LOCATION> began. Her eyes welled. `` There were so many dead.'' A visitor's book is filled with poignant messages left by those who have come to the monument. One man wrote: `` Uncle Vasiya, I have found you at last. Your name is on one of the banners.'' The memorial complex on Mamayev Kurgan hill does not only stress the heroism and patriotism of the Soviets who fought here, but also the fact that they fought in the name of socialism and Soviet power. The name of <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, wartime generalissimo and Soviet dictator, was stripped from this city in 1961 when it was renamed <LOCATION> Volgograd </LOCATION>, but now the party as a whole is lauded as the organizer of World War II victory. <PERSON> Olga </PERSON> <PERSON> Sobelyova </PERSON> made that point as she slowly escorted a group of 24 orphans from the <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Sasovo </LOCATION> up the hill toward the giant statue of <LOCATION> Mother </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>. `` Children, you must n't think that it was just our armies who won here,'' said the 41-year-old guide from <LOCATION> Volgograd </LOCATION>. `` It was our entire country, our socialist system, and our <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>.''
