<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: These People Are Communists, But Some of Them Are
Acting Like ...</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 15th graf pvs, bgng, For the, to delete extraneous
words, capitalize Western and delete dollar sign before rubles;
subs 17th graf pvs, bgng, One new, to capitalize West; picks up
18th graf, Prices at xxx.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>By JONATHAN WOLMAN</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 You fly in on the state airline, <ORGANIZATION> Aeroflot </ORGANIZATION>, make your way through <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> passport and customs control and catch a ride downtown with a driver from the state travel monopoly, Intourist. GUM, the huge state-owned department store, is packed _ but not because there's a sale on. There are no sales, the prices are fixed by ... that's right, the state. That's life in the <ORGANIZATION> USSR </ORGANIZATION>. This is, after all, a communist state. But less so, it seems, every day that perestroika survives. If the buzzword of the 1980s in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> has been entrepreneurship, the key word here is cooperatives. Under the banner of perestroika, the <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> campaign to restructure the nation's stagnant economy, authorities last week acted on new laws that will encourage the expansion of cooperatives, economic units akin in many ways to the small business sector of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, except that all employees are co-owners and thus share in the profits. Profits? Profits have come to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and thus profit motive. Soviet Premier <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> said last week that 14,000 cooperatives were formed in the first 18 months they were permitted, with another 6,000 formed in the past three months. The cooperative system, he said optimistically, `` in a short time can solve the most severe problems of perestroika, the demand of the population for goods and services.'' Perestroika signals a dramatic evolution in the communist economy that has built a huge military might and an ominous bureaucracy, but little in the way of consumer services that people in the West have come to take for granted. Foreigners who live here send out to <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> for the finer things in life. When the train from <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION> arrives at <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION> here, it is loaded down with the fruits of the capitalist West, such as dishwashing detergent, modern ranges, fresh produce and Big Macs. Soviet citizens have neither the income, nor the hard currency nor the authority to order out. Instead, they shop in state-owned shops where variety is rare and the stock is either overpriced or depleted. As a rule, quality is nothing to brag about either. Perestroika is already in deep trouble, not the least because economic restructuring has brought the uncertainties of layoffs and future price increases, without any of the rewards of a true consumer economy. Change has been a long time coming to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The local press has come to dismiss the Brezhnev-to-Chernenko era, 1964-1985, as the `` period of stagnation.'' That said, the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> News _ a state-controlled paper that takes advantage of glasnost -LRB- the democratic companion of perestroika -RRB- to push the economic reforms on the front page _ has run reams about cooperatives. It's the hot topic in town, at least among the intellectuals and the foreign community. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, you ask a cabbie to take you to <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON>'s maybe. In <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, you ask for a cooperative and if you're lucky, you make your way to one of the new restaurants _ owned by its employees, who pocket the profit and thus have an incentive to create an attractive dinner or sew an attractive dress For the past six months, the way to the <LOCATION> Vavilova </LOCATION> market has become lined with wooden stalls and card tables, as vendors sell whatever they can make or get their hands on. One young lady is modeling a red-and-white striped apron and has a dozen on the table starting at 30 rubles -LRB- about $ 50 -RRB-. A fellow across the way has got his hands on some stylish Western blue jeans _ for sale, he says, at 130 rubles -LRB- $ 200, a month's pay for many Muscovites -RRB-. After dinner, walk through the Arbat shopping mall _ or even <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> _ and you see artists selling their portraits of St. Basil's Cathedral or the <ORGANIZATION> Lenin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mausoleum </ORGANIZATION> They implore. They barter. They discount. They would be capitalists or eccentrics at the <LOCATION> Pontevecchio </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Florence </LOCATION>, or in <LOCATION> Ghirardelli </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, but in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> they call themselves cooperatives. One new co-op restaurant in the northern section of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> displays the stickers of major credit cards familiar in the West and tries to make foreigners pay with plastic, an open violation of currency laws that forbid practically all private trade in hard currency. Prices at the restaurant double at midnight, and one unwary foursome found themselves stuck with a 98-ruble -LRB- $ 170 -RRB- bill for dinner, outrageous by Soviet standards but more and more common as co-ops learn the demand is there at practically any price in this supply-starved economy. This turn in the local economy is not without controversy or opposition, and many are the residents who recall Khrushchev-era reform efforts and expect this go-round to go-round, too. The current edition of the <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> has a piece whose front-page teaser says, `` Worker Demands A Revision of the Law on State Enterprise.'' The worker, identified as steelmaker <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Koptev </PERSON>, complained in an open letter to the Supreme Soviet that there are people putting roadblocks before the cooperative economy. Last week, the Supreme Soviet _ always your basic rubber stamp in this one-party society _ rebelled against a proposal to encourage cooperatives and insisted on a shift in the tax laws that would allow employees to keep a greater percentage of the profits. That's right, they were considering tax breaks. Tax breaks? It seems like curious business for Soviet communists.
</TEXT>
