<HEAD>Soviet Media Highlighting US Human Rights Abuses</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit-Dissidents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN FRIEDMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet media are highlighting cases the <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION> perceives as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> human rights abuses, in an apparent bid to counterbalance President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s meeting with dissidents and refuseniks. The official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> carried a critical commentary in advance of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s meeting Monday at <ORGANIZATION> Spaso </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, quoting Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Petrovsky </PERSON> as saying such an action `` is hardly aimed at improving understanding between the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper Pravda told its readers that although the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is a land of scientific and technological marvels, it is also a land of homelessness, hunger and repression of minorities. On a day when news of the summit meeting dominated the pages of the newspaper, it printed a photograph of blacks in shabby clothes lining up for a free Thanksgiving Day meal at <LOCATION> Lafayette </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, noting it was across the street from the White House. On the bottom of the same page, it printed a story about <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Peltier </PERSON>, an American Indian convicted of killing two <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents in 1975 at the Pine Ridge Indian Reservation in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Peltier </PERSON>'s case has been cited by Soviet officials as an example of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> human rights violations. Civil rights lawyer <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Kunstler </PERSON> said recently that the treatment of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should be raised as a human rights issue at the summit. Radio <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in one of its newscasts Monday mentioned a May 23 report by a panel of 40 prominent Americans that said minorities in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> were failing to make progress in efforts to achieve full participation `` in the life and prosperity of the nation.'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> also publicized a news conference Monday by four Americans who came to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to speak about alleged <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> human rights abuses involving minorities. The four `` wanted to make human rights part of the agenda'' at the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit and provide `` a balanced view,'' said one of the participants, lawyer <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, in an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> commentary said the Soviet government is `` seriously concerned'' about the human rights situation in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, especially `` discrimination against national minorities, persecution of people because of their political views and the passing of death sentences on minors.'' It also said that ideological disputes between the superpowers are inevitable, but `` one can not put up with the fact that the subject of human rights is exploited for purposes of whipping up hostility in inter-state relations, for impeding the processes of disarmament and detente.'' The Soviet Peace Committee was the setting for the news conference by the four American human rights activists, but <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> said they all paid their own way to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Parker </P