<HEAD>Priest Can't Get Mrs. Reagan Interested In `Just Say Nyet'
Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 J.W. <PERSON> Canty </PERSON>, an American Episcopal priest working against alcoholism and drug abuse in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, could not get <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> interested in his `` Just Say Nyet'' campaign, so he'll try her husband. <PERSON> Canty </PERSON>, 41, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet-U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alcoholism </ORGANIZATION> and Drug Addiction, wants to deliver a letter to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> asking them to issue a joint statement on the need to fight addictions. `` Alcoholism and drug addiction is an extremely serious problem in both of our countries,'' <PERSON> Canty </PERSON>'s letter says. `` May history remember these days as a summit for sobriety.'' One question <PERSON> Canty </PERSON> thinks <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> should address is why the cultures in the two countries seem to spawn alcoholism, a disease which robs both societies of their human resources. `` Why do these two countries share these drinking problems?'' <PERSON> Canty </PERSON> asked. In both countries, <PERSON> Canty </PERSON> thinks there is a certain `` macho'' image associated with drinking. <PERSON> Canty </PERSON> has spent two years working on and off in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> setting up the conference. Since 1986, <PERSON> Canty </PERSON> has established an Alcoholics Anonymous chapter in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, persuaded the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> city government to give him a building for a fellowship house, taken Soviet physicians on a tour of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to study alcoholism and arranged for Americans to visit the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. But the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> turned down <PERSON> Canty </PERSON>'s invitation to have Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> visit the site of his soon-to-be-opened fellowship house. Since 1981, Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has campaigned against drugs, adopting the slogan `` Just Say No.'' The fellowship house in downtown <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> will be a place for people to meet, read in the library and see videos. `` It will be a club to celebrate sobriety.'' he said. Undeterred by the reaction of Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s staff, <PERSON> Canty </PERSON> decided to solicit help from the superpower leaders in writing. <PERSON> Canty </PERSON> has already eaten dinner with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and received help from the Soviet leaders' aides who are committed to the country's anti-drinking policy Since he took office, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has raised the drinking age from 18 to 21, reduced the number of liquor stores and cut back on the production of alcohol. `` <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has challenged his people to do something but the follow-through has been a joke,'' <PERSON> Canty </PERSON> said. The Soviets say there are officially 4.3 million alcoholics in the country of about 284 million, but <PERSON> Canty </PERSON> thinks the figure is closer to about 10 million _ the same as in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> daily Pravda reported on Nov. 15, 1987 that there are more than 4.5 million registered alcoholics in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and that about 1 million of them need compulsory care. There has been no official estimate of the number of unregistered alcoholics. Though a drug problem exists in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, it is far less severe than in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Canty </PERSON> said. Drugs like cocaine and crack are not prevalent here, but <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> women often abuse tranquilizers and teen-agers sniff Benzene, he said. <PERSON> Canty </PERSON> acknowledges that people in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> find his efforts to reach global peace through sobriety somewhat off-beat. But he says he has been effective. `` I ` ve been told we are the first non-profit joint venture,'' he said. The low-budget conference is funded with money from foundations and gifts. The Soviet government has provided in-kind help such as donating a building and paying for its doctors to travel abroad. <PERSON> Canty </PERSON> receives no money from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government and declines to take a salary. Since 1986, <PERSON> Canty </PERSON> has made seven trips to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, and he has been here since January, staying at the National Hotel, a plush historic building overlooking the Kremlin. He operates out of his hotel room. The Russians seem perplexed by his `` grassroots, Scotch-tape operation,'' he said. `` The new party line is profit, and here we are saying, ` Do this for free,''' he said.
