<HEAD>Dutch Police Recover Stolen Van Gogh, Cezanne, Jongkind</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 7 grafs of background.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dutch police on Tuesday recovered three paintings, including works by <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Cezanne </PERSON>, less than two weeks after they were stolen from this city's Municipal Museum, police said. Three Dutchmen were arrested when they tried to sell the 19th-century paintings in an <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> hotel, said police spokesman <PERSON> Klaas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilting </PERSON>. The works, whose combined worth has been estimated at up to $ 52 million, were recovered undamaged, he told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. The art theft was the nation's biggest ever. Wilting refused to disclose any further details of the hotel transaction. He would also not say whether the three suspects were thought to include the burglars who smashed a museum window and stole the three works on May 20. Stolen were `` Carnations,'' a 1888 work by the Dutch painter <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>, `` Bottle with Apples,'' a still life painted in 1894 by the French master <PERSON> Cezanne </PERSON>; and `` The House of <PERSON> Maitre </PERSON> <PERSON> Billaud </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Nevers </LOCATION>,'' an 1874 painting by Dutch artist <PERSON> Johan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jongkind </PERSON>. Museum director <PERSON> Wim </PERSON> <PERSON> Beeren </PERSON> said at the time that the theft was thought to have been commissioned by a private art lover, since the paintings are virtually unsellable on the open market. <PERSON> Beeren </PERSON> said the record loss figure was in part due to the astronomical prices fetched recently by <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> paintings at auctions. Last November, an unidentified collector paid $ 53 million for <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>'s `` Irises'' at a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> auction. Eight months earlier, the impressionist master's `` Sunflowers'' was auctioned in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> for $ 29.8 million. However, experts of the <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s auction firm in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> said soon after the <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> burglary that the three paintings were worth only $ 11 million. The theft also sparked a public debate on the security of the Dutch artistic collections. Critics said too little was being done to protect the nation's art treasures from often highly professional thieves. The pre-dawn burglary on May 20 triggered only an electronic alarm at the museum, which has 3,200 artworks, mostly modern, but no night guard. It took 20 minutes for police to arrive on the scene of the burglary reportedly because the museum's private security company failed to immediately alert authorities.
