<HEAD>Weapons In Superpowers' Arsenals</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit-Arms Negotiations Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> are talking about strategic, or long-range, nuclear arms at their summit meeting. Here are the numbers of these weapons in the superpowers' arsenals as of the end of 1987 The sources are the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, a private research organization.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 INTERCONTINENTAL BALLISTIC MISSILES
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has three types, 450 Minuteman IIs, 520 Minuteman IIIs and 30 MX-Peacekeepers. Total warheads, 2,310. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has 1,400 of seven types, SS11, SS13, SS17, SS18, SS19, SS24, SS25. Total warheads, 6,846.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 SUBMARINE LAUNCHED BALLISTIC MISSILES
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has 256 Poseidons and 384 Tridents. Total warheads, about 5,630. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has six types, totalling 928 missiles with 3,232 warheads.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 WEAPONS CARRIED ON BOMBERS
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has three types of long-range nuclear bombers, 64 B-1Bs, 241 B-52s and 56 FB111s, totalling 361. These are capable of carrying about 5,070 warheads. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has four types of Bear bombers, totalling 155, capable of carrying about 1,170 warheads.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 TOTAL WARHEADS
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has about 13,000 warheads and the Soviets have about 11,200 warheads.
