<HEAD>Brubeck to Test the Jazz Waters with the Gorbachevs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> used to say jazz gave him gas, but no one seems to know what effect it has on <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. Tonight, pianist <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Brubeck </PERSON> plans to find out when he gives the general secretary and his wife <PERSON> Raisa </PERSON> a taste of `` Take Five'' and other American jazz classics. One thing is for sure, says <PERSON> Brubeck </PERSON>: the Reagans like jazz. They have chosen him to perform with his quintet at a state dinner for the <ORGANIZATION> Gorbachevs </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Spaso </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador's residence where the <ORGANIZATION> Reagans </ORGANIZATION> are staying during the summit. `` The Reagans really seem to appreciate American music in general. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> seems to know all the standards. You can see her mouthing the words,'' the gray-haired 67-year-old <PERSON> Brubeck </PERSON> said in an interview Monday. As for the president, a former <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> actor, <PERSON> Brubeck </PERSON> recalled that at a Feb. 21 performance at the White House for governors, `` He told me how much he loved the big bands and how much they were a part of American history.'' <PERSON> Brubeck </PERSON> is no stranger to the halls of power. He was the first jazz musician to play at the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and has entertained every president since <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. He met the <ORGANIZATION> Gorbachevs </ORGANIZATION> but did n't have a chance to talk to them or play for them at the previous summit state dinner at the White House last December. That dinner produced one of the most memorable moments of the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> summit _ the <ORGANIZATION> Gorbachevs </ORGANIZATION> singing along as the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> classical pianist <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Cliburn </PERSON> played the <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> standard `` <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Nights.'' Asked if he would follow in <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Cliburn </PERSON>'s footsteps with the dixieland jazz version of the song, renamed `` Midnight in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Brubeck </PERSON> said: `` We're prepared to play it if someone asks, but it's been done so many times. But in typical Brubeckian manner, if it's played, it'll be with a twist, in five-four rhythm. `` It can be done,'' he assured a doubting reporter. In honor of the occasion, <PERSON> Brubeck </PERSON> has dug up `` The Real Ambassadors,'' a song he wrote in 1958 for a musical that featured trumpeter <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON> running the world for a day. Although the <ORGANIZATION> Gorbachevs </ORGANIZATION> wo n't hear it because <PERSON> Brubeck </PERSON> plans to play only an instrumental version of the song, one line speaks of Armstrong using music to bring peace: `` The next time around, it's a session where we jam the blues <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> pounding both his shoes could n't have the final say if I was king for a day.'' <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON>, who pounded a shoe on a desk at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> in 1960, was no jazz lover. `` When I hear jazz, it's as if I had gas on the stomach,'' he said in December 1963. At the other extreme, <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Andropov </PERSON>, the former <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> chief who led the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> from November 1982 until his death in February 1984, was reputed to be a jazz fan. But although Mrs. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has showed up at several classical music concerts, little is known about the Kremlin couple's musical tastes. `` I keep asking everyone if <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> likes jazz, but no one seems to know,'' says <PERSON> Brubeck </PERSON>'s 36-year-old son <PERSON> Chris </PERSON>, who plays bass guitar and trombone in the group. `` They all say <PERSON> Andropov </PERSON> liked jazz and had a huge record collection.'' The elder <PERSON> Brubeck </PERSON>, who says he's played in most countries of the world, from `` the dance halls to all the joints'' during his 50-year career, believes jazz is a unique medium for espousing the American ideal of freedom. `` To play jazz, you have to have tremendous discipline and you are expected to use it in a free way. There's no art form that represents <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> better than jazz,'' he said. And to many jazz lovers, there is no single jazz standard better known than `` Take Five,'' <PERSON> Brubeck </PERSON>'s 1958 tune that was the first jazz single to go gold. The <LOCATION> Wilton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, resident gave Soviets who had heard him only on <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> shortwave broadcasts and records a chance to hear him in person in March and April of last year. He played 13 concerts in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tallinn </LOCATION>, the capital of <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>. The Soviet record label Melodiya plans to release a recording from last year's tour. It has already come out in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, under the title `` <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Night.''
