<HEAD>Study: Afghanistan Unable To Support Return Of Refugees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The war-ravaged Afghan countryside could not feed the country's millions of civil war refugees if they were to return immediately, a new study on the state of Afghan agriculture says. `` There was deliberate destruction of the agricultural system by the Russians, particularly along the highways,'' Professor <PERSON> Azam </PERSON> <PERSON> Gul </PERSON>, an Afghan citizen who directed the six-month study, told a news conference Monday. `` If the refugees returned en masse now, the land would not support them. That is the categorical conclusion of the survey,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> of the Britain-based Agrisystems, which trained the researchers and collated the data. <PERSON> Gul </PERSON> said the devastation had occurred mainly since Soviet troops intervened in 1979 to back the government in its war with anti-communist guerrillas. Villages were systematically bombed and trees destroyed around <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> bases, he said. The Soviets are in the process of withdrawing their more than 100,000 soldiers from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> under a U.N.-sponsored accord signed in April. The pullout is to be completed in February. The guerrillas, who launched their insurgency after a Communist coup in 1978, have said they will keep up the war until the government of President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> is defeated. <PERSON> Gul </PERSON> said agricultural production in 1986 fell to 45 percent of the level in 1978, the year before the Soviet intervention. Good rains last spring brought production up to 53 percent of its 1978 level, he said. The survey said it will take at least three years and $ 4 billion to restore cropland and livestock affected by 10 years of fighting in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Other officials have said such reconstruction could take 10 to 20 years. Farmers told the researchers that the Afghan army burned crops and shot cattle and sheep, sometimes from helicopter gunships. Hundreds of farmers said more than five animals a year in their herds were blown up by land mines, according to the report. Other farmers told researchers they sold livestock to pay for food or transportation out of the country. The Swedish-financed survey was conducted by a team of Afghan researchers who returned to their home areas to question 20,000 farmers. The results are designed to help aid projects and resettle more than 5 million refugees after Soviet troops leave <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. The 68-page report says food production improved in 1986 after the U.S.-supplied guerrillas received anti-aircraft missiles, `` providing a protective umbrella and allowing agricultural operations to continue during daytime.'' <PERSON> Gul </PERSON> said the survey was conducted only in guerrilla-held areas but included all 29 provinces. At least two of the 68 researchers escaped an ambush by government troops and another was captured and imprisoned. Six who were sent to remote provinces still have not reported back, <PERSON> Gul </PERSON> said. The researchers used questionnaires to collect details on war damage, crop yields, irrigation and use of fertilizers. The results showed that among farmers who fled <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in 1987, 42 percent reported their cattle, sheep or goats had been shot to death or killed by mines, and 65 percent of the farmers said their crops were burned. The report recommended a phased return of the refugees timed to the distribution of food aid and the rebuilding of the Afghan farms. Most of the refugees have fled to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. Reconstruction will be slow, said <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>. `` It's not only a question of money. It's a matter of time just for oxen to reproduce. You need three years to produce high quality seed,'' he said. Political obstacles also will delay rehabilitation, said <PERSON> Anders </PERSON> <PERSON> Fange </PERSON> of the Swedish <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> for <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, which paid for the $ 870,000 project. `` No matter what kind of government there will be, it will be very weak,'' said <PERSON> Fange </PERSON>, who is based in the refugee camps at <LOCATION> Peshawar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. Fragmentation of authority between the government and local guerrilla commanders will make the distribution of aid extremely complicated, he said.
