<FIRST>r w PM-IMF-Poverty     05-31 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-IMF-Poverty,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>IMF Reports Some of Its Programs Hurt the Poor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A report from the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> acknowledges that poor people have been hurt by policies it has pressed on Third World countries with the support of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In the past the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> has stressed that countries will be worse off if they delay the austerity policies such as devaluation of currencies and cuts in government spending usually required as a condition for <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> loans. The fund is owned by 151 governments, with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> holding the biggest block of votes. At the end of March, poor countries owed the fund $ 28.6 billion. Though founded in an effort to keep all currencies stable, in recent years the fund has spent its money almost entirely on helping about 80 poor countries keep up with their debt, much of it owed to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government and banks. `` Although many of the major policy instruments improved the position of the dominant poverty groups in the sample countries, other poverty groups were made worse off in the short run,'' the new report says. It chooses seven sample countries whose governments in recent years have adopted `` adjustment programs'' in order to get loans from the fund: <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>. The authors are five members of the fund staff led by an American, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Heller </PERSON>. The fund distributed the report this week from its headquarters in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The statement that introduces it comes from <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Camdessus </PERSON>, the fund's French managing director: `` Adjustment does not have to lower basic human standards. ... The more -LRB- that -RRB- adjustment efforts give proper weight to social realities _ especially the implications for the poorest _ the more successful they are likely to be.'' Large groups of poor people in the cities of <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> suffered from devaluations, it says. For the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, the report tells how spending on health and schools was cut, devaluation and restrictions on imports raised prices sharply while restrictions on the supply of money held down the number of jobs and the amount of wages. In the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>, basic items were subsidized by a high exchange rate for the peso. When the rate was lowered there was what the report calls `` major social unrest.'' More than 50 people died in the Dominican rioting of 1984. Sharp cuts in government spending may have hurt the poor in the long run as well as the short run in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>, according to the report. But it adds that the cuts might have been even greater if there had been no agreement between the governments and the fund. A rise in the tax on beer hit the people of <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>, `` though not perhaps in welfare terms,'' the report adds. On the positive side, the report says fund programs brought more credit for poor farmers in the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> and the removal of price controls helped cut rents in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION>. It also says that lowering the exchange rate helped increased the real earnings of poor people in the country who were raising crops for export in <LOCATION> Ghana </LOCATION>, and to a lesser extent in <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
