<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Reformers     05-31 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Reformers,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Conservatives Preventing Reformers From Attending Crucial
Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A leading reformer says he expects <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s liberalization drive to prevail at next month's crucial party conference despite conservatives' success at blocking some of its backers from attending. The Soviet leader's `` policies and programs are sufficiently strong to carry the conference,'' prominent political scientist <PERSON> Fyodor </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Burlatsky </PERSON> said Monday. He is among those who have been excluded. The Communist Party conference, the first since 1941, will lay out a a slate of policy decisions and proposals forming a blueprint for legislative changes. It will amount to passing judgment on <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s wide-ranging program of social and economic reforms known as `` perestroika.'' The selection of the 5,000 delegates to the June 28 conference has already turned into a showdown between backers of reform and those who seek to limit change _ often to preserve their privileges. <PERSON> Burlatsky </PERSON> said the conference will not name any new people to the 300-member, policy-making <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, in part to protect the committee headed by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> from changes viewed as harmful. `` If elections to the party conference have become so difficult, how do we know elections to the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> wo n't be tied up by some of these negative factors?'' he asked. <PERSON> Burlatsky </PERSON> fell with the fortunes of <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON>, the late former premier, but resurfaced to back <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s `` perestroika'' campaign He said the party's charter does not spell out procedures for selecting delegates to party conferences: `` We are learning democracy, finding a style as we go. It is certainly experimental.'' Sin