 Customs officers said today that they seized a huge cache of weapons bound for <LOCATION> Fiji </LOCATION> that could have started a small war in the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> nation, scene of two coups last year. The cache, including submachine guns, automatic rifles, hand grenades, mortars and anti-tank mines, arrived on a ship from <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hodeidah </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yemen </LOCATION> via <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, said Customs spokesman <PERSON> Alastair </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>. He said the shipment, discovered Monday in <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION>'s downtown Darling Harbor, was bound for <LOCATION> Lautoka </LOCATION>, in eastern <LOCATION> Fiji </LOCATION>, stronghold of deposed Prime Minister <PERSON> Timoci </PERSON> <PERSON> Bavadra </PERSON>. A <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said all the weapons were Soviet-made. `` It has nasty connotations,'' the official said. News reports said it was the biggest illegal haul of military equipment in Australian history. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said consigment papers listed the contents of a more than one-ton container as used machinery. `` Customs officers located the container, opened a number of sealed boxes, and instead of used machinery they found weapons,'' he told a news conference. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said an army demolition squad was brought in to remove the weapons and officials were doing an inventory. He said the shipment contained enough arms to have `` started a small war in <LOCATION> Fiji </LOCATION>.'' News reports said the consignment was intercepted after being loaded onto the french ship Capitaine <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>. The reports said the captain and his crew were being questioned but had not been arrested. The Foreign Ministry official said authorities in <LOCATION> Fiji </LOCATION>, which is about 2,000 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION>, had been informed of the seizure. Australian officials said they had no immediate indication of for whom the weapons were bound. In <LOCATION> Suva </LOCATION>, the Fijian capital, authorities expressed surprise at the seizure. <PERSON> Bavadra </PERSON>, who was ousted in a coup a year ago, was not available for comment. There has been no armed resistance by the majority Indian community to the coups, which <PERSON> Sitiveni </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabuka </PERSON> said he staged to protect the rights of ethnic Fijians, who comprise a 43 percent minority of the islands' 715,000 people. <PERSON> Bavadra </PERSON>'s Indian-dominated elected government was ousted on May 14, 1987, just one month after it came to power. <PERSON> Rabuka </PERSON> staged a second coup four months later, claiming the interim administration had not settled the issue of Fijian political dominance.
