<HEAD>Navy Hero, Wife, Buried Side-By-Side After 168 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A duel took <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wheeler </PERSON> <PERSON> Decatur </PERSON>'s heroic husband from her 168 years ago and fate kept their remains apart until now. Mrs. <PERSON> Decatur </PERSON>'s resting place was dedicated Monday in a church yard next to her husband's grave. Three students from an elementary school named for <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Decatur </PERSON> participated in a wreath-laying ceremony attended by about 100 people. <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION> was one of the young <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s heroes, lionized for his feats of daring against North African pirates and for a victory over a British warship during the War of 1812. After he was killed by a duelist's bullet on March 22, 1820, Mrs. <PERSON> Decatur </PERSON> lived 40 years without him. She then lay buried for 128 years in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, while he rested beside his parents at <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peter </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> here. Through the efforts of <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, the remains of Mrs. <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION> were removed from a university-owned cemetery, placed in a mahogany coffin and on May 19 reburied beside her husband, who had been buried under a 30-foot-tall granite column. Monday's ceremony coincided with the opening of a small <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION> exhibit at the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> Maritime Museum. <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION> was a native of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, the son of a Revolutionary War naval officer who was reared among the ships and shipbuilders of the city's late 18th-century waterfront. His most intrepid act was his Feb. 7, 1804, burning of the captured <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> frigate <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> in the harbor of <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION>, in modern-day <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>. Then 25 and disguised as a Maltese sailor, <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION> headed a raiding party that sailed into the heavily guarded harbor. They boarded, set fires and destroyed the frigate, which had been seized six months earlier by <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION> warships. Two years later, <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION> married <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wheeler </PERSON>, the daughter of the mayor of <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, and a noted belle of that town and <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>. She was said to be well educated, charming and pretty, but little else is known about her. They were childless and had been married for 14 years when <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION> died in the duel at age 41. <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION> was challenged by Capt. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Barron </PERSON>, whom <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION> had criticized after a ship <PERSON> Barron </PERSON> commanded was severely damaged by a British warship in 1807. The men stood about 8 yards apart in <LOCATION> Bladensburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, outside <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and fired a pair of ornate, long-barreled silver pistols. <PERSON> Barron </PERSON> was wounded in the hip but recovered. <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION> also was shot in the hip but the bullet traveled into his abdomen, and he died in his home that evening. Mrs. <PERSON> Decatur </PERSON> eventually settled near the campus of what is now <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and in 1837 gave the struggling <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> college $ 7,000. She died July 21, 1860, and was buried in a college graveyard that was forgotten until the ground was prepared for a new building in 1954, according to <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Meng </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION>'s vice president for administration. Her remains were moved to another college cemetery, where they stayed until she was reburied alonside her husband. `` All of the family, and there are quite a number of us, feel very good about this,'' said <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Decatur </PERSON> <PERSON> Garnett </PERSON>, 67, of <LOCATION> Kittery </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, a great-great-great-niece of <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION>. `` It was a romantic marriage. They were extremely romantic and very handsome.''
