<SECOND>PM-College Chemicals,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tons of Toxic and Explosive Chemicals Found At College</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tons of old chemicals that have turned toxic and potentially explosive were being removed from two buildings at <ORGANIZATION> Hunter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, where they were like `` a time bomb'' in science laboratories, officials said. The discovery of the chemicals, some up to 30 years old, forced the college to close <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> and the North Building on May 20, city <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> and school officials said Monday. Among the chemicals found were 25 canisters of explosive and highly reactive chemicals, including ether and picric acid, and 90 canisters of gases, some of which may be poisonous, said department spokeswoman <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Paylo </PERSON>. `` Picric acid, when it crystallizes, can be as explosive as dynamite in small quantities. It is feared throughout labs when it is old,'' Ms. <PERSON> Paylo </PERSON> said, calling the chemicals `` a time bomb.'' College officials learned about the chemicals' presence when the Fire Department discovered ether during an inspection May 11, college spokesman <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> said. Subsequent investigations revealed tons of expired chemicals in the buildings' science laboratories and storage rooms, Ms. <PERSON> Paylo </PERSON> said. So far, the spokeswoman said, 135 to 140 rooms have been searched for dangerous chemicals. A hazardous waste removal contractor planned to search all 500 rooms in both buildings today, she said. The police bomb squad and individual contractors have removed some of the dangerous substances, <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> and Ms. <PERSON> Paylo </PERSON> said. `` Some of the gas is still on the premises because it is difficult to find a contractor who will take it,'' she said. The college's policy had been `` to leave the regulation of materials to individual researchers in the labs,'' <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> said. The discovery of the chemicals `` shows that you ca n't leave this important safety-related area to individual people.'' Classes at the college ended for the summer two weeks ago.
