<HEAD>Red Cross Visits Prisoners in Cuba, U.N. Team to Study Human
Rights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> officials have arrived in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> to visit political prisoners and investigate prison conditions for the first time since <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> came to power 29 years ago, an organization spokesman said today. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauverd </PERSON>, spokesman for the Geneva-based <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>, said the team arrived in <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION> on Monday and hoped to begin visiting prisoners today. <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> is believed to be the third Soviet ally to permit the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> to visit prisoners. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> have already done so. The officials, including one doctor, hoped to visit every political prisoner in the Communist country during their stay, expected to last about one month, <PERSON> Bauverd </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. The delegation planned to visit all of <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s prisons, <PERSON> Bauverd </PERSON> said. Cuban authorities say there are 15. <PERSON> Bauverd </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> officials had agreed to the standard <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> procedures of visiting prisoners without witnesses and reserving the right to repeat visits in the future. He said the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> would not have an exact number of political prisoners in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> until after the visit. However, according to published reports, the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> government has said the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> would be allowed to visit 323 prisoners, described as `` counter-revolutionaries,'' or state-security prisoners. <PERSON> Bauverd </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> team would give a confidential report to the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> government after the visit and that its contents would not be made public under <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> policy. In a related development, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> announced today the composition of a team of delegates from its <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> who are to visit <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> later this year. The six-member team will be headed by the commission chairman, <PERSON> Alioune </PERSON> <PERSON> Sene </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION>. It includes delegates from <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Therese </PERSON> <PERSON> Gastaut </PERSON> told a weekly briefing. Ms. <PERSON> Gastaut </PERSON> said a date for their visit had not been set. <PERSON> Sene </PERSON> said in March that the visit would probably take place in July or August. The <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> decided at its annual meeting earlier this year to accept an invitation from <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>'s government to send a delegation to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> to investigate the human rights situation there and report back to next year's commission, which begins in February. The decision followed allegations by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and some international organizations, including <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, of human rights violations in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, such as torture and mistreatment of political prisoners. <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, which was an observer to the commission last year, was elected last week to sit on the 1989 commission.
