<HEAD>General Strike Protests Car Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Banks, schools, restaurants, gas stations and other businesses closed today in <LOCATION> Christian </LOCATION> east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Rmaeil </LOCATION> district to protest a car bombing that killed 20 people and wounded 78. Christian militia leaders blamed Monday's bombing on <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>. Police estimated the car that blew up in a crowded street in <LOCATION> Rmaeil </LOCATION> was packed with more than 200 pounds of TNT. Charred corpses wrapped in nylon bags were turned over to the victims' relatives at the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Georges </ORGANIZATION>' Greek Orthodox hospital for burial, police said. `` The victims will be buried separately because they come from different villages and areas,'' said a police spokesman, who can not be identified under standing regulations. He said the Lebanese Forces, the main Christian militia, had banned a mass funeral, adding: `` They do n't want a large crowd gathered at one place. It will be too tempting a target for another terrorist attack.'' The bomb exploded about 500 yards from an office of Christian President <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Phalange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. It shattered facades of eight apartment buildings, badly damaged 20 others and wrecked at least 30 cars. The bombing came four days after Syrian troops moved into the slums of south <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, ending three weeks of bloody clashes between Shiite Moslem militias in which nearly 300 people were killed and 1,000 wounded. The Lebanese Forces blamed <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> for the bombing. <PERSON> Karim </PERSON> <PERSON> Pakradouni </PERSON>, the militia's second in command, told a news conference: `` The day before yesterday -LRB- Saturday -RRB-, we received the propaganda message. Today -LRB- Monday -RRB- we received the bloody message.'' He referred to a statement Saturday by Information Minister <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Salman </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, who said presidential elections in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> would only be possible this summer if the Lebanese Forces withdrew from east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> deployed about 2,400 troops in the slums of south <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> on Friday and Saturday to end street battles between the Iranian-backed <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> and the Syrian-supported Amal militias. The police spokesman said about 40 percent of south <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s estimated 250,000 population who fled the fighting had returned to the devastated area since the Syrians moved in to enforce a cease-fire Government buses resumed services in the area today after bulldozers removed earth barricades used by the feuding factions for combat positions. In December 1985, <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON> torpedoed a Syrian-brokered peace treaty intended to end <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s civil war. <PERSON> Pakradouni </PERSON> maintained <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> wants the Lebanese Forces out of east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> to facilitate the election of a pro-Syrian president and to extend <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s control over the whole country Syrian forces now control Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, most of the capital's southern slums and <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s eastern and northern provinces. Most of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s Moslems, who have been at war with the Christians since 1975, are backed by <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>.
