<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Firefighters,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Refuses to Reinstate Affirmative Action Plan for DC Fire
Department</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to reinstate an affirmative action plan designed to increase the number of blacks in the <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that the plan _ calling for hiring at least six blacks for every 10 job openings _ unlawfully discriminates against whites. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> here ruled last year that the hiring quota violates federal law and the Constitution. Relying on recent <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rulings, the appeals court said the plan is not narrowly tailored to remedy past discrimination. The appeals court noted, for example, that since 1981 about 75 percent of those hired as city firefighters are black. The appeals court said, `` We are entirely at a loss to discern any act of hiring discrimination, much less any pattern or practice of discrimination'' that the quota seeks to remedy. `` There were no present-day impediments to black hiring. There were no relics from yesteryear to overcome.'' The appeals court added: `` To be valid, race-conscious remedies must in fact be remedial in nature. They are not to promote the Utopian goal, as some might see it, of a society in strict proportional racial balance in every employment setting, from brain surgery to basketball.'' The appeals court overturned a federal judge's decree approving the plan. The plan had been challenged by white firefighters and the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. City officials, in asking the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to reinstate the plan, said the appeals court ruling `` has crippled voluntary efforts by government employers to eliminate discriminatory barriers to employment and to cure the lingering effects of past unlawful discrimination.'' City officials said past discrimination was caused in part by a written test for firefighters used from 1969 to 1980 that was not related to the job and resulted in the hiring of whites for most openings. The city also said that the appeals court ruling has put the fire department in a bind, with some 100 firefighter vacancies now. City officials note that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, in an appropriations bill for the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, effectively has barred the fire department from hiring at random from among applicants. The city has hired a testing firm to develop an examination for hiring firefighters that would pass legal muster. But the exam is not expected to be completed until 1989. Also at stake in the case could be back pay and seniority for whites allegedly discriminated against by the affirmative action plan. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, urging the justices to reject the city's appeal, said the hiring quota is improper because there is no continuing segregation that must be addressed. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers, noting that some 38 percent of the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> firefighters are black, said that `` compares very favorably to the 29 percent black population in the greater <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> metropolitan area'' that includes parts of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. City officials said the relevant figure is the 64 percent working-age black population within the borders of the nation's capital Approximately 70 percent of the city government's workforce is black The city's appeal was supported by state officials in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>. Civil rights groups also urged the high court to reinstate the plan. They said the appeals court ruling, if adopted elsewhere, could have a devastating impact on voluntary efforts to fight racial discrimination. The case is <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 87-1150.
