<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Cable Access,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justices Say Cable Systems Need Not Carry All Local Signals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to resurrect federal rules that would force cable television operators to carry all local TV signals on their systems. The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that struck down as unconstitutional interim `` must-carry'' rules adopted by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>'s in 1986. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> here ruled last December that the rules, which were to be imposed for five years, violated free-speech rights. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stations </ORGANIZATION> and other broadcast organizations urged the justices to reinstate the rules, saying they fear cable operators may drop their over-the-air signals. The appeals court said the need for such rules `` is more speculative than real.'' Lawyers for the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> agreed, and urged the justices to reject the broadcasters' appeals. The appeals court in 1985 said the commission's original set of rules unlawfully `` coerce speech'' because they required cable operators to carry local broadcasters' signals irrespective of whether the operator considered them appropriate programming. After the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> refused in 1986 to disturb that ruling, the commission issued the interim rules _ forcing cable system operators to carry local signals for five years. The rules entitled a television station to insist that its signal be retransmitted on any cable system serving the station's local service area Cable systems, especially those with fewer channels, have opposed the rules because they often were forced to run the same programming on a number of stations if stations they are required to carry broadcast programs from the same television network. For example, a cable system in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> might be forced to carry the signal of the <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> affiliates in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, even though the programming is identical much of the time. In its December ruling, the appeals court said, `` The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s reimposition of must-carry rules on a five-year basis neither clearly furthers a substantial governmental interest nor is of brief enough duration to be considered narrowly tailored -LRB- in imposing -RRB- restrictions on speech. In one of the appeals acted on today, lawyers for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION> contended that the appeals court ruling could affect what television programming is available to tens of millions of American families. `` The lower court has made the television choices that are available to these homes largely dependent on the economic and political predilections of the only cable operator to provide cable service in any given neighborhood,'' the appeal argued. But <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers representing the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> told the court that during the 16 months between the appeals court's invalidation of the original must-carry rules and imposition of the interim rules `` cable operators generally did not stop carrying local broadcast signals. They said the appeals court's ruling `` gives the commission an opportunity to observe how broadcasters and the cable industry will operate without must-carry rules.'' `` If experience, as opposed to prediction, proves that must-carry rules are needed to advance public interests, the commission may build a record supporting new must-carry rules and defend those rules in the courts,'' the government lawyers said. The cases are <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>, 87-1487; <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> vs. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Century </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION>, 87-1506; <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> vs. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Century </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION>, 87-1510; and <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> vs. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Century </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION>, 87-1551.
