<HEAD>Court Lets Stand Award Won by California Firm Against Ohio Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today let stand a $ 5 million punitive-damages award won by a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> savings and loan association against an Ohio-based insurance company. The justices, over two dissenting votes, refused to hear arguments that the award, believed to be the largest of its kind ever upheld in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> courts, is unconstitutionally excessive. Justices <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> voted to hear arguments in the case, but four votes are needed to grant such review. Justice <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> did not participate in the case, for uannounced reasons. The high court earlier this month passed up deciding in a <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> case whether the ban on `` excessive fines'' imposed by the Constitution's Eighth Amendment applies to non-criminal cases. No court ever has applied the constitutional principle to non-criminal cases. A <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> jury awarded the <ORGANIZATION> Downey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> $ 123,769 in compensatory damages and $ 5 million in punitive damages after ruling that the <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Casualty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a wholly owned subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Casualty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, had denied insurance benefits in bad faith. <PERSON> Downey </PERSON> had been insured by <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Casualty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> against any dishonest or fraudulent act by the savings and loan's employees. <PERSON> Downey </PERSON> sought to collect on that insurance bond after one of its branch managers allegedly took part in a conspiracy to bilk <PERSON> Downey </PERSON> for hundreds of thousands of dollars. <PERSON> Downey </PERSON> claimed the scheme was partially successful, and resulted in a lawsuit against the savings and loan by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Funding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. In defending against that suit, <PERSON> Downey </PERSON> paid over $ 68,000 in legal fees and $ 55,000 in settlement costs. <PERSON> Downey </PERSON> in 1977 sought reimbursement of those expenses from <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Casualty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION>. The jury in 1984 found that <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Casualty </ORGANIZATION> acted in bad faith in denying <PERSON> Downey </PERSON>'s claim. The challenged $ 5 million award was upheld by a state appeals court, and the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> refused to hear <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Casualty </ORGANIZATION>'s appeal last May 29. In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Casualty </ORGANIZATION> argued that the punitive damages award, and the way it was awarded, `` are the inevitable, yet unpredictible, products of a system fundamentally out of control in which fines are becoming larger and are imposed more frequently.'' Some state legislatures, reacting to soaring insurance rated, in recent years have imposed ceilings on how much money can be recovered in personal-injury lawsuits. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> has abolished the awarding of punitive damages _ those aimed at punishing wrongful conduct that harms others and deterring such conduct in the future. Some commentators have decried soaring damages awards, charging that such a trend spurs more lawsuits, some of them frivolous, and that it overcompensates injured people. But other commentators contend that awarding punitive damages in addition to compensatory damages serves a vital public interest in deterring wrongful conduct. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Casualty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Downey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, 87-159.
