<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Judges,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Says New York Can Force Some Judges to Retire at Age 70</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s policy of forcing elected judges to retire at age 70 even though no such mandatory retirement is imposed on appointed judges was left intact by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today. The justices, four of whom are over 70, threw out an appeal by eight current or former <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> judges who say the retirement policy violates the Constitution's equal-protection guarantees. The court cited the lack of a `` substantial federal question'' in dismissing the appeal. The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> policy, reflected in the state's constitution and a state law, was upheld by the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last Sept. 3. The state's highest court ruled that the differing treatment of elected and appointed judges is valid. The state policy previously had applied to state and local judges in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, whether elected or appointed. A challenge to it was rejected by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1985. But the federal Age Discrimination in Employment Act, which originally protected only people between 45 and 70 and does not apply to elected officials, was amended in 1987 to bar employment discrimination against people over 70. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s policy subsequently was changed to exempt appointed judges, sparking the equal-protection challenge. `` That the state policy requiring retirement of judges is partially frustrated because the federal statute preempts it with respect to appointed judges does not render the policy irrational, and the state is free to pursue that policy to the extent doing so is consistent with federal law,'' the state court ruled. The state court used the least stringent standard of review for equal-protection challenges, in which courts decide whether a law or governmental policy that allows differing treatment is rational. In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for the five state judges argued that differing treatment based on age should spark the same stringent standard of review in courts as does differing treatment based on race. The state <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> rejected that argument. The eight judges who challenged the state policy are: Benjamin Glass, an elected state trial judge in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> forced to retire in 1981; <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Nolan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Grossman </PERSON>, elected <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judges; <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaiser </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Diamond </PERSON>, elected state <ORGANIZATION> Family </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judges in <LOCATION> Westchester </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nassau </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Counties </LOCATION>, respectively, who turned 70 last year; <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenstein </PERSON>, an elected <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Civil </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Court </LOCATION> judge who is 65; and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> and <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Buswell </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, whose judicial positions were not listed in submitted court documents. Federal judges, including <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> justices, are appointed for life. The four justices over 70 are <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> and <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>. The case is Diamond vs. <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>, 87-1361.
