<HEAD>Paintings by Van Gogh, Cezanne Recovered After Theft</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds price sought for stolen paintings, additional details.
No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police used an undercover agent posing as a prospective buyer today to recover three 19th-century masterpieces, including works by <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Cezanne </PERSON>. All three paintings taken from <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Municipal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Museum </LOCATION> last month were recovered undamaged, according to police spokesman <PERSON> Klaas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilting </PERSON>. The paintings, valued at up to $ 52 million, were seized when police raided a hotel and arrested a 36-year-old man who was selling them for $ 1.14 million, Wilting said. The money was confiscated during the raid at the Pullman Hotel, he said. The paintings are <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>'s 1888 `` Carnations,'' the 1894 still life `` Bottle with Apples'' by <PERSON> Cezanne </PERSON>, and a work by Dutch painter <PERSON> Johan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jongkind </PERSON>, `` The House of <PERSON> Maitre </PERSON> <PERSON> Billaud </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Nevers </LOCATION>,'' done in 1874. In their pre-dawn raid, police found the <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON> inside the hotel and the two other paintings in a car parked outside, Wilting said. The artworks were wrapped in blankets, Wilting said. Another police spokesman, <PERSON> Joost </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Wijngaarden </PERSON>, said an undercover police officer had posed as a buyer in the deal, but he refused to give details. Two other people, thought to be genuine prospective buyers, also were arrested, police said earlier. All suspects were being held pending charges. None were identified, in line with Dutch police practice. Police refused to say whether the undercover police officer was posing as a partner of the other two prospective buyers, or whether police had a role in raising the substantial amount of cash. There was no immediate word whether the alleged seller, who has a police burglary record, was involved in the May 20 break-in and theft at the Municipal Museum. In that incident, a ground-floor window was smashed to gain access to the museum. Last week, police received anonymous tips that buyers for the paintings were being solicited abroad, Wilting said. `` We got hard evidence of that early this week and that's when we decided to act,'' said Wilting. Museum director <PERSON> Wim </PERSON> <PERSON> Beeren </PERSON> said when the paintings were stolen that they are so famous it would be almost impossible to sell them on the open market. He speculated they were stolen on commission by a private collector. The three works were only insured for fire damage, but <PERSON> Beeren </PERSON> said at the time the huge loss estimate was due in part to the record prices paid for recently auctioned <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Goghs </PERSON>. Last November, a collector paid $ 53 million for <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>'s `` Irises'' at a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> auction and eight months earlier, the artist's `` Sunflowers'' was auctioned in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> for $ 29.8 million However, experts at the <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s auction firm in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> said soon after the <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> burglary that the three paintings together were worth just $ 11 million, with <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>'s estimated at about $ 2 million. Experts at the <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> museum put the value of the three at up to $ 52 million. The smashed window in the May burglary at the Municipal Museum triggered an electronic alarm at the museum's private security firm, which reportedly took 20 minutes to warn police and investigate the burglary. The museum holds about 3,200 mainly 19th and 20th-century artworks, but has had no night guard since 1975, when round-the-clock surveillance was abolished as an economy measure.
