SON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> at a White House state dinner. <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> was constructed on the northern marshland of the <LOCATION> Neva </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> by <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> the Great in the early 1700s, and has become a jewel of Russian historical and cultural treasures. But the city is also a monument to the strength of the Soviet spirit. The city was first named <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Petersburg </LOCATION> and then <LOCATION> Petrograd </LOCATION>, and it was the capital of the Russian Empire from 1703 to 1918. It was in the forefront of the Bolshevik Revolution in 1917, and its citizens heroically withstood a siege by <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> forces for 900 days during World War II. More than 650,000 people died of starvation during the blockade and more than 17,000 were killed in air raids and artillery shelling. Traditionally, newlyweds place flowers at the 150-foot high Monument to the Heroic Defenders, composed of an obelisk and sculptures with figures such as a mother mourning a dead child. The Hermitage's main building, <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON>'s Winter Palace, is itself a work of art. The baroque architecture was done by <PERSON> Bartolomeo </PERSON> <PERSON> Francesco </PERSON> <PERSON> Rastrelli </PERSON>, an Italian who designed several other <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> landmarks. In all, the complex has 1,050 rooms, 117 staircases, 1,886 doors and 1,945 windows, and many a visitor has become exhausted trying to see the 65,000 works occupying 400 rooms in the museum. Even though guides advise spreading a tour over several days, Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had less than an hour to spend at the palace. It proved to be a focal point of the revolution when the troops of Czar <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> fired on peaceful demonstrators, killing as many as 30 people in what came to be known as `` Bloody Sunday.'' The Winter Palace was a residence of the Imperial Family until the provisional government occupied it in 1917. The final item on Mrs. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> agenda was a trip by hydrofoil to <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> the Great's summer palace, built by the czar as a monument to <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>'s victories over the Swedes in his struggle to find an outlet to the <LOCATION> Baltic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. The interiors of the palace are a collection of sumptuous and ornately furnished reception areas, but the highlight is the collection of cascading fountains, canals and gardens.
