<HEAD>Ultra-light Plane Crashes, Killing One Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANKAKEE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Witnesses watched from the windows of a popular restaurant as an ultra-light plane crashed and burned, killing its pilot, a sheriff's investigator said today. The pilot had waved to restaurant patrons and was attempting to regain altitude `` when his left wing folded, the plane started spiraling and crashed'' several feet from the restaurant's parking lot Monday night, said Sheriff's Department investigator <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Erickson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blankestyn </PERSON>, a 34-year-old auto mechanic from <LOCATION> Kankakee </LOCATION>, was the pilot, <PERSON> Erickson </PERSON> said. `` At this time we do n't know if it was pilot error or structural failure,'' <PERSON> Erickson </PERSON> said. No one else was injured in the accident, the investigator said. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Kankakee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Sheriff's department were investigating, <PERSON> Erickson </PERSON> said. According to witnesses, the plane had taken off from the <LOCATION> Kankakee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> and was headed southwest when it crashed and caught fire, <PERSON> Erickson </PERSON> said.
