<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today unanimously struck down the way <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> promotes through tax credits the use of `` gasohol,'' a motor vehicle fuel less environmentally troublesome than gasoline. The court ruled that the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> tax-credit scheme, challenged by a gasohol producer in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, interferes unconstitutionally with interstate commerce. Gasohol is the common name for a blend of 90 percent gasoline and 10 percent ethanol, a 199-proof alcohol derived from corn and other sources. Use of gasohol reduces the toxic emissions from leaded motor vehicle fuels. To advance environmental goals, most states and the federal government have offered tax credits for the production and sale of gasohol. Prior to 1985, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> offered reductions in its fuel taxes for fuels containing ethanol, regardless or where the ethanol was produced. But since 1985, the state <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> has extended the credit to gasohol containing ethanol produced out of state only if it comes from a state in which Ohio-produced ethanol receives a tax credit. The credit for gasohol amounts to about 25 cents per gallon. The reciprocity feature of the state law was challenged by <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, which produces gasohol at its South Bend, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, plant and in 1985 was shipping about 25 percent of its output to <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> distributors. New Energy said it was priced out of the market in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> when it lost its tax incentives. The <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> struck down the tax-credit law as unconstitutional by a 4-3 vote in late 1986. But shortly thereafter two of the justices in the court's majority were voted out of office. In 1986, the newly constituted state court granted a rehearing, and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>'s tax credit for ethanol was upheld. Today, the nation's highest court said the <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> was wrong. <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> said the law `` imposes an economic disadvantage upon out-of-state sellers, and the promise to remove that if reciprocity is accepted no more justifies disparity of treatment than it would justify categorical exclusion.'' The case is <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Limbach </PERSON>, 87-654.
