<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to settle a multi-million dollar dispute between <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> over unclaimed dividend and interest payments on securities. The justices granted <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>'s request that it be allowed to sue <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> without the case first having been heard in some lower court. The court has such `` original'' authority in disputes between states. The conflict stems from the fact that 15 of the nation's largest stock brokerage firms are incorporated in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> but based in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Each year, the firms recover substantial amounts of money in dividend and interest payments for people who can not be located. All states have so-called `` escheat'' laws providing that such abandoned money goes into the state treasury after remaining unclaimed for a certain time. In <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, the waiting period is seven years. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, it is three years. <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>'s escheat law is binding on all corporations chartered in the state, but <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> considers brokerage firms with <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> trading addresses subject to its escheat law and has pursued unclaimed payments. <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Oberly </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> said <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> has been collecting such payments from Delaware-chartered brokerage firms since 1971. He said more than $ 50 million could be involved. <PERSON> Oberly </PERSON> told the j