<HEAD>Court Gives Federal Regulators Power to Oust Bank Executives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today gave federal regulators broad power to oust bank executives from their jobs temporarily when the executives are accused of serious crimes. In a 9-0 ruling, the court said the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> acted properly in suspending an <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> bank president. The justices upheld a law permitting the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> to suspend a bank executive accused of serious wrongdoing for up to 90 days while the agency decides the executive's appeal for reinstatement. Justice <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, writing for the court, said a bank executive's `` interest in continued employment is without doubt an important interest that ought not be interrupted without substantial justification.'' But <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said, a suspended officer also `` has an interest in seeing that a decision concerning his or her continued suspension is not made with excessive haste.'' The case stems from the indictment in 1986 of <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mallen </PERSON>, president of the now defunct <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kanawha </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, on charges he made false statements to the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Mallen </PERSON> was accused of concealing financial interests in other businesses and of concealing loans his banks made. His small agricultural bank in a town of 750 people had assets of $ 18 million. He was convicted in federal court last year and sentenced to three years in prison and fined $ 10,000. He was ordered to spend only 60 days in jail and the rest of the sentence was suspended. Prior to his criminal trial, the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> barred him from continuing as bank president and director, prohibited him from taking part in running the bank and said he could not vote his stock in the bank's holding company The <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> acted under a law empowering federal banking regulators to suspend executives charged with crimes involving dishonesty or breach of trust that are punishable by imprisonment for more than one year. The law gives the executive a right to appeal to the regulatory agency. But the statute allows the agency to take up to three months to resolve the appeal. Moreover, the law does not guarantee the banker a chance to present oral arguments in making the appeal. A federal judge ruled <PERSON> Mallen </PERSON>'s rights were violated by the suspension and by the ban on oral testimony to the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION>. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, on behalf of the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION>, appealed the ruling to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. The case is <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Mallen </PERSON>, 87-82.
