<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-NaturalGas     05-31 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Natural Gas,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justices Pave Way for Some Deregulation; Consumer Benefit Eyed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in a decision the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration says could save consumers an estimated $ 100 million a year, cleared the way today for price deregulation of some natural gas. The justices, 8-0, reversed an appeals court ruling that had placed a floor under the gas prices. The appeals court ruling was challenged by the administration, the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and natural gas distributors who buy from producers. The dispute was over interpretation of the Natural Gas Policy Act of 1978, a federal law that phases out regulation of natural gas prices and is designed to assure an adequate supply of gas for delivery across state lines. Prior to the law's enactment, there was a ceiling on the price of gas sold interstate but no such regulation for gas produced and sold within the same state. The two-tier system prompted producers to commit more of their supplies to the intrastate market, causing shortages in interstate supplies of natural gas. The 1978 law created a complicated system of phasing out price controls that divides gas into three categories _ old, new and difficult-to-produce gas. Generally, the price regulations applied more to old gas and lifted controls for new gas to encourage discoveries and production. Old gas is that produced from wells operating before the law was passed, and new gas is that from wells that began producing after the law's passage. The third category covers gas produced by particuarly high-cost methods, such as that obtained from between layers of more impervious rock. The gas supplies involved in the case decided today overlap the categories, qualifying for both regulated and deregulated treatment under the 1978 law. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> in 1985 eliminated controls for such `` dually qualified'' gas _ allowing the price to be determined by the free market. The commission said maintaining controls would lead to a regulated price higher than the free-market price _ an opposite effect from the one intended by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in enacting the 1978 law. But the 10th Circuit court, acting on appeals by gas producers, said the commission's deregulation rule violated the 1978 law. Writing for the high court today, Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said the appeals court wrongly overturned the commission's rule. He said the commission's interpretation of the 1978 law was correct. Justice <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> did not participate in the case for unannounced reasons. The case is <ORGANIZATION> FERC </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Martin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exploration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, 87-363.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
