<FIRST>r w AM-FarmScene     05-31 0743</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Scene,0764</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Fish Farm Can Be Large- or Small-Scale Operation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A sharpened consumer appetite for fish and seafood offers an opportunity for American farmers to reel in a share of a growing worldwide aquaculture industry, says a report by the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. Expanding world population and growing consumer demands have already forced some nations to harvest `` previously underutilized species'' of fish and seafood, and to develop alternative sources, the report said. `` Many commercial fisheries, which harvest from the wild, are approaching their maximum sustainable yield,'' it added. `` Thus aquaculture _ growing fish or other aquatic life in a controlled environment _ is expanding.'' Americans are also honing their appetites, last year consuming more fish and seafood per person than veal, lamb and mutton, roasting chicken or turkey. Beef, pork and broiler chicken, however, remain far in the lead as <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> favorites. In 1980, aquaculture accounted for 13 percent of the global production of aquatic foods and goods, up from 7 percent in 1970. Industry sources indicate that by the year 2010 aquaculture will provide 25 percent of the worldwide aquatic harvest. The report was included in the June issue of Agricultural Outlook magazine issued by the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. The article was written by economists <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Dicks </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON>. By 1981, total <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> fish consumption had grown 30 percent from 1970. About 47 percent was imported. `` Population growth accounts for only half the increase,'' the report added. `` Per capita <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consumption of fish and shellfish has grown, reaching a record 15.4 pounds -LRB- edible weight -RRB- in 1987. It is expected to expand another 50 percent by 2010.'' <PERSON> Dicks </PERSON> said in a telephone interview that the 1987 per capita consumption figure included only 0.5 pound of the estimated 3 to 5 pounds per capita of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aquaculture production. The half pound, he said, only included catfish and none of the other species, ranging from trout and salmon to oysters and shrimp. Despite the recent increases, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> per capita fish and seafood consumption is well behind <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, which averages 40 to 45 pounds per person, and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, which averages 130 to 140 pounds annually. Per capita consumption of veal last year by Americans averaged 1.5 pounds; lamb and mutton, 1.3; mature chicken, 2.5; and turkey, 15.2. Beef consumption was 75.5 pounds; pork, 58.8; and broiler chicken, 60.1. Those are retail weights as sold by grocery stores. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aquaculture industry _ fish farming _ has expanded greatly in recent years but still is led by catfish, produced primarily in the South. In 1986, for example, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aquaculture harvest was nearly 620 million pounds valued at more than $ 496 million. Of those amounts, catfish comprised 327 million pounds worth $ 229 million to growers, the report showed. Comparatively, in 1980 the total harvest was 203 million pounds valued at $ 192 million, with catfish comprising less than 77 million pounds at a value of $ 54 million. Catfish, crawfish, salmon and trout make up about 90 percent of the total <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aquaculture production. By 2010, according to industry estimates, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aquaculture production is expected to exceed 2 billion pounds, and that does n't count production from `` catch-out'' ponds and direct sales to consumers, the report said A study in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> showed that for every 10 million additional pounds of catfish produced, 220 new jobs are created in the industry, and 1,100 jobs are created in related industries. Most catfish are grown in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, while salmon output is mainly in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, crawfish in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, and trout in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>. Channel catfish east mostly soybean products and corn. To get a pound of catfish requires one pound of soybean meal, a half pound of corn meal, and a half pound of other nutrients. Nearly 55 percent of the usual diet of farm-grown salmon are also from the farm _ 17 percent whey, 16.5 percent wheat germ, 15 percent cottonseed meal, and 6 percent soybean oil. The report said aquaculture is suited to small as well as commercial farms and that a modest operation can provide significant income. `` Many agricultural institutions still regard aquaculture as a sideline,'' the report said. `` Even so, aquaculture has become a technical and highly capitalized commercial enterprise.'' One problem has been the `` limited information'' available to potential lenders, the report said. As a result, it added, many federal agencies have been reluctant to aid aquaculture producers financially.
</TEXT>
