<HEAD>U.S. Television News Broadcast In Central Moscow, Not Enough Music</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Muscovites responding to their first peek at <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> television news say they wish it had more music and less talk, but they still are wide-eyed over glimpses into the personal lives of government leaders and average Americans _ even when they do n't understand the language <ORGANIZATION> Cables </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> is being broadcast into central <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> during the summit under an agreement with the state broadcast agency <PERSON> Gostelradio </PERSON>. Those Muscovites lucky enough to own recent model television sets can pick it up on Channel 6. It also is available in the Rossiya Hotel overlooking Red Square, where many foreign journalists are staying. Maids and plainclothes <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> agents are often seen sitting together before television sets in halls, watching attentively and sometimes with the volumn off. For most, it marks the first time they have seen fast-paced, round-the-clock, up-close-and-personal American television. Television news imported from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is a far cry from the Soviet evening news show Vremya. The show has been jazzed up in recent months with new graphics and backdrops, but it is still dry and focuses on agricultural reports and Politburo announcements. A 46-year-old clerk who would only give her first name, <PERSON> Svetlana </PERSON>, said she was watching <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> news this week as often as she could. `` I enjoyed learning something about the private life of former President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>,'' she said, smiling shyly. `` I saw him on a fishing trip. For us, this is very unusual.'' `` I would like to see such things about General Secretary -LRB- <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> on Vremya. But for the moment, we have only rumors about his personal life,'' she said. <PERSON> Svetlana </PERSON> said she understood some English. But a lack of language comprehension has not stopped Soviets from tuning in to <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION>, sometimes for hours. `` We've watched at least two hours a night all this week, even though I do n't know any English,'' said <PERSON> Lyubov </PERSON> <PERSON> Ivanova </PERSON>, 50. `` I wish it had more music, but I'm still very interested. It is nice to see President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and now I would like to see one of his movies.'' Both <PERSON> Svetlana </PERSON> and Mrs. <PERSON> Ivanova </PERSON> said they were disappointed that the stories on American television, which last an average of two or three minutes, were so short. On Soviet television, an item like a <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> speech can take up the entire newscast, which is sometimes extended to two hours. <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION> producer <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Oxenberg </PERSON> said the network was broadcasting its program only in central <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and had received comments and telephone calls from Soviets which indicated it was widely watched. `` We know sometimes official Soviets are not happy about the way we do our reporting, but we think it is good for <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> that we were allowed to do this,'' she said. Moscow-born <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON>, 25, agreed. `` I think it is important to see even these small pieces of the lives of Americans,'' <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> said. `` We Soviets may be able to learn things that could help us,'' he said. `` For example, the Americans seem so relaxed and social compared with us. Maybe we can learn how to take it easy by watching them.'' <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> said he was disappointed to learn <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION> would go off the air here once President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> leaves <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on Thursday. `` It's too bad,'' he said `` I wish American TV could stay here and our show Vremya could go to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Television should have no borders.''
</TEXT>
