<HEAD>Bomb Explosion in Punjab Market Kills 6, Wounds 32</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A bomb hidden in a plastic bag exploded in the crowded vegetable market of a Hindu town in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state Tuesday, killing six people and wounding at least 32, police reported. They blamed Sikh extremists for planting the bomb in the market at <LOCATION> Dinanagar </LOCATION>, 50 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION>, the Sikh holy city. It went off at about 6:30 a.m. as people were beginning their morning shopping, said D.S. <PERSON> Khala </PERSON>, deputy police commissioner of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. He said most of the victims were Hindus. <LOCATION> Dinanagar </LOCATION> is in the <LOCATION> Gurdaspur </LOCATION> <LOCATION> district </LOCATION>, where seven bombs have killed at least 13 people this year. The bombings are blamed on extremists who have been fighting since 1982 for an independent Sikh nation in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, the only Indian state where the sect has a majority. On Monday, an explosion in a crowded market in <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> killed 23 people and wounded 44. Police initially said the cause appeared to be the accidental ignition of a propane gas cylinder. But the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Suresh </PERSON> <PERSON> Arora </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> district police chief, on Tuesday as saying it was a bomb, probably set off by remote control. Authorities blamed Sikh extremists for the <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> explosion. Two Hindu-dominated political parties sponsored a general protest strike Tuesday in <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> that closed many stores and offices. The bombing deaths and the killing of a Sikh man Tuesday in the <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> district raised to at least 1,230 the number of deaths blamed on <ORGANIZATION> Sikh </ORGANIZATION> radicals in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> so far this year, 200 more than the 1,030 in all of 1987. Most of the gunmen's targets are Hindus, but they also kill Sikh moderates. Police defused two bombs in a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> residential neighborhood Tuesday, and a bomb scare delayed the departure of a Paris-bound <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> jet for more than 16 hours, Indian news agencies reported. Press Trust of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> said the two bombs were found in a plastic bag in the <LOCATION> Kailash </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nagar </LOCATION> neighborhood and defused by the police bomb disposal squad. Air <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s Flight 123 to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> was delayed because an anonymous telephone caller said a bomb was aboard, but a search revealed no explosives, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> said. There was no claim of responsibility for either incident in the capital. Thousands of people have been killed since Sikh militants began their violent campaign for a homeland in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, a rich northwestern state that is <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s main agricultural region. <LOCATION> Sikhism </LOCATION> was founded 500 years ago as an alternative to <LOCATION> Hinduism </LOCATION> and Islam. Members of the sect, who make up only 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 800 million people, claim discrimination by the predominant Hindus.
