<HEAD>Teachers Begin Indefinite Strike; Classes Put off for 2Oth Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Schoolteachers began a strike for more pay Tuesday. It was the 20th time in the past three months that public schools have been closed because of teacher work stoppages. Unlike past strikes, this one was called for an indefinite period. It was the first indefinite work stoppage by civil servants in the public administration since <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> returned to democracy in 1977. The strike meant no classes for the nearly 6 million students in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s public elementary, secondary and technical schools. There is just one month left in the regular school year. The six unions representing <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s 272,000 public schoolteachers approved the indefinite strike Thursday. The government of Prime Minister <PERSON> Felipe </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> broke off negotiations after the strike was approved. Teachers are demanding pay parity with civil servants of similar qualifications and monthly pay increases of $ 223 by September 1990. Teachers at elementary schools earn an average of $ 929 a month. Teachers at secondary and technical schools earn about $ 1,090 a month. On May 4, five of the six teachers unions reached a tentative agreement with the <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> for a monthly pay increase of $ 178 by September 1990. The teachers branch of the Communist-oriented <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commissions </ORGANIZATION> union opposed the pact, and a referendum was held May 16. Of the teachers who voted, 75 percent rejected the pact. A government decree published last week forces teachers to guarantee students their required tests and final exams by June 30 or face suspension from their jobs for three to six years. The unions said teachers would comply. In announcing the breaking off of talks last week, government spokesman <PERSON> Santiago </PERSON> <PERSON> Varela </PERSON>, said `` this kind of strike is unjustified.'' `` It threatens the constitutionally guaranteed right of education for students and impedes further talks in search of a reasonable and just solution,'' <PERSON> Varela </PERSON> added. The National Confederation of Student Associations has criticized the teachers' indefinite strike, as has the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Confederation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parents </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Students </ORGANIZATION>.
