 As <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> moves closer to the Democratic presidential nomination, some <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> Democrats are pressing him to choose Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> as his running mate. Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>, for one, is heading a group of Floridians writing Graham-promoting letters to <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, as well as to uncommitted Democratic delegates and other party leaders. The group has distributed 500 `` <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> for V.P.'' buttons, and <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> said a formal committee will be put together as the Graham-backers expand. `` We're trying to create a national awareness that he is a viable possibility,'' said <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>, adding that the committee hopes to flood the national convention in July with <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> banners, signs and stickers. Another active <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> supporter is state <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> is not only a favorite son, he's a very strong candidate,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. `` He was a very popular Southern governor, and he would bring a Southern flavor to the ticket.'' Other <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> Democrats have mixed feelings about the effort by <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> supporters, one of the better organized efforts across the country to promote possible vice presidential candidates. Though many Democrats want <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, a Northeasterner, to pick a Southerner, <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> is n't the most frequently mentioned possibility from that region. `` Not to take anything away from <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> because <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> is very qualified, but my strong recommendation would be <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>,'' the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> senator, said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Tallahassee </LOCATION> attorney and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> supporter. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>'s press secretary, <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON>, said in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, `` Senator <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> is not seeking a spot on the ticket. He is not active in trying to make the phone ring. He has been flattered by the suggestion that it might ring.'' Meanwhile, state <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitehead </PERSON> feels pulled in two directions. `` The greatest thing for me as party chairman would be <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> on the ticket, because I believe that would ensure us of carrying <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Whitehead </PERSON> said. `` But the worst thing for me would be to have Gov. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> get to appoint a senator.'' If <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> were elected vice president, the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> governor would appoint someone to serve as senator until a special election in 1990.
