<HEAD>Waldheim to Visit Saudi Arabia; Other Middle East Trips Postponed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> will make an official visit to <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> this month, his chancellory announced Tuesday. The visit is scheduled for June 4-6. The statement said planned visits to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> have been postponed because of an upcoming Arab summit in <LOCATION> Algiers </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>, who was elected in June 1986, has not been invited or received by any Western heads of state because of allegations about his World War II past. He visited Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> in June 1987 and visited <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> a month later at the invitation of King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>, whom <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> welcomed in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> earlier this year. An international commission of historians in February questioned <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON>'s moral integrity as a second lieutenant serving in the German army in the <LOCATION> Balkans </LOCATION> during World War II. It said <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> knew of Nazi war crimes but did nothing to prevent them. It left open the question of whether he was guilty of atrocities. <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> has denied any wrongdoing.
