<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions taken Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. GRAY MARKET The court ruled the bulk of so-called `` gray market'' goods are legal, giving a green light to a big part of a multi-billion-dollar business that allows consumers to buy costly, brand-name imports at steep discounts. In another case, the court ruled that states sometimes may execute convicted murderers even if their constitutional right to a lawyer's help was violated. The case is K Mart vs. <ORGANIZATION> Cartier </ORGANIZATION>, 86-495. CAPITAL PUNISHMENT The court ruled that states sometimes may execute convicted murderers even if their constitutional right to a lawyer's help was violated. By a 5-3 vote, the justices said for the first time that errors in which a convicted murderer's constitutional right to a lawyer's help was violated may be deemed `` harmless. But the justices voted 8-0 in stating that such an error in the prosecution of convicted <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> murderer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Satterwhite </PERSON> was not harmless. The decision overturned his death sentence. The case is <PERSON> Satterwhite </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, 86-6284. FIREFIGHTERS The court refused to reinstate an affirmative action plan designed to increase the number of blacks in the <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that the plan _ calling for hiring at least six blacks for every l0 job openings _ unlawfully discriminates against whites. The case is <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 87-1150. CABLE ACCESS The court refused to resurrect federal rules that would force cable television operators to carry all local TV signals on their systems. The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that struck down as unconstitutional interim `` must-carry'' rules adopted by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>'s in 1986. The cases are <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>, 87-1487; <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> vs. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Century </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION>, 87-1506; <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> vs. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Century </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION>, 87-1510; and <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> vs. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Century </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION>, 87-1551. CHECK-KITING The court left intact a $ 25 million fine against a businessman for what prosecutors called the biggest check-kiting fraud in the history of American banking. The court, citing the lack of a `` substantial federal question'', rejected a challenge to a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> law that says those convicted in such schemes may be forced to pay fines equal to twice the amount gained through their criminal conduct. The case is <PERSON> Halloran </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, 87-1595. TAMPONS The court refused to reduce a jury award of more than $ 11.2 million won from a tampon manufacturer by the family of a <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> woman who died of toxic shock syndrome. The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by <ORGANIZATION> Playtex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> seeking to reduce the award. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Playtex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> O'Gilvie </PERSON>, 87-1021. NATURAL GAS The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, in a decision the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration says could save consumers an estimated $ 100 million a year, cleared the way today for price deregulation of some natural gas. The justices, in an 8-0 decision, reversed an appeals court ruling that had placed a floor under the gas prices. The case is <ORGANIZATION> FERC </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Martin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exploration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, 87-363. PUNITIVE DAMAGES The court let stand a $ 5 million punitive-damages award won by a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> savings and loan association against an Ohio-based insurance company. The justices, over two dissenting votes, refused to hear arguments that the award, believed to be the largest of its kind ever upheld in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> courts, is unconstitutionally excessive. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Casualty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Downey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associat