<TEXT>
 A small fishing boat with three people aboard hit a mine and exploded in the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oman </LOCATION> on Tuesday, killing one fisherman and injuring two, <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> officials said. The official <ORGANIZATION> Emirates </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> quoted an <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> statement as saying the incident occurred off <LOCATION> Dednah </LOCATION>, 20 miles south of the entrance to the Strait of <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION>. The waters are just north of a major anchorage off <PERSON> Khor </PERSON> <PERSON> Fakkan </PERSON> that is used by tankers and other commercial vessels going to and from the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. The anchorage is the staging area for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Navy-escorted convoys of American-flagged Kuwaiti tankers bound for <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>. There was no word on whether the mine was floating free or tethered to the floor of the gulf. The area was plagued by a spate of mines last fall, and at least two vessels were hit. One, a small offshore supply boat, sank, and six crewmen died. The incidents, which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other officials blamed on <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, prompted <ORGANIZATION> UAE </ORGANIZATION> authorities to close the anchorage temporarily and were a factor in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> deciding to dispatch mine sweepers to the gulf region. Some of those craft eventually cleared the area, and no mines had been reported in the Gulf of <LOCATION> Oman </LOCATION> for several months prior to Tuesday's incident. The ministry said all of the victims Tuesday were Indians. The two survivors were rescued by another fishing boat and