would have to divide his time during the summit between the affairs of state and the pressures of an approaching party conference that will pass judgment on `` perestroika,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reform program. The conference could prove explosive, as some of the 5,000 delegates are believed to share <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> ideology chief <PERSON> Yegor </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON>'s view that changes are being introduced too quickly. Hosting the <ORGANIZATION> Reagans </ORGANIZATION> at broadly publicized events like Monday night's state dinner and showing them around a spruced-up Soviet capital has apparently impressed the populace and strenthened their pride in their nation. The 57-year-old <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has been more accessible to Western reporters than <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, and the Soviet assessment of how the summit is progressing trickles out through a battery of Soviet briefings for the thousands of reporters covering <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s visit. The usually bureaucratic Soviet business world has taken a cue from the leader, showing unusual attentiveness to the needs of the press and officials. The <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency published the state dinner menu in English and has distributed unusually detailed historical reports on summit venues like <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON>'s Hall and <ORGANIZATION> Spaso </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. Managers of the International Hotel housing the summit press center have made rounds of some offices to ensure that the air-conditioning works and that waste baskets are emptied. As part of the public relations drive, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> planned to give a press conference at the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> press center on Wednesday afternoon, the first-ever event here that approximates a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presidential press conference. He has met with reporters during his three previous summits with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Reykjavik </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, and during visits to other major countries. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> bristled at a question about Soviet political prisoners during his first full news conference in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, but has since shown himself to be adept at handling the range of queries thrown out to him by Western reporters. His first session in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> will give him a chance to set out his views of how the summit turned out, and to portray himself as a victor on the foreign affairs front as he heads toward the domestic debate of the party conference.
