 <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> had fired <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>. At the time, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> accused <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> of using immature words and of radical actions and said he `` placed his personal ambitions above the interests of the party.'' Removed from the Politburo, he was named to the Cabinet-level position of deputy head of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Construction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. He lost his job on the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the country's nominal legislature, on May 4 As <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> party boss, <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> stood out for his brusque, aggressive manner and populist style. He was popular among Muscovites for criticizing consumer shortages and sometimes striding into stores to take his complaints straight to shopkeepers. Rumors circulated in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in mid-April that <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> had a bitter face-off, with <PERSON> Ligachev </PERSON> reportedly backing a newspaper article defending the late dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> supposedly counterattacking through another article pushing radical reforms. The two have made several public appearances together since then, with no obvious sign of disagreements.
