<HEAD>Some Butterflies Take Wing, Others Don't</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> enshrined the tiger swallowtail and <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> embraced the allosaurus, but no such warm welcome awaited the banana slug in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> or the monarch butterfly in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. The fate of these and other creatures was debated in legislatures across the nation this year, part of the time-honored custom of naming official state symbols for everything from fish to fossils, from mollusks to muffins. Critics say the practice wastes time and holds lawmakers up to ridicule, but defenders say it can help get young people involved in the political process, boost tourism, and provide some beneficial comic relief. `` It gets so tense in there sometimes. It's just too much,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Vanderlinde </PERSON> in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, where this year's <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> designated the triceratops, a plant-eating dinosaur, as the state fossil and <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> gold as the state jewelry `` This livens it up, and then people will relax and get back to work,'' she said. After the gold measure was passed by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> in January, lawmakers adopted a second resolution naming Vanderlinde the state's official jewel because she takes gold shots for arthritis. <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> adopted a fossil this year, the <ORGANIZATION> Hagerman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Horse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fossil </ORGANIZATION>, a 3 -LCB- - million-year-old relic found in southern <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Magic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> State and local officials are trying to turn the fossil beds south of Interstate 84 into a tourist attraction to boost the economy. The <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted in April to name the Key lime pie the official state pie, inspired by a legislative report that recommended the honor as `` an excellent way to promote a genuine <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> product, since the pie can only be properly made with Key limes from <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>.'' However, the measure ran into trouble in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, where Rules Chairman <PERSON> Dempsey </PERSON> <PERSON> Barron </PERSON> favors sweet potato pie more common to the Panhandle. On Thursday, the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> nearly squashed a measure to name the banana slug the official mollusk, but narrowly decided to allow the proposal to be reconsidered in the future. `` These things are replusive, I mean look at them ... The joke has to stop here,'' said Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Doolittle </PERSON>, as banana slugs oozed around inside a glass terrarium on a cart parked on the floor of the upper house. In some other actions so far this year, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> designated the tiger swallowtail the state butterfly, but the <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> refused to act on a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> measure naming the monarch butterfly the state insect. <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> made the allosaurus the state fossil, and <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> approved making the nene, a native goose, the state bird, and the Hibiscus the state flower. Last month in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee named a long-extinct aquatic creature _ phacops rana _ the state fossil after 100 Bucks County schoolchildren trooped into the committee room and performed skits and gave speeches supporting the appellation. At one point, the committee chairman, Rep. <PERSON> Camille </PERSON> <PERSON> George </PERSON>, donned a scarf and sunglasses and held an umbrella to show the children how fossils are formed over millions of years. `` There's certainly some time consumed in this, but if you're involving a bunch of youngsters in the process ... maybe there's nothing wrong with it,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> MacNett </PERSON>, chief counsel for <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> `` I guess it depends on how long it takes and when on the legislative agenda it occurs.'' That attitude was not encouraged this year in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, where <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mannweiler </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> President Pro Tem <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Garton </PERSON> warned lawmakers not to introduce frivolous bills for the biennial short session. `` It creates the wrong image for the Legislature,'' said <PERSON> Garton </PERSON>. `` It's a frivolous image. It creates the image that that's all we do, and it detracts from the serious business.'' <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Knapp </PERSON>, editor with the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governments </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, defended the practice of naming symbols. `` It's not something that takes up a great deal of attention or time,'' she said. `` I do n't think anybody expects every minute to be taken up with something serious. Maybe it's more harmless than raising taxes.''
