<HEAD>Sales of New Homes at Year-High Level</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New-home sales climbed 4 percent in April to the highest level in a year, the government said Tuesday, but analysts said rising interest rates would likely dampen sales this summer. New single-family homes sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 679,000 last month, the fastest pace since new homes sold at a rate of 728,000 in April 1987, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> departments said in a joint report. It was the third consecutive increase, coming atop a 1.2 percent rise in March and an 11.4 percent jump in February. `` Overall, it's a very nice report. No question about it,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Seiders </PERSON>, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Builders </ORGANIZATION>. A survey of home builders showed sales remained strong in early May, he said. `` But clearly our concern is what's been going on with interest rates,'' <PERSON> Seiders </PERSON> said. `` ... If rates move much higher, certainly sales are going to be coming down. Our forecast is for sales activity to peak in the second quarter.'' Rates on 30-year, fixed-rate conventional mortgages have been climbing steadily since late March, averaging 10.58 percent last week, up from the low this year of 9.84 percent, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Lasko </PERSON>, executive vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, said sales could be helped in May by purchasers hoping to beat out further increases `` But by June, the bloom will be off the rose and we're going see sales trailing off,'' he said. However, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Christian </PERSON>, chief economist of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutions </ORGANIZATION>, said higher rates, rather than chasing buyers from the market, may simply cause them to switch to adjustable rate mortgages. `` We've proved over and over again that adjustable rate mortgages provide a reasonable alternative to fixed rates. Even though both rates are moving up, you still have adjustables in what has to be considered very affordable ranges,'' he said. More worrisome, <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> said, is the increase in new home prices. The median, or midpoint, price of a new home was $ 110,500 in April, up 3.3 percent from March and 14.5 percent from a year ago. The average price of a new home was $ 137,000, up 4.2 percent from March and 16 percent over the past year. The recent increases in sales followed declines in the three previous months: 1.2 percent in January, 6.2 percent in December and 4.3 percent in November. Economists attributed them to buyers' uncertainty following the October stock market crash Sales for the first four months of this year are 9.3 percent below the same period of 1987, when mortgage interest rates hit nine-year lows. There were 671,000 new homes sold in 1987 and 750,000 sold in 1986, a record. Analysts are predicting sales in the 620,000-650 ,000 range this year Sales increased in all regions of the country in April. They were up 5.9 percent in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, 5.5 percent in the West, 2.9 percent in the South and 2.8 percent in the Northeast. In a report last week, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION> said sales of existing homes increased 4.5 percent in April after increases of 2.5 percent in both March and February.
</TEXT>
