<SECOND>AM-India-Heat Wave,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Death Toll at 280 in Record Heat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 280 people have died of sunstroke and other heat-related illnesses in a heat wave in northern <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, news agencies reported Tuesday. <LOCATION> Rajasthan </LOCATION> state was the area hit hardest. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> said 205 deaths were reported there in the past four days. Temperatures in some parts of the state hit a record 120 degrees Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> UNI </ORGANIZATION> said. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>, at least 25 people have died, according to reports from two major hospitals, the <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> said. The temperature in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> was 113 degrees on Tuesday. Water shortages and intermittent power cuts were reported in many areas. The death tolls reported by the news agencies included 18 in <LOCATION> Maharashtra </LOCATION> state, five in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, 11 in <LOCATION> Haryana </LOCATION> and 18 in <LOCATION> Uttar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pradesh </LOCATION>. Dust storms were forecast for <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Haryana </LOCATION> and neighboring areas. High temperatures often precede the nation's annual monsoon rains, critical for its agricultural economy. The rains are expected to begin in southern states early in June. They usually do not reach northern areas until July.
