<HEAD>Elsie Frum Remembers 1889 Disaster as `A Roar'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHNSTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Elsie </PERSON> <PERSON> Frum </PERSON> remembers running uphill from the Johnstown Flood of 1889, which swept everything in its path, killing 2,200 people in one of the nation's worst natural disasters. `` It was just like a roar. There were millions of gallons of water, you know,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Frum </PERSON>, 105, said Tuesday. `` It came just like a tidal wave and then it was over. Everything was washed away. We ran. If we did n't run, I would n't be here today.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Frum </PERSON> was 6 when the South Fork Dam burst and a 40-foot wall of water and debris slammed into this western <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> steel and railroad city 12 miles downstream. She and <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Shomo </PERSON>, 99, of <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, are the two remaining survivors of the May 31, 1889, disaster. They were to be guests of honor at the annual Flood Survivors' Banquet on Tuesday night. The dam held back <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Conemaugh </LOCATION> and was owned by the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fork </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hunting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, a summer playground for wealthy industrialists led by <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Carnegie </PERSON> and <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Clay </PERSON> <PERSON> Frick </PERSON>. After several days of rain, the poorly maintained dam was breached and finally burst, unleashing a torrent of water that cleared the <LOCATION> Conemaugh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> valley of houses, bridges and trains before it hit <LOCATION> Johnstown </LOCATION>. Pushing ahead uprooted trees, splintered beams, dead and dying people and farm animals, and miles of wire from a destroyed steel mill, the watery mass crashed into a <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> Railroad bridge just below <LOCATION> Johnstown </LOCATION>, where it piled up to form a temporary second dam that soon caught fire. Many bodies never were found. When she was a child, Mrs. <PERSON> Frum </PERSON>'s family lived in nearby <LOCATION> Conemaugh </LOCATION>. As the water approached, her father grabbed his wife and three daughters and started them running up a hill. The floodwater passed below. `` It happened and then it was over,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Frum </PERSON> recalled. `` After that, it was calm like nothing happened.'' <PERSON> Shomo </PERSON>, only 100 days old when the dam burst, lived about 20 miles downriver from <LOCATION> Johnstown </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Lockport </LOCATION>. He said the high water did not reach his house. Mrs. <PERSON> Frum </PERSON> survived another flood in 1936, stranded on the second floor of her <LOCATION> Johnstown </LOCATION> house. By the area's third flood disaster, in 1977, Mrs. <PERSON> Frum </PERSON> was living high and dry on a mountain in nearby Southmont.
