<SECOND>AM-Endangered Turtles,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Program Turns Out Too Many Male Sea Turtles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A program used in some areas to hatch endangered sea turtles is turning out too many males and must be changed, naturalists say. From May to November, loggerhead and green sea turtles lay eggs on the beach and abandon them. Eggs buried in cooler sand hatch as males and in warmer as females, said <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Huff </PERSON>, who heads the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> turtle protection program. But some of those nests are dug up by scientists and hatched in incubators to gurarantee a higher survival rate. Until recently, eggs gathered up in the <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lloyd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Recreation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION> here and in some other locations around <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> have been incubated in styrofoam chests. Young turtles do not show their gender externally, however, and scientists were unsure how many hatchlings were male. But a study of 1986 hatchlings which involved a painstaking surgical procedure has confirmed what some had suspected _ most of the turtles from the chests are male. To solve the problem, the naturalists are switching to burial of the turtles in beach sand, but with a cage surrounding them to ward off predators, as some other <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> hatcheries do. The cages are placed near the shore to make the hatchlings' run from their nest to the sea as short as possible. `` We do n't know all the implications, and are just being conservative and encouraging people to use beach hatcheries whenever possible,'' said <PERSON> Huff </PERSON>. Incubating the eggs in boxes will now be the choice of last resort, he said. The unbalanced sex ratio is not considered serious yet because only about 10 percent of the turtle nests are dug up and incubated artificially, he said. `` We take so few compared to the worldwide population, it's unlikely we'd ever affect the wild population,'' he said But the aim of the turtle program is to simulate nature as nearly as possible, he added.
