<TEXT>
 Critics are praising the adventurous spirit of this year's <ORGANIZATION> Spoleto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Festival </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION> of the performing arts, even if some productions have n't emerged unscathed from reviewers' pens. The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> Spoleto </LOCATION> `` has often been daring, but this year seems to be more so than usual.'' Everywhere at this year's festival `` there is something beguiling and new _ or so ancient it's just as challenging,'' said <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Today </ORGANIZATION>. The main opera at the festival which continues through Sunday is <PERSON> Dvorak </PERSON>'s `` Rusalka,'' a work which is rarely performed in this country. <LOCATION> Spoleto </LOCATION> also features the seldom-performed `` Montezuma'' by <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Graun </PERSON> and saw the premiere of a controversial dancer-theater piece by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> choreographer <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON>. The Post called the <LOCATION> Spoleto </LOCATION> production of `` Rusalka'' `` one of the most effective in the festival's 12-year American history.'' But The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> said the staging and special effects are the real highlights of the opera based on a Czechoslovakian fairy tale about a water sprite. `` Though the singers involved were mostly good second-and third-level professionals, the principal strengths of this staging, at least for two of the three acts, were visual,'' the Times reviewer said. `` Striking stage pictures came and went, compensating to an extent for a lack of vocal excitement.'' The State said the production `` is not to be missed by opera-lovers. <LOCATION> Spoleto </LOCATION>'s staging may be the only opportunity to see this sadly neglected opera in a lifetime,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> newspaper said. `` Montezuma,'' which tells of the Spanish destruction of the Aztec civilization in the 1500s, is performed even less frequently and has n't fared well with the <LOCATION> Spoleto </LOCATION> critics. The News and Courier of <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> called the cast `` spotty'' and suggested `` it is not an opera for all to enjoy.'' `` It did manage to give a taste of ` Montezuma' however, albeit with a merely serviceable abstract decor and conducting and singing that was mostly insensitive and inauthentic to the period, `` wrote The Wall Street Journal. USA Today called Ms. <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON>'s `` Miracolo D'Amore'' `` a delicious little scandal'' for the festival. The work, which conjures sometimes violent images of love, features some nudity and has caused a stir among <LOCATION> Spoleto </LOCATION> audiences. A number of people have walked out of the historic Dock Street Theater before the end of the performances. `` Viewed with a calm, receptive eye, ` Miracolo d'Amore' is a profoundly impressive, tight, lucid piece,'' said <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Today </ORGANIZATION>. `` The naked women evoke <PERSON> Botticelli </PERSON>, and the lyrics and minuscule amount of text are all in Italian, making for a rather remote experience if you do n't get the references,'' The Wall Street Journal said. `` It's either a dream or a bore, depending on whom you ask.'' One reviewer for The News and <PERSON> Courier </PERSON> called the work `` unsettling'' and described it as `` a hateful piece, bitter and malevolent. As a theater work it's visually beautiful. But then, so is a coral snake.'' Another reviewer for the paper suggested `` this is clearly a work of _ dare I say it? _ feminist revenge.'' The reviewer added Ms. <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON> `` has wrought a theatrical experience that will affect different people in radically, one might say almost violently, different ways.'' Composer <PERSON> Gian </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlo </PERSON> <PERSON> Menotti </PERSON> founded the Festival of the Two Worlds in <LOCATION> Spoleto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, in 1958, and later founded the <ORGANIZATION> Spoleto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Festival </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Spoleto </LOCATION> Festival of the Three Worlds in <LOCATION> Melbourne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. He still heads all of them.
