<HEAD>Fireworks Producer Says He Can Account for Shells</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The director of a fireworks production at which a shell exploded, injuring 27 people, said Tuesday he can account for all the shells that were fired and the exploding one may have come from somewhere else. `` We have n't been able to substantiate that,'' said Lt. <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyers </PERSON>, who heads the arson abatement investigating the Sunday evening accident during the annual Dayton River Festival. Thirteen people remained hospitalized, all but one in good or fair condtion. <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, 34, of <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, was in serious condition. <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leibert </PERSON>, producer for <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fireworks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ensemble </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION>, believes the shell that exploded came from somewhere other than the launch area, about 600 feet from the bank of the <LOCATION> Stillwater </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> where it hit. The shells, which normally travel 350 to 500 feet in the air before exploding, are fired off electrically. All 1,500, ranging from 3 to 13 inches in diameter, were sequenced and timed according to a script, <PERSON> Leibert </PERSON> said. `` When we looked at the videotape, the bursts were all in the sky where they should be when they were supposed to be,'' he said. <PERSON> Meyers </PERSON>, who said investigators had about 40 more witnesses to interview, said an inspection of the site yielded little conclusive information. `` We found a lot of debris along on the bank, and some of the markings were not of the type that the show uses,'' he said. `` Yet we did n't have any odor of gunpowder on it'' which would indicate a recently fired shell, he said. He said it would be several days before anything conclusive can be released. `` Most people were looking at the sky and were n't paying any attention. We'll get lucky if we find two of three people that saw something that do n't have a claim in this,'' <PERSON> Meyers </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diego </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fireworks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, which supplied the shells and the necessary state and federal licenses, carried the $ 1 million umbrella insurance policy required by the city, <PERSON> Leibert </PERSON> said. Fire Chief <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> said the shell appeared to explode twice. <PERSON> Leibert </PERSON> said his show did not use any `` double-banger'' shells. Any drifting debris from the launching site also should have been pushed away from the accident scene by the prevailing winds, he said. <PERSON> Meyers </PERSON> said that if the shell had come from the launch site, it must have come out of a launch tube, turned sharply right and skimmed 15 or 20 feet above the ground until hitting the bank. <PERSON> Leibert </PERSON> said the ensemble's most recent show was for the <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Derby </LOCATION> weekend in <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION> and its next show would be the July 4 celebration in <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>.
