<HEAD>Memorial Day Accidents Claim At Least 385 Lives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Traffic accidents claimed the lives of at least 385 people on the nation's roads during the three-day Memorial Day weekend, authorities said Tuesday. Based on `` the past trends of the Memorial Day holiday period,'' the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> had projected 380 to 480 people would die in traffic accidents, said council spokeswoman <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Carraro </PERSON>. The preliminary total late Tuesday morning `` is right around the normal'' for a non-holiday, three-day weekend, Ms. <PERSON> Carraro </PERSON> said. Generally, she said, more people die in accidents on holiday weekends because automobiles carry more people. The three-day holiday period began at 6 p.m. Friday, local time, and ended at midnight Monday. During last year's Memorial Day weekend, 416 people died in traffic accidents, the Chicago-based council said. The worst Memorial Day traffic toll in the last quarter-century was recorded in 1968, when 629 people died. The lowest recorded toll, in 1982, was 341. About 390 traffic deaths on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> roadways would be projected for a non-holiday, three-day weekend this time of year, council statistics clerk <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> said.
