<HEAD>Coroner Rules Deaths of Seven Drowning Victims Accidental</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COFFEEVILLE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A holiday joy ride in an overcrowded aluminum boat turned to tragedy when six young women drowned about 30 yards from the short of a lake, along with a man who tried to rescue them. Funeral home officials who met with the families of the seven victims said they hoped to complete arrangements by Wednesday morning. <ORGANIZATION> Yalobusha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coroner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> True </ORGANIZATION> said Monday he had ruled the deaths accidental. `` There were several people that witnessed the accident,'' he said. `` It was one of those tragic things.'' The bodies were recovered in eight to 10 feet of water near the boat, True said. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, 32, who was operating the 16-foot, flat-bottomed aluminum boat, said the occupants were on a slow `` joy ride,'' splashing water on each other when the accident occurred Monday afternoon. `` One girl leaned over when the boat was turning and some water started coming in the boat and everybody panicked,'' said <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, who admitted that the boat was overloaded. `` Everybody stood up and started moving around in the boat,'' said <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>. `` Then it turned over. They was just hollering ` Help. Help. Help.' Could n't none of them swim.'' `` There were about 35 or 40 people on the shore and I was saying, ` Somebody help us.' People on the shore kind of panicked. A couple people fainted,'' he said. True identified the victims as sisters <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, 21, and <PERSON> Marlee </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, 20; their cousin, <PERSON> Janice </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, 20; <PERSON> Sherry </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, 21; <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, 24, and <PERSON> Sherry </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, 19. <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PER