<HEAD>Sales Tax Going Up to Bail Out Treasury</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to make clear tax taking effect at end of day.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By A.V. GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An increase in the state sales tax from 5 percent to 6 percent is expected to pump $ 70.4 million into the state's hard-pressed treasury between now and July 1, 1989. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> McKown </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retailers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said that, despite objections to the higher tax which was to take effect at midnight Tuesday, most people `` feel they have an obligation to participate and pay the bills of the state and this is one way of doing it.'' The tax increase was part of an elaborate compromise worked out among the governor and the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> as they battled over finances earlier this year, when the state was forced to borrow $ 80 million on a short-term basis to meet operating expenses. The compromise was approved during the March 22 one-day special session of the Legislature. The increased sales tax is expected to raise $ 5.4 million for the remaining month of this fiscal year and and an estimated $ 65 million during the fiscal year that starts July 1. It is due to expire on June 30, 1989, although some merchants have said they expect it to become permanent after the general election in November. The tax was included in a bill that allowed the governor to borrow $ 30 million from the state black lung fund for miners to meet a backlog in Medicaid payments for medical treatment for the poor. The sales tax is to be used in part for the payback on the loan money. <PERSON> McKown </PERSON> said the temporary tax will cause little inconvenience for the state's 25,000 to 30,000 retailers, who collect and send the tax to the state <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. The state's border counties may see a temporary exodus of customers to other states, but <PERSON> McKown </PERSON> said he does not expect that to last long, if it even occurs. Surrounding <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> have a 5 percent sales tax; <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> has a 4 -LCB- percent tax rate. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> has called two more special legislative sessions to deal with finances. The second special session starts Wednesday and will cover all areas but education. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> has proposed a nickel-a-gallon gasoline tax increase to meet his proposed budget. The third special session will be dedicated to education, which takes up 72 percent of <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>'s proposed $ 1.46-billion budget. The governor has threatened to revive several taxes which failed passage in the Legislature previously. No date has been set for the third session.
