<HEAD>Clergymen Call For Non-Violence Resistance In South Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOWETO, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Anti-apartheid clergymen ended an unprecedented emergency conference Tuesday with a church service at which they called for intensified non-violent resistance to the government. `` We are determined we are going to obey God whatever the cost,'' said Anglican Archbishop <PERSON> Desmond </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutu </PERSON>. `` We are on the march!'' he shouted as a mostly black audience of 1,200 people shouted, cheered and whistled. The 1984 Nobel Peace Prize winner then removed symbolic gags from the mouths of black and white youths on the podium, took up a wooden cross and carried it back and forth down the center aisle of the <ORGANIZATION> Regina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mundi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cathedral </ORGANIZATION>. The audience held hands and swayed together, singing `` We Shall Overcome.'' Participating church leaders said they would try to mobilize support for a three-day national protest planned next week by black trade unions. They also disclosed plans for a campaign seeking release of political prisoners, to start June 12 and end July 18 _ the 70th birthday of jailed <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>. The Rev. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Chikane </PERSON>, general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION>, said: `` We are not trying to undermine authority or advocate anarchy. We are distinguishing between two different kinds of authority.'' The Rev. <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesak </PERSON>, mixed-race leader of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reformed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION>, said he wanted the convocation to adopt a stronger statement calling for more protests and direct confrontation with the government. `` I was hoping the convocation would ask for a personal commitment that not all church leaders are ready to make either in their personal capacities or on behalf of the churches,'' said <PERSON> Boesak </PERSON>. `` It will take time. But we are moving away from a theology of protest to a life of protest, and resistance.'' <PERSON> Chikane </PERSON> said there was division among the church leaders, the largest group in many years to gather to discuss action against white domination. He said the decision to support the national protest next week was significant but added that the church leaders had decided to form a committee to work out details of specific actions. During the convocation, workshops were held to discuss a range of anti-apartheid tactics, including `` non-cooperation and non-collaboration'' with the government. The agenda suggested that targets of civil disobedience could include tax payments, military service and racially oriented laws such as those mandating segregated residential areas. People attending the church service were asked to take these and other proposals back to their congregations for consideration. The convocation was sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION>, which includes major Protestant denominations active in the fight for black rights. Also participating were the Roman Catholic Church and a number of independent African churches. Organizers said political conditions in the country have worsened since leading clergymen decided in early February to organize the convocation. They cited the effective bannings of 17 anti-apartheid organizations, the closure of two opposition newspapers, and pending legislation to restrict labor unions and opposition political groups.
