<TEXT>
 An anonymous caller to a <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> radio station on Tuesday said a newspaper editor was kidnapped to force the government to suspend the extradition of drug traffickers to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` We are The Extraditables,'' the man told <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Todelar </ORGANIZATION> in a reference to a group that identifies itself with Colombian drug traffickers that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has sought to extradite for prosecution. The man said he and his associates abducted <PERSON> Alvaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurtado </PERSON> on Sunday in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurtado </PERSON>, who is also a <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader, was kidnapped by four men carrying machine guns who shot and killed his bodyguard. The caller also said the kidnappers want to exchange <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurtado </PERSON> for <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivas </PERSON>, a reputed leader of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s so-called <LOCATION> Medellin </LOCATION> drug cartel who was convicted in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on drug trafficking charges In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> was asked about the possibility of an exchange of <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurtado </PERSON> for <PERSON> Lehder </PERSON>. `` We do n't deal. We do n't make concessions,'' she said. `` We deplore this act of violence, whether it emanates from the traffickers, the violent left or right ... We offer his family and friends our hope he will be released soon.'' However, a statement signed by `` The Extraditables'' denied the gr