<FIRST>r a AM-LickObservatory     05-31 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lick Observatory,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Century Mark For Famous Window On The Stars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNT HAMILTON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lick Observatory, a pioneering mountaintop astronomical complex that once boasted the world's largest telescope, observes its 100th skywatching anniversary Wednesday It was at Lick where <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnard </PERSON> found the fifth moon of <LOCATION> Jupiter </LOCATION>; where the existence was established of innumerable distant galaxies; where expansion of the universe was mapped; and where scientists studied how stars form and age. Businessman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Lick </PERSON>, who set up a trust and earmarked $ 700,000 for construction of the telescope and observatory, made his orders clear: `` Build a powerful telescope, superior and more powerful than any telescope yet made.'' Lick died in 1876, 12 years before the observatory was ready for operation. But his remains were moved to <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hamiliton </LOCATION> in January 1887 and placed in a vault at the base of the Lick telescope. Astronomy was a strange choice for Lick, who got his start making pianos in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, made a fortune in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> real estate and once owned <LOCATION> Catalina </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and big pieces of downtown <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. Lick Observatory was built on 4,430-foot <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hamilton </LOCATION>, and an immense 36-inch lens was mounted on a 57-foot tube _ then the world's biggest telescope. `` It was the first real demonstration of the value of being on a mountaintop,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, an assistant Lick director, noting that before Lick, most observatories were in cities. Later, mountaintop observatories became standard, encouraging the development of other pristine sites, including those in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Owned and operated by the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Califoria </ORGANIZATION>, the observatory 60 miles south of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> has lost some of its glitter. But its seven telescope domes, offices and workshops have a world reputation for solid, valuable work. The telescope still functions, second in size only to the 40-inch refracting telescope at <ORGANIZATION> Yerkes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Observatory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>. The Lick telescopes today also include the 120-inch <PERSON> Shane </PERSON> reflector, a 40-inch reflector, two 24-inch reflectors and a twin 20-inch refractor. The telescopes are used all the time, and are most in demand for moonless nights. Lick also pioneered the use of reflecting telescopes, which use a mirror instead of a lens to focus light.
