<TEXT>
 Taxicabs are scarce, subway signs are indecipherable and police guards are everywhere. So when the going gets tough in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, tough <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> visitors go shopping. Many of the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> staffers and news reporters attending the <LOCATION> Reagan-Gorbachev </LOCATION> summit are forced to spend most of their time in the Hotel Mezhdunarodnaya press center. When they grab a few minutes of free time, they usually head for the hotel's duty-free <LOCATION> Beryozka </LOCATION> gift shop, which accepts <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollars and other hard foreign currencies. Among the recent gift shop customers was <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Crispen </PERSON>, press secretary to first lady <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, who was found inspecting oil paintings ofreligious figures. `` You caught me,'' she laughingly told a reporter. Another man who spent time the hotel was <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> official who flew to the Soviet capital from <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> to lend a hand at summit coverage. He discovered that only a few reporters are selected to accompany President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on his summit forays. Hundreds of other media people stay close to the press center, watching outside events on television monitors and attending press briefings by a steady stream of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet officials. `` I really haven ` t had time to get out since <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> arrived,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> stenographer <PERSON> Pamela </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> has spent virtually all her time in the `` Mezh,'' as the press hotel is nicknamed, or shuttling across town by bus to the Hotel Rossiya, where the television networks maintain headquarters. She slipped into the shop to buy souvenirs for a 3-year-old boy back home. Some of the most popular items on display are painted wooden Russian dolls, whose prices range from $ 3 to $ 48. Also favored are lacquered boxes, lifelike children's dolls and coffee table picture books. Determined shoppers who ventured out to the giant GUM department store near Red Square and other local shops were disappointed by the merchandise. `` I feel sorry for the Russians _ they do n't have anything,'' said <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> flight attendant. At the `` Marathon,'' a neighborhood cooperative store, one American shopper found 10 sweatshirts, a few headbands and a dozen pair of blue jeans _ one of which cost the equivalent of $ 176 in rubles. The biggest crowd stood around a display of European-made, low-heeled leather shoes. Besides shopping, the American summiteers enjoy eating the caviar, ham and cheese sandwiches at the press center or sampling the borscht, chicken <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION>, mushroom soup and other Russian fare in hotel restaurants. Far more popular, however, were the free hamburgers that a <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> entrepreneur, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Spiers </PERSON>, was dispensing at a kitchen in the Hotel Mezh. <PERSON> Spiers </PERSON>, president of a chain of fast-food restaurants called Fast Track, shipped in 10,000 hamburger patties to serve in a summit restaurant operated by Cajun cook <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Folse </PERSON>. When the restaurant's $ 16 cover charge _ fixed by the Soviets _ turned away many prospective customers, <PERSON> Spiers </PERSON> decided to give his hamburgers away. He says he figures his $ 25,000 loss is worth all the publicity. `` Representatives of every major media have eaten my burgers,'' he said.
