<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A flight attendant who was injured when a pilot abruptly turned a <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> DC9 to avoid a small plane said Tuesday that passengers remained calm and she did n't know what happened until after they landed. <PERSON> Milotka </PERSON> <PERSON> Liebelt </PERSON> said she was bent over her luggage near the rear of the airplane when the small plane was spotted about 100 feet away. `` It just happened in a split-second,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Liebelt </PERSON> said Tuesday from her <LOCATION> Akron </LOCATION> home. `` Before I could realize what was going on, I was on the floor with my bag in my lap.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Liebelt </PERSON> was the only person reported injured when <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> Flight 283 narrowly missed colliding with the small plane while the jet prepared to land Monday at <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hopkins </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. The flight from <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> carried 79 passengers and a crew of five. Mrs. <PERSON> Liebelt </PERSON>, 35, was treated at <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> General </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> for bruises to her back and left knee. `` I do n't see how that -LRB- small -RRB- plane could not have seen us,'' she said. `` Thank God that our first officer responded instantly.'' `` The first officer -LRB- co-pilot -RRB- observed a light aircraft approximately 100 feet below our aircraft and to the right. He initiated a sharp climb to the left and gained an additional 800 feet of altitude,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ned </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. `` The Continential pilot did a professional job in reacting the way he had been trained.'' <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said the airline does not release crew members' names. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> are investigating the incident, officials said Tuesday. The encounter occurred in restricted air space at about 7,000 feet and five miles southeast of the airport. However, <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Mort </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelstein </PERSON> said from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> that air traffic controllers were unable to track the small plane, which did n't show up on radar. Small planes entering restricted airspace near airports are required to get tower permission and to carry transponders, which produce a signal to display airplane identification on radar screens. Mrs. <PERSON> Liebelt </PERSON> said the flight had been uneventful and the passengers, who were in their seats in preparation for landing at the time of the sudden maneuver, remained calm. `` It's amazing when things happen, you do n't have time to get scared. You just assume your responsibilities,'' she said. Mrs. <PERSON> Liebelt </PERSON> said the plane's captain told the passengers what had happened after the plane landed at <LOCATION> Hopkins </LOCATION>.
