<HEAD>Houston-Area Restaurant Owner Cited For Hiring Illegal Aliens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal agents slapped $ 10,000 worth of citations on the owner of a <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> restaurant chain Tuesday, claiming he is <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>'s most blatant employer of illegal aliens. Immigration and <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> agents delivered citations and notices of intent to fine to lawyers for <PERSON> Ghulan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bombaywala </PERSON>, president and chief executive officer of <PERSON> Marco </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Restaurants </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION> The chain operates 10 Mexican restaurants that employ about 500 people, <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> officials said. <PERSON> Bombaywala </PERSON>'s lawyer said the government was overreacting. Under provisions of the 1986 Immigration Reform Act, Tuesday was the last day federal officials had to serve citations before issuing fines. Starting Wednesday, `` we can go directly to the fine. That's the major difference beginning June 1,'' INS District Director <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Parra </PERSON> said at a news conference. <PERSON> Parra </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bombaywala </PERSON> and his lawyer, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gee </PERSON>, had 30 days to respond to Tuesday's notices by either paying the fine or requesting a hearing before a federal administrative law judge. Gee said they likely would request the hearing. <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> officials said they raided one <PERSON> Marco </PERSON>'s Restaurant in January and arrested 18 illegal aliens working there. In April, another raid netted nine illegal workers. `` He did n't have any intention to clean up his act,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> McMahon </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> deputy director in charge of employer sanctions. `` The top rung of the ladder _ the corporate structure _ had some knowledge.'' But Gee said the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> citations and fines were an overreaction by the government and the result of a misunderstanding. `` Our client has made very strenuous efforts to comply,'' Gee said. `` All of our people now are in compliance.'' Gee, who described <PERSON> Bombaywala </PERSON> as a Pakistani who has become a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen, said his client has made good-faith efforts by meeting with <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> officials and by getting attorneys for undocumented aliens who wished to apply for amnesty. `` We have a disagreement -LRB- with the INS -RRB- as to what constitutes a good-faith effort,'' Gee said. He estimated more than 100 aliens had been aided by <PERSON> Bombaywala </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Finch </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> special agent who delivered the four-page citation and intent to fine to Gee with about a dozen reporters and photographers in tow, said the <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> INS office was working about 25 such cases, with around 15 nearing the stage at which fines will be sought. <PERSON> Parra </PERSON> said most of the 66,000 <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> businesses have cooperated with immigration officials to comply with the tough, new federal laws regarding hiring of illegal aliens. `` We are not going to tolerate non-compliance with the law,'' he said. `` The message to employers is: It's no longer good business to hire illegal aliens.''
