<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY26</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of Armenians stayed away from work on Tuesday in a general strike that shut down factories and mass transportation in a city at the center of an ethnic dispute, a local resident said. Also Tuesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency announced that two officials were dismissed from the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> for alleged negligence that led to the violence between Armenians and Azerbaijanis. In the Armenian capital of <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, round-the-clock demonstrations were reported to be continuing for a fifth day. The resident of the city of <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION>, reached by telephone from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, said public transport was not running and that factories and other businesses in the city were closed in a strike that had been going on for days. `` People are n't working,'' the woman said. Asked how many, she answered: `` Many thousands. Everyone.'' She hung up the telephone before a reporter could ask her name or other questions. In <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, dissident journalist <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON> said the general strike had been under way for about a week. Telephone calls to <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION> city offices and radio and television stations did not go through. <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION> is the main city of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, a region in the republic of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. Armenians want the Armenian-dominated region to be made a part of their neighboring republic. Armenian literary critic <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Popoyan </PERSON>, 45, said by telephone from his <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> home that since Friday about 5,000 people have gathered during the day and 20,000 in the evening on the square outside the city's Opera Theater. He said smaller groups of protesters, mostly students, continued the vigil overnight, `` awaiting an official response to their demand.'' The protesters want <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>'s Supreme Soviet, the republic's parliament, to consider the annexation issue at a meeting next week, he said <PERSON> Popoyan </PERSON>, who spent four years in jail and six months in internal exile for distributing underground literature, said <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> authorities have not tried to stop the demonstrations. On Monday, <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON>, who is half-Armenian and half-Russian, said the crowd in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> swelled to about 300,000. It was unclear why the figure he cited was so much higher than that given by <PERSON> Popoyan </PERSON>. Armenians began agitating in mid-February for the right to annex Nagorno-Karabakh. At the end of the month, ethnic rioting broke out in the Azerbaijani city of <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION>. At least 32 people _ six <PERSON> Azerbaijanis </PERSON> and 26 Armenians _ were killed. Most of the 160,000 residents of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> are ethnic Armenians, most of them Christians. Since 1923, the region has been part of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, whose titular ethnic group is predominantly Moslem. The Soviet government rejected the demand to change jurisdiction over Nagoro-Karabakh, opting instead for a program of social and economic development. On May 21, <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> officials fired the two leaders of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, apparently because they had not quelled the unrest. New party shake-ups were announced Tuesday. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the former first secretary of the <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> regional party committee, <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Kevorkov </PERSON>, was dismissed from the party because of his `` serious political mistakes.'' `` His errors resulted in the loss of the party organization's vanguard role and in the heightening of inter-ethnic relations,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said in announcing the action taken by a plenary meeting of the Azerbaijani party organization `` He was found to be personally responsible for the disorders that took place in the autonomous region.'' <PERSON> Kevorkov </PERSON> had been dismissed as head of the <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> party committee on Feb. 24. He was replaced by <PERSON> Genrikh </PERSON> <PERSON> Pogosyan </PERSON>, subsequently identified by <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> as an Armenian born in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the plenum also dismissed from the party D.M. <PERSON> Muslim-Zade </PERSON>, the former first secretary of the <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> city committee, for `` serious shortcomings in organizational and political work that brought about the tragic developments in <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION>.''
