<BYLINE>By CRAIG HORST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Republicans working Tuesday on their party platform accused the Democrats of being less open than the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> and of trying to hide liberal views of likely nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fahrenkopf </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said of the Democrats, `` They are simply not interested in writing an honest, straightforward platform that expresses their true plan for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. The Republican approach is one of openness.'' Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasten </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> said Republicans would force the Democrats `` to take the field'' on critical issues and would `` flush the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> Democrats'' out, exposing what he said were their left-of-center views. The seven-member committee met to discuss social issues in one of four hearings it will hold before the national convention in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. Sen. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kassebaum </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> said in remarks to the committee that the value of the platform should be restored by shortening it and not `` making it a catch-all and promise-all.'' <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> has made a similar request concerning his party's platform. <PERSON> Kassebaum </PERSON> said, `` The one major difference between Republicans and Democrats is that government must have a limited role.'' Gov. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> urged the committee to include a strong rural plank in the platform. `` Sometimes policies of the federal government have discriminated against rural areas,'' <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON> said. `` We have heard about urban renewal, but seldom have we heard about rural revitalization.'' The party's 1980 and 1984 platforms, the latter particularly pleasing to conservatives, will serve as a basis for the 1988 platform, said <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> <PERSON> Orr </PERSON>, chairman of the platform committee. `` It's a good base,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Orr </PERSON> said of the 1984 platform. `` But times have changed. There is a different emphasis that we will place on things.'' <PERSON> Fahrenkopf </PERSON> said the 1984 platform `` established a base, a soul'' for the party. `` But times have changed, problems have changed,'' <PERSON> Fahrenkopf </PERSON> said at a news conference held by the seven committee members during a lunch break. `` We want to take conservative approaches to solve the problems we see coming down the road.'' `` We have had no specific direction from <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Orr </PERSON> said, referring to likely <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> presidential nominee <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` We will have a line of communication open. We're very interested in the vice president's views.'' As for the party's November opponents, <PERSON> Fahrenkopf </PERSON> said, `` The Democrats face a level-with-America dilemma. Do they hide the liberal agenda and record of their nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, or do they level with Americans and detail their liberal goals and plans.''
