<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> gave the Toledo Zoo the go-ahead Tuesday to continue exhibiting two giant pandas on loan from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Klinger </PERSON>, spokesman for the service, said export documents provided by the zoo late Friday have been reviewed and found to be acceptable. `` The permit is acceptable to us,'' <PERSON> Klinger </PERSON> said. `` The condition of the law has been met. That should settle it.'' He said the zoo will be notified by letter Wednesday and that the panda exhibit will be allowed to continue. However, a lawsuit is pending in which a wildlife group contends the pandas _ an endangered species _ are being exploited for commercial gain. In its federal suit against the Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, the World Wildlife Fund argues that the exhibit violates an international convention that bars trafficking in endangered species for commerical purposes. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Norma </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> has set a hearing on the suit for June 13. The pandas entered the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on May 13 accompanied by an exemption form instead of a full Chinese export permit as required. The animals were allowed to begin their three-month exhibit last Tuesday as part of <LOCATION> Toledo </LOCATION>'s 150th anniversary celebration, but the <ORGANIZATION> USFWS </ORGANIZATION> gave the zoo until May 29 to provide the proper documentation.
