<HEAD>Major Thefts in 1980s</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Art Theft Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Paintings by <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Gogh </PERSON>, <PERSON> Cezanne </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jongkind </PERSON> recovered by Dutch police Tuesday, 11 days after they were stolen from an <LOCATION> Amsterdam </LOCATION> museum, were valued at up to $ 52 million. Here is a list of other major art thefts in this decade:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 FEB. 23, 1988 _ Thieves break into the <ORGANIZATION> Munch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, carrying away `` The Vampire,'' a painting by Norwegian artist <PERSON> Edvard </PERSON> <PERSON> Munch </PERSON> insured for $ 2.3 million. FEB. 8, 1988 _ In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s biggest art theft, burglars break through a skylight into the Colnaghi Art Gallery and steal 27 Old Master paintings and drawings, including two panels by Italian Renaissance master <PERSON> Fra </PERSON> <PERSON> Angelico </PERSON>. The art is valued at $ 6 million. MARCH 24, 1987 _ Six paintings are stolen from the Castagnino Museum in <LOCATION> Rosario </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>. Among the paintings, worth an estimated $ 12 million, are works by <ORGANIZATION> Goya </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Greco </PERSON>, <PERSON> Tiziano </PERSON> and <PERSON> Veronese </PERSON>. FEB. 14-15, 1987 _ Nine paintings valued at $ 2.65 million, including works by <ORGANIZATION> Renoir </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Brueghel </PERSON>, are stolen from the Noortman Art Gallery in <LOCATION> Maastricht </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>. MAY 21, 1986 _ <PERSON> Vermeer </PERSON>'s `` Lady Writing a Letter with Her Maid,'' is among 18 paintings worth $ 40 million stolen from <ORGANIZATION> Russborough </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Blessington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>. Others include works by <ORGANIZATION> Goya </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Rubens </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Gainsborough </PERSON>. Seven of the least valuable works are dumped near a reservoir. OCT. 27, 1985 _ Five armed men steal nine Impressionist paintings from <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>' Marmottan Museum in a bank-style holdup. Five Monets, including `` Impression Sunrise,'' are among those stolen. The curator estimates the paintings' value at $ 12.5 million. `` Impression Sunrise'' has been traced to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, but has not been recovered to date. NOVEMBER 1983 _ Seven Italian Renaissance masterpieces, including works by <PERSON> Raphael </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tintoretto </PERSON>, are stolen from the <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>. All of the paintings, worth $ 7 million, are recovered within a year.
