<HEAD>British Doctors Perform Third Transplant Using Fetal Brain Cells</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 British doctors have given a third sufferer of Parkinson's disease brain cells transplanted from an aborted fetus, a hospital announced Tuesday. A 58-year-old woman underwent the surgery May 17 at the <ORGANIZATION> Midland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Neurosurgery </ORGANIZATION> and Neurology at <LOCATION> Smethwick </LOCATION> in central <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. She was reported to be back home and showing `` an initially good response'' to the treatment. The hospital announced the development in a statement by neurologist <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitchcock </PERSON>, whose team carried out <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s first known fetal brain-cell transplants in March and April Parkinson's disease is a potentially fatal condition that causes gradual loss of muscle control. Fetal tissue is thought to stimulate production of dopamine, a brain chemical lacking in Parkinson's disease. <PERSON> Hitchcock </PERSON>'s disclosure last month that he used the experimental procedure provoked controversy. Critics complained it reduced the aborted fetus to the status of a human spare part. Others welcomed it as a possible medical breakthrough. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> has banned government scientists from carrying out surgery using tissue from aborted fetuses, pending study of the ethical, legal and medical questions involved. The first documented use of the experimental procedure was reported in January, when surgeons in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> said they injected tissue from a miscarried fetus into the brains of two Parkinson's sufferers last September. Swedish doctors subsequently reported use of the technique, with disappointing results. <PERSON> Hitchcock </PERSON> said last month that his team transplanted fetal brain cells into a 60-year-old woman and a 41-year-old man, both of whom were said to have shown `` dramatic improvement.'' <PERSON> Hitchcock </PERSON> said the latest operation was carried out under guidelines issued by the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> last month.
