<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> signaled Tuesday it is prepared to assist farmers in the nation's drought-stricken heartland by easing curbs on the use of land idled under conservation programs. Hay production and cattle grazing on such land will be allowed in counties found to be suffering from a natural disaster that harms pasture and forage crops, the department said. The statement came amid heightened concern over a drought hammering broad stretches of the nation's heartland from south <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> to the Canadian border and as far west as <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>. Thus far, however, no disaster counties have been declared. The statement from <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hertz </PERSON>, administrator of the <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stabilization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, mainly outlined possibilities already open to the department. It contained no new programs. Under the 1985 Farm Act, farmers must devote a specified portion of their land to conservation uses if they are to be eligible for crop programs that produce federal payments. The amount of land involved varies from one crop to another. For example, it is 27.5 percent for wheat. Producers also receive payments for placing endangered land in the long-term Conservation Reserve Program. Under the law, haying and grazing are banned on acreage devoted to conservation programs. The theory is that farmers already derive economic benefit from the land in the form of government payments. But <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> may make exceptions in the case of natural disasters. In counties found to be suffering from such a disaster, <ORGANIZATION> Hertz </ORGANIZATION> said, `` haying and grazing will be allowed for any consecutive five-month period between April 1 and October 1.'' He said determination of counties eligible will be made on a county-by-county basis. <ORGANIZATION> Hertz </ORGANIZATION> said no requests from state and county offices will be approved if it appears that doing so will adversely effect haying operations in the counties involved. No hay or forage harvested may be sold, he added. A producer may charge a `` reasonable harvesting fee'' for allowing other farmers to hay and graze on his acreage, however, the department said. But it said he `` may not receive compensation for the value of the vegetative matter that is harvested or grazed.'' <ORGANIZATION> Hertz </ORGANIZATION> noted that a number of steps already have been taken in response to rising concern over the drought. He said producers enrolled in <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s wheat and feed grains programs may take part in the 0-92 disaster program, even though the March 11 deadline for participation has passed. Under the 0-92 program, farmers produce no crop but still receive 92 percent of the federal payments they otherwise would get. He also pointed to two programs under which the government provides subsidies to farmers to purchase livestock feed.
