<HEAD>U.S., Soviets Clash Over Need for Nuclear Weapons Testing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s top arms control official, <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON>, said Tuesday the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will keep testing nuclear weapons to preserve its nuclear deterrent. A senior <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> official called such tests `` immoral.'' Speaking on the first day of a special four-week <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> session on disarmament, <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> added that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will not try to pass a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> resolution calling for arms cuts by Third World nations. <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON>, assistant director of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arms </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disarmament </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, said: `` We are not going to come here and insist that developing countries somehow change their defense priorities for the acquisition of arms. `` Of course, we would like them to spend less money on arms and put more money into development of their own countries.'' The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration wants to increase arms sales to foreign buyers this year to more than $ 15 billion, $ 3.3 billion more than last year. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is also a major arms supplier. <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said if the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> refused to sell to a foreign country seeking arms, `` they would go to another country that would say ` yes.''' When asked why <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> keeps testing nuclear weapons, he replied: `` The security policy of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its allies is based upon the concept of deterrence. `` And as long as this is the policy which undergirds our security and that of the Western alliance, we will continue to test, because the requirement exists.'' At a separate news conference, Deputy Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Petrovsky </PERSON> said, `` We decline this strategy and policy of nuclear deterrence, not only because of practical unusefulness but because of the immoral nature of this kind of deterrence. ... `` We think the time is right to stop the nuclear tests.'' <PERSON> Petrovsky </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> intends to `` reduce the number and might of nuclear tests conducted during each year'' and to press for adoption of a test ban treaty. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> opened the session by noting it began `` at a most opportune time ... -LRB- when -RRB- President <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and General Secretary -LRB- <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> -RRB- <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> are engaged in a dialogue in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> partly in the context of the reduction of strategic nuclear weapons.'' He expressed pleasure over the recent ratification of the U.S.-Soviet intermediate-range nuclear forces treaty to scrap medium and shorter-range nuclear missiles. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said it `` clearly shows that, with political will, agreements to reverse the nuclear-arms race are possible and compliance with them can be duly verified.'' He called on the superpowers to take the next step and cut in half their long-range nuclear arsenals under a strategic arms reduction treaty, or START. <PERSON> Petrovsky </PERSON> told reporters the Soviets will seek to focus the attention of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> disarmament session on `` the whole range of nuclear issues, on the nuclear weapons test ban, prevention of the weapons' expansion into outer space, the soonest possible conclusion of a convention on the ban on chemical weapons,'' as well as reducing conventional forces. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> wants the session to stress cuts in conventional arms. <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> does not seek to bring <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> into superpower talks to reduce nuclear arsenals. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> would prefer a treaty that would include British and French weapons. <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> also seeks to balance European arms control with progress on human rights issues. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> stated in 1979 that the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> should play a central role in disarmament, and that complete nuclear disarmament was the priority. No breakthroughs are expected to emerge at this <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> session, during which at least 25 presidents and prime ministers are scheduled to address the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>.
