<HEAD>Bush Says Wants No Tax Increase, No Strong Credit Tightening</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said Tuesday he would reject any call for a federal tax increase, even if one came from a blue-ribbon bipartisan commission now working on ways to trim the huge federal deficit. However, he also said that higher local school taxes might be needed to carry out his education policies. On another economic subject, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> cautioned the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> against tightening credit too much, saying, `` I do n't want to see action taken that's going to shut down economic growth.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the all-but-certain Republican presidential nominee, met with a group of private economic advisers, then spoke with reporters in a meeting hall in this oceanside town where he has a vacation home. He said that, while he had full confidence in <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>, he wanted to voice `` a word of caution.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> in recent weeks has been slightly tightening credit in hopes that by nudging up interest rates it can keep inflation in check. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said `` there was some expression of concern'' about recent <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> actions among the economists during the first day of a two-day session. The group included <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> economist <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Feldstein </PERSON>, a former chairman of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisers </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> economist <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boskin </PERSON>. They are two of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s most frequently consulted economic advisers <PERSON> Feldstein </PERSON> quit his <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> post after his advocacy of tax increases to reduce the federal deficit ran afoul of <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration no-new-taxes policy. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said of <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> policymakers, `` I think they are putting a great emphasis on inflation. Whether it's too much, I do n't know. ... It's a tough balancing thing.'' In response to a reporter's question, he said he would reject the notion of a tax increase even if it were part of the recommendations of the bipartisan commission now at work. The panel, which includes administration appointees as well as members appointed by <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> congressional leaders, was formed earlier this year to seek ways to trim the nation's massive budget deficit. `` It seems to me that commission might well come up with a tax increase,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` And I'll be saying, wait a minute, I've taken my case to the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people to hold the line on taxes. The commission, which will also gain two new members appointed by the president-elect after the November election, is scheduled to present its findings in 1989. `` I wold be interested in their views, but not persuaded'' if a tax increase is included, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. However, the vice president, who has told audiences he wants to be the `` education president'' and has stressed educational issues in his campaign, was asked if local school taxing authorites might have to increase taxes to carry out some of the still-unspecified programs he envisions. `` They may have to,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` Ninety-three percent of the money for education comes from sources other than the federal government. If it's taxes, that's where it has to be. It is n't going to be at the federal level, absolutely. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is spending a week at his family oceanside retreat in a series of meetings with advisers and Republican consultants. The vice president said that there was wide support among the economists for his propsal for a `` flexible freeze'' on spending to reduce the budget deficit. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan would hold federal spending, except for Social Security benefits, to the levels of the 1989 budget plus inflation. Individual programs would not have to be frozen. However, for every one that went up, another would have to go down by a corresponding amount. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> says such a plan could result in a balanced budget within four years. He said there was some discussion of taxes at Tuesday's meeting, but that he made his position clear from the outset that he opposed any form of tax increase. On other subjects, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>: _ Said he was pleased with how things were going in the superpower talks in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and did not think that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> `` offended the Soviets by talking too much about human rights I do n't believe that for a minute.'' _ Said that his wait-and-see position on Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> has n't changed `` We're so close to hearing from that independent counsel we ought to get the report and let <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> sort all that out.'' _ Said remarks like a recent comment by <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> that he was a `` country club Republican'' did n't bother `` Listen, that's just part of the territory. That was mild, they did n't even lay a glove on me.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had said over the weekend that his campaign was running low on cash and tht it might have to curtail some travel plans after the June 7 <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> primary. Aide <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Teeter </PERSON> said on Tuesday that, of the $ 29.5 million raised so far by the campaign, including $ 7 million in federal matching funds, less than $ 1.5 million is left in campaign coffers. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has raised the maximum allowed by law for pre-convention spending.
