<FIRST>r a AM-BoeingCoincidence     05-31 0745</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boeing Coincidence,0766</SECOND>
<HEAD>Similarities Between Taiwan, Aloha Crash Only Coincidence, Boeing
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 that disintegrated and crashed over <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> in 1981 and another one that lost part of its fuselage over <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> in April were built back-to-back, but <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> officials Tuesday attributed any similarities to coincidence. The 151st 737-200 model <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> produced was the <ORGANIZATION> Far </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> jet that broke up at 22,000 feet over central <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> Aug. 22, 1981, killing all 110 people on board. No. 152 was the <ORGANIZATION> Aloha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> aircraft on which a 20-foot section of forward upper fuselage ripped away at 24,000 feet on April 28. A flight attendant fell to her death and 61 passengers were injured, but the flight crew landed the plane safely. The cause of the <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> accident is still under investigation. But the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> has ordered <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines flying older 737s to re-inspect the aircraft, including mandatory electronic testing of planes with more than 50,000 landings. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> believes the Far Eastern crash was caused by maintenance problems, spokesman <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Gamble </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airplanes </ORGANIZATION> said. Any connection between that crash and the <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> accident are `` a series of coincidences,'' <PERSON> Gamble </PERSON> said. `` We do not think that is a fair assessment'' to directly link the two, he said. At the time of the planes' manufacture in 1969, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> was turning out two or three 737s a month, <PERSON> Gamble </PERSON> said. He said he knew of no other problems involving 737s made about that time. <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Cosgrove </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airplanes </ORGANIZATION> vice president and general manager for engineering, was quoted by The Wall Street Journal Tuesday as saying the consecutive aircraft numbers were coincidence. Although both accidents involved the same part of the fuselage, nothing was inherently wrong with that portion of the aircraft, <PERSON> Cosgrove </PERSON> said. He told the Journal that the Taiwanese 737 repeatedly was used to ship fish in open containers, and corrosive salt water may have gotten into the cargo hold. The newspaper said Far Eastern officials denied that. <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Benson </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, said Tuesday the safety board's investigators also believe leaking salt water from fish shipments caused the <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> jet's corrosion. Gamble said <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> had issued a series of service bulletins on older 737s. Those included a March 1978 bulletin recommending additional inspections of fuselage skins for possible corrosion. On July 1, 1981, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> issued an airworthiness directive requiring <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carriers to inspect older 737s. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> had supplied kits to airlines to allow them to replace corroded skin on planes, <PERSON> Gamble </PERSON> said. A kit was delivered to Far Eastern in April 1980, which means it was in the company's spare parts inventory considerably before that crash, but it apparently was never used on the plane, he said. <PERSON> Cosgrove </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, to attend a conference on problems with aging aircraft and was unavailable for comment Tuesday, <PERSON> Gamble </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> called the three-day conference after the <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> incident to study safety issues involving older aircraft. One of the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> directives issued after the Aloha accident focuses on early models of 737s in which <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> used a cold-bonding process, in which structural parts of the fuselage were laminated using an adhesive that cured at room temperature. <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, director of public relations for <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airplanes </ORGANIZATION>, said that about 1971, after the first 291 models of 737s were built, the company changed to a hot-bonding process that used an adhesive that cured with heat. He said the new method was a technological improvement over the previous process, which was more prone to corrosion. About that time, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> also made a series of changes in manufacturing processes and design, including strengthening parts of the fuselage and making the skin thicker where sections overlapped, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said. The twin-engine 737 is the world's most popular commercial aircraft, with more than 2,000 on order. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said he found a number of differences between the two accidents. The Taiwanese plane, for example, was 12 years old and had approximately 33,000 landings, while the <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> jet was 20 years old and had about 90,000 landings. He said that `` as best we know,'' the Far Eastern accident was caused by corrosion in the plane's cargo hold, while the <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> accident involved the top of the plane. `` But again, the appropriate thing is to see what the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> conclude before drawing all these analogies and comparisons,'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
