ich the then-ruling junta under Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Namphy </PERSON> did little to curtail. <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> maintained their aid commitments to <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>, but the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> have withheld $ 40 million in loans. <PERSON> LaTortue </PERSON>, who spent 10 years in <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> as part of his 25-year exile during the Duvalier dictatorships, criticized <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials for blocking aid to <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> following controversial national elections last January. He asked <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commonwealth, to make available scholarships for Haitian students and do what it could to promote <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION>'s economic development. Dictator <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Duvalier </PERSON> ruled <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> since 1957. His son, <PERSON> Jean-Claude </PERSON>, took over at his death but fled Feb. 7, 1986 during a popular uprising. A president, <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Manigat </PERSON>, was chosen in January.
