<HEAD>Chile Extends State Of Emergency</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout with junta member saying emergency will be
lifted before referendum, more exiles to be allowed to return. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The military government on Tuesday decreed a 90-day extension of the state of emergency. Opposition leaders say the extension will prevent a fair campaign in the presidential referendum this year. In another development, <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> officials issued a list Tuesday of 25 political exiles allowed to return home. It included several prominent figures in the leftist government of President <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON> that was overthrown in September 1973. More than 4,000 exiles have been authorized to return since the government began issuing periodic lists early in 1986, but only a few hundred have done so. Human rights groups say 400 exiles still are banned. The government claims the number is closer to 300. No date has been set for the presidential referendum, in which Chileans will be allowed only to vote `` yes'' or `` no'' on a single, military-appointed candidate for the 1989-97 term. Gen. <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, who is 72 and has been president since the 1973 military coup, is considered the most likely candidate. If voters reject the government's choice, a competitive election is to occur a year later, with <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> remaining in office until then. The state of emergency would have expired Tuesday. `` By renewing the state of emergency, the government is casting doubt on the fairness of its own plebiscite,'' said <PERSON> Patricio </PERSON> <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON>, president of the centrist <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, the largest opposition group. <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON>, president of the centrist <ORGANIZATION> Radical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said: `` Under the state of emergency, the most basic guarantees for a clean electoral process can not exist.'' Government officials have hinted the election might be held Sept. 11, which means the emergency would cover at least part of the campaign. Adm. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Merino </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> navy </ORGANIZATION> chief and member of the ruling military junta, told reporters after a junta meeting the emergency would be lifted 30 days before the referendum. `` If the opposition does n't like it, it means the state of emergency is good,'' Merino said. <PERSON> Genaro </PERSON> <PERSON> Arriagada </PERSON>, a leading member of a 15-party coalition organized to promote a `` no'' vote in the referendum called extending the emergency `` a gross abuse'' by the government. Officials claim the emergency is necessary to deal with what the government calls a growing terrorist threat from radical leftists. The <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> and several foreign governments, including the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, have urged <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> to lift the restrictions before the referendum. Under the emergency, which was imposed when the military seized power and has been enforced intermittently since, the government can restrict freedom of the press and ban public gatherings. It allows authorities to censor mail and prevent citizens from entering or leaving the country or traveling freely. The emergency is enforced by regional military commanders. On December 17, 1987, President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> declared his support for a <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> statement urging <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s government to lift the restrictions several months before the election The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> statement said that was essential for a fair campaign.
