<HEAD>Videotape Retailers, Anti-Porn Group Head For Showdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY R. SANDOK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An anti-pornography group is planning to picket videotape retailers, who plan to retaliate with boycott threats against protesters' employers, as amendments to the state's obscenity law take effect A group called the <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cleanup </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Project </ORGANIZATION> plans to protest at about 50 videotape stores throughout the state Saturday to draw attention to provisions taking effect Wednesday and to urge local officials to enforce it, said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinrich </PERSON>, director of the anti-pornography organization. But video store owners are planning a countermove, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ballstadt </PERSON>, president of Adventures in Video, which operates 10 videotape stores in the Minneapolis-St. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> area `` In retaliation for this picketing, video store operators are going to hire private detectives, take down license plate numbers of people picketing and find out where they are employed,'' <PERSON> Ballstadt </PERSON> said. Letters will be sent to the picketers' employers telling them their products will be boycotted because of their employees' activities, he said. `` If these people think they can walk around and express their freedoms, which they have a right to do, they're going to have to pay a price, just as we have to,'' <PERSON> Ballstadt </PERSON> said. The Legislature approved amendments this year to make the state's obscenity law conform with <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rulings. `` The changes technically are not that great, but they do provide some tools for prosecutors to use,'' <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> Solicitor General <PERSON> Norm </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> said. The previous law provided only for civil penalties and left unclear what role prosecutors should play in enforcing it, <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> said. The new law provides for criminal penalties, which clearly are in the purview of county prosecutors, he said. A first offense is considered a gross misdemeanor and carries a penalty of up to one year in prison, a $ 3,000 fine or both. Subsequent offenses are considered felonies and carry a prison term of up to two years, a fine of up to $ 10,000 or both. Among its provisions, the law prohibits distribution of obscene materials and specifically includes videotapes in its definition of materials that may be deemed obscene. `` Anything on film or video is more enticing than a still picture, and this material is readily available to children of all ages and people of all ages,'' <PERSON> Heinrich </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Heinrich </PERSON> said pickets will target `` major hard-core pornography outlets throughout the state'' which previously were contacted by the group and have refused to remove what the group considers obscene materials from their shelves. Besides picketing stores in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION> and some suburbs, protests are planned at stores in <LOCATION> Mankato </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> St </LOCATION>. Cloud and <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, he said. Though <PERSON> Ballstadt </PERSON> came up with the idea for the boycott to counter the pickets, his own stores may no longer offer the videotapes targeted by the group. A decision has yet to be made, he said.
