<HEAD>Ethiopian Leader Calls For Better Relations With U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE FAUL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Mengistu </PERSON> <PERSON> Haile </PERSON> <PERSON> Mariam </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> called on Tuesday for better relations between his Marxist government and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, reminding Americans, `` Once upon a time we were good friends.'' The leader of this East African nation also made an impassioned defense of <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s war in its northern provinces, charging that the rebels are fighting a proxy war to consolidate <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> control of the <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. In reply to a question, <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> denied that his government was using food as a weapon in the north, where the war and a big government counteroffensive have jeopardized a massive Western-financed relief effort for 3.2 million Ethiopians facing starvation in <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION> and Tigre provinces. Instead, <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> insisted, rebels were using `` an issue as sensitive as a food deficit situation and hunger to elicit international sympathy and support for them to promote their propaganda activities against us.'' Mengistu spoke with unusual candor on a wide range of issues, gesticulating with passion and occasionally smiling and laughing during a six-hour news conference with foreign reporters, his first since May 1986. For the first time, <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> accused <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> states of backing the northern secessionist insurgency, where rebels have won major victories this year by capturing several towns. Rebels of the <ORGANIZATION> Eritrean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> have been fighting for 27 years in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s oldest civil war. <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> made no reference to the insurgency by rebels of the <ORGANIZATION> Tigrean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, who have been fighting for 14 years for a bigger say in the governing of their province. <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government refused to impose sanctions on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> but was `` imposing an undeclared embargo'' on <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>. He said <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> was `` at the verge of cutting the last tethers which we have to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>'' with congressional discussions last week on stopping annual imports of 20,000 tons of Ethiopian coffee. `` We are not really pleased with our relations with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and it is our hope that better times will come in the future. We want to assure them, and I am sincere, quite sincere, about this, that we will do our best to improve relations,'' <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> said. `` We have always pushed for better relations with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and I hope the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will reciprocate.. Once upon a time we were good friends.'' He said Ethiopians were fond of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people and admired their achivements, but relations could improve only if `` the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> accepts us on a basis of equality and respect.'' `` We are really not sure what mistakes we have committed against the -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> -RRB- government,'' he said, adding perhaps it was <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s choice of socialism that was repugnant to `` the defender of capitalist values. He said <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s Marxist revolution of September 1974 had improved lives of the country's 42 million people. Contrary to Western news reports, he said, and to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government insistence on categorizing it as communist, his government was not an ogre intent on filling <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s prisons with political dissidents and starving its people. Western diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, were puzzled by <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION>'s conciliatory attitude. They said <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> at the last minute caused <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistant secretary of state for <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> affairs, to cancel a January visit when it announced he would not be meeting <LOCATION> Mengistu </LOCATION>. In February, <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON> said he believed <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> was not serious about improving relations with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Once-warm <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> relations with <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> deteriorated after the revolution in which <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> and a clique of fellow army officers overthrew Emperor <PERSON> Haile </PERSON> <PERSON> Selassie </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> continued to arm the new military government until <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION> invaded <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s southern <LOCATION> Ogaden </LOCATION> region in 1977. In a dramatic superpower reversal, the Soviets switched sides to <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> started backing the Somalis. <ORGANIZATION> Mengistu </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday that rebels in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> also had won support from progressive countries, which the diplomats identified as <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, which in the past have helped trained Eritrean rebels. About 2,500 Cuban troops in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> have refused to fight in the north.
