<FIRST>u w AM-EMPSuit     05-31 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EMP Suit,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Tests Put Off By Court Order; Were Set To Start Wednesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge Tuesday temporarily enjoined the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> from starting tests of a high-powered electrical generator designed to simulate one of the effects of a nuclear explosion. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> <PERSON> Penn </PERSON>, after hearing arguments from attorneys representing the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and the Foundation on Economic Trends, issued a temporary restraining order against the tests, which were set to begin Wednesday. The restraining order, which expires at noon Friday, was issued to give the government time to file a motion striking a paragraph from a consent decree the foundation contends prohibits the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> from beginning the tests. <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officials had planned to begin the test Wednesday with Empress II barge in international waters about 15 miles off the <LOCATION> Virginia-North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> coast. The Empress II barge is equipped with two diesel generators and a huge antenna system, capable of sending `` pulses'' of electrical power into the atmosphere at power levels up to 7 million volts to test a phenomenon known as electro-magnetic pulse, or EMP. Each pulse lasts only a billionth of a second, and the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> maintains the testing will have no affect on human or marine life. Electro-magnetic pulse is a powerful wave, or surge, of electrical energy that is released by a nuclear explosion and which can travel long distances through the atmosphere or water. <ORGANIZATION> EMP </ORGANIZATION> became a matter of concern to the military in the early 1960's when the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> discovered a nuclear bomb detonated at high altitudes could generate a pulse so strong it could disable the electronic components used in computers, communications and guidance equipment. As a result of that discovery, military laboratories have studied the phenomenon for 25 years in the course of developing methods for `` hardening'' electronic weapon components to withstand EMP. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> wants to use the Empress II barge to test its success in hardening electronic equipment on warships. The Foundation on Economic Trends, an activist environmental group that has long tried to curtail biological weapon research, sued the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> in March 1987 with the goal of stopping all <ORGANIZATION> EMP </ORGANIZATION> testing until environmental impact studies had been performed. The lawsuit asserted that EMP experiments could `` affect human health directly, and through the disruption of electronic circuits in nuclear power plants, automobiles, computers, airplanes, phone lines and navigational systems, can cause potential catastrophies under many possible circumstances.'' Two weeks ago, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> agreed to settle that suit by sharply curtailing or shutting down <ORGANIZATION> EMP </ORGANIZATION> research facilities across the country until environmental assessments were performed. In the case of Empress II, however, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> argues it already has performed the necessary environmental study and thus can proceed with testing. The foundation acknowledges the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has finished one environmental study, but says the recent settlement clearly envisioned the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> performing a second study because the first focused on the effect of <ORGANIZATION> EMP </ORGANIZATION> testing in the <LOCATION> Chesapeake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, not the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> prohibited <ORGANIZATION> EMP </ORGANIZATION> testing in the <LOCATION> Chesapeake </LOCATION>. `` The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has violated the settlement,'' asserted <PERSON> Jeremy </PERSON> <PERSON> Rifkin </PERSON>, the president of the foundation. `` Our attorneys questioned them on this before we finalized the settlement. They ca n't claim now that the first impact study is sufficient. And if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> says it's too dangerous for the bay, why should the waters off <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> be treated differently?'' <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION>'s ruling gives the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> time to file a motion to strike the paragraph in the consent decree that <PERSON> Rifkin </PERSON> contends prohibits the test.
</TEXT>
