<BYLINE>By DENISE LAYFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Researchers studying four AIDS-infected men who appeared to stop producing detectable antibodies to the disease confirmed the finding Tuesday and said the virus may have stopped reproducing in those patients. Tests to pinpoint AIDS and protect blood supplies are based upon detection of the antibodies produced naturally by the body to fight the virus. But <PERSON> Homayoon </PERSON> <PERSON> Farzadegan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Saah </PERSON>, both professors of epidemiology at the <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, said their findings do not imply increased dangers of blood supply contamination. `` I do n't think the risk to the blood supply is any different today than it was yesterday,'' said Saah during a news conference. The instances of AIDS victims who stop producing detectable antibodies to the disease are `` very, very rare,'' and so far have only been observed in those who show small amounts of the virus present in their bodies, Saah said. Four of 1,000 homosexual men who participated in the researchers' continuing study showed the loss of antibodies up to 3 -LCB- years ago and continue to test negative. `` Usually when an infected person loses HIV-1 antibodies, he or she is in the end stages of AIDS and has a deteriorated immune system,'' said <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Polk </PERSON>, also a professor of epidemiology at the school and co-author of a report on the study. But the four men `` had no clinical symptoms of illness, such as swollen lymph glands or abnormal counts of the white blood cells targeted by the virus,'' he added. The researchers reported their findings in June 1987, but could not determine whether the men were properly diagnosed as having AIDS initially and whether mistakes had been made in laboratory tests. During follow-up, the researchers used a new method to test for the virus rather than the antibody and have determined that the men show evidence of infection, but not antibodies to the AIDS virus. The new test, called polymerase chain reaction assay or PCR, magnifies the presence of the virus' genetic material up to 1 million times. <PERSON> Farzadegan </PERSON> speculated that the virus may go into a latent phase during which it does not reproduce. `` We do n't know if something in the virus itself is defective and causing it not to reproduce, or whether it is something within the host,'' Saah said, adding that researchers have not determined whether the disease is transmissible during this phase. AIDS is caused by a virus that attacks the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to fatal infections and cancers. It is most often transmitted by sexual contact or by drug abusers sharing contaminated hypodermic needles and syringes. All of the men who participated in the initial report are participants in the Multicenter AIDS Cohort Study -LRB- MACS -RRB- that follows nearly 5,000 homosexual and bisexual men in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> to document the natural progression of AIDS. The latest findings are to be published in the June 1 issue of Annals of Internal Medicine.
</TEXT>
