<HEAD>Group Urges Legislation To Outlaw Execution Of The Mentally
Retarded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Advocates for the mentally retarded said Tuesday that executing the mentally retarded, even those convicted of first degree murder, is cruel and unusual punishment and urged lawmakers nationwide to outlaw the practice. `` It has been our experience that even the foremost proponents of the dealth penalty draw the line at young children and people with mental retardation,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON>, president-elect of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> on Mental Retardation. `` States which have the death penalty, in our view, must pass laws that make it unlawful to execute someone who is mentally retarded or to sentence to death someone who is mentally retarded,'' said <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> announced the organization's resolution calling for a ban on the death penalty for the retarded at a press conference during the group's annual conference, citing a recently passed <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> law that allows for a plea of `` guilty but mentally retarded.'' <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON>, a law professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION>, said the <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> law requires a psychological examination for defendants who wished to enter the plea. Individuals convicted under the law could be sentenced to life imprisonment but not executed he said. <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> also noted that most of the members of the <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> are strong supporters of capital punishment. The <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> law, which becomes effective July 1, was prompted by widespread criticism of the June 24, 1986 execution of mentally retarded convicted murderer <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowden </PERSON>. `` This position, that the mentally retarded should never be sentenced to death or executed, leaves the whole array of the criminal justice system left to deal with in any way that seems most appropriate,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Burr </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> which has handled several capital punishment cases involving the mentally retarded. According to figures compiled by <PERSON> Burr </PERSON>'s group, at least 13 percent of the 66 persons executed since capital punishment was reinstated in 1976 had been diagnosed as mentally retarded. <PERSON> Burr </PERSON> also noted that while blacks comprise 40 percent of the general prison population, 80 percent of all mentally retarded prisoners are black or Hispanic. Both men agreed that initial determination of a defendant's mental capacity was vital to correcting the problem They urged states to follow the example of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, which routinely tests its prison inmates for mental deficiencies. `` We need to address the needs of criminal offenders or criminal defendants from the very begining when confessions are sought, when waivers of rights are sought, `` <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> said. He noted the need to educate members of the criminal justice system about mental retardation `` to make sure justice is done'' in cases involving the mentally retarded. But <PERSON> Burr </PERSON> cautioned that even with these procedures in place a number of mentally retarded defendants may be `` deemed competent to stand trail or educated sufficiently to become compenent to stand trial ... and -LRB- could be -RRB- convicted'' to face possible execution. <PERSON> Burr </PERSON> noted that there were several cases currently in the court system in which a retarded individual sits on death row. He cited the case of <PERSON> Limmie </PERSON> <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON>, 28, of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> who was convicted in the ax murder of a crippled neighbor in 1985. <PERSON> Burr </PERSON> said the courts should be to asked decide whether executing <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON>, whom he said has the mind of a 10 - or 12-year old, would constitute a violation of the 8th Amendment's prohibition of cruel and unusual punishment
