<TEXT>
 Soldiers arrested dozens of protesting students and teachers on a university campus in <LOCATION> Quito </LOCATION> on Tuesday after the government declared a state of emergency to counter a planned nationwide strike. Interior Minister <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> <PERSON> Moeller </PERSON> said troops arrested 27 people at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Polytechnical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, entering the school after students threw rocks at a car carrying military personnel. At an evening news conference, he called the planned general strike `` illegal and anti-constitutional.'' <PERSON> Ruben </PERSON> <PERSON> Orellana </PERSON>, the university rector, said both students and professors were detained. The independent station <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quito </ORGANIZATION> said 60 people were seized. Witnesses said troops also fired machine guns, but no casualties were reported. <PERSON> Moeller </PERSON> did not mention any gunfire nor did he identify those arrested. President <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Febres </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON> signed a state of emergency order that went into effect at 9 p.m. Tuesday, just hours before the one-day, anti-government general strike was to start Wednesday. The strike, the seventh against the <PERSON> Febres </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordero </PERSON> government, was called by the communist-led <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laborers </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>'s most powerful union <PERSON> Fausto </PERSON> <PERSON> Durand </PERSON>, president of the 200,000-member union, said the main demand is an increase in workers' wages from $ 31 a month to $ 76. Labor unrest in this small Andean nation has intensified over the past two years, because of economic woes arising largely from depressed world prices for oil, <LOCATION> Ecuador