<HEAD>Argentina Considering Shutdown of Nuclear Plant Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDALL HACKLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Financial shortfalls may force <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s leading user of nuclear power, to halt construction on a third nuclear reactor and a heavy-water plant, its top nuclear official says. Plans are being made to stop work on the nuclear reactor Atucha II, which is 60 percent completed, and <PERSON> Arroyito </PERSON>, 90 percent finished, unless financing is obtained or the government agrees to a $ 800 million budget request, said <PERSON> Emma </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferreira </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. `` We'll have to stop work on the big ones first if we do n't get enough money or obtain financing for the projects,'' Ms. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferreira </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s top-ranking female government official, said in a recent interview. A shutdown could hurt <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s nuclear industry, which is the most advanced in the Western Hemisphere outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, and cut into its future sales of surplus heavy water. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> has a contract to build a $ 100-million, 10-megawatt nuclear reactor outside <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>. It also has contracts to build a nuclear reactor in <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> and to provide enriched uranium for a small experimental nuclear reactor at <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Tehran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, Ms. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferreira </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s nuclear technicians have mastered the entire fuel cycle, which gives them the ability to make nuclear weapons, but officials from President <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> on down deny this is in their plans. At one time, the nuclear program was closely tied to the armed forces, in particular the navy. An admiral headed the <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> until the early 1980s, and some reports at the time said the military favored building an atomic bomb. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> mines its own uranium ore in the Andes. It prepares its own fuel, and is capable of enriching the fuel, making fuel elements, running nuclear reactors and reprocessing the fuel. Enriching and reprocessing fuel are the keys to making nuclear weapons. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, the world's eighth-largest country geographically, has two existing nuclear power plants. Until its economic crisis worsened last year, it had dreams of building four power plants by the end of the century. `` There's no sense in talking now even about a fourth nuclear plant,'' Ms. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferreira </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> also has an uranium-enrichment plant, six research reactors and two reprocessing plants. The nuclear program is important to <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, providing up to 20 percent of its electrical power, and is a source of pride to a country whose standard of living has declined steadily since the 1950s. But now <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> is the developing world's third-largest debtor behind <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, owing $ 55 billion. It also has a 247 percent inflation rate in addition to other severe economic problems, including a loss of real wages for workers. Indeed, 22 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>'s 6,500-member work force have left their jobs since 1983, many for similar posts offering double their pay in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, Ms. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferreira </PERSON> said. Neighboring <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> has a nuclear-power program but its sole plant near <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Janeiro </LOCATION> has had constant troubles. Plans to build two other nuclear plants have been set aside for the time being. Ms. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferreira </PERSON>, a 52-year-old nuclear physicist, took over the commission last year when her predecessor quit over budgetary disputes with the government. As head of commission, she reports directly to President <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>. Although officials deny any plans for nuclear weapons, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> has yet to sign the international nuclear non-proliferation treaty. It opposes the treaty on grounds that it interferes with national sovereignty. The other non-signatory nations with nuclear technology are <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. Accidents at Argentine nuclear facilities have left three technicians dead since 1982 but experts say <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> is not considered unsafe. A radioactive water spill and a burst pipe also briefly shut down Atucha I and the Embalse plant last year and in May. National reliance on nuclear-generated power became apparent in April when power shortages caused in part by temporary shutdowns of Atucha I and Embalse forced emergency power cutoffs in <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> del </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plata </LOCATION> and other major cities. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s nuclear interest stems from 1950, during the first presidency of <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peron </PERSON>. Its first power plant was Atucha I, a 335-megawatt facility built with West German technology in 1974. The second, Embalse, outside <LOCATION> Cordoba </LOCATION> in north-central <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, was finished in 1983. Built with Canadian technology, it has 600 megawatts of power, equal to the <ORGANIZATION> Connecticut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION> plant in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Atucha II, if it is completed, will have 745 megawatts.
</TEXT>
