<HEAD>Undocumented Workers Still Taking Risks for Jobs in U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAM ROSSIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTERREY, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` They keep crossing the river,'' said <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Trejo </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Ciudad </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juarez </LOCATION> on the <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION>. He was talking about Mexican laborers and how the new <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> immigration law was n't stopping them from illegally crossing the border to work in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` And people still are coming from the central and south of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> hoping to go to the other side,'' <PERSON> Trejo </PERSON> said on the telephone. He is the press chief for Mayor <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Ciudad </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juarez </LOCATION>, on the other side of the <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paso </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. He and other Mexican authorities believe the unwritten law of supply and demand is winning out over the 1986 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Immigration Reform and Control Act, also known as the Simpson-Rodino law, even though jobs are going begging in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. `` The undocumented migrants continue entering the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as if there never had been a Simpson-Rodino law,'' <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Bustamante </PERSON>, director of the Tijuana-based <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Border </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> and a leading critic of the immigration law, wrote in a recent newspaper column. The law's supporters say its intent is to help the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, `` regain control of its borders.'' <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Pilliod </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said in mid-May, however, that the `` law was not conceived to eliminate the movement of Mexican workers to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> needs these workers _ not only in the farm area, but also in the many service sectors such as food outlets, hotels, etc.,'' <PERSON> Pilliod </PERSON> said in a speech to the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. The law gave legal status to aliens who were able to prove they have lived in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> at least since 1982. In doing so, the alients ensured themselves of such rights as a minimum wage, health care, and education. Those who entered the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> after 1982 without legal documentation remain subject to deportation. <PERSON> Pilliod </PERSON> said, however, that predictions of mass deportations are unfair. `` Granted, the <ORGANIZATION> Border </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrol </ORGANIZATION> will continue to apprehend and return undocumented aliens to their home countries as always, but there are no plans for mass roundups,'' he said. <PERSON> Bustamante </PERSON> and others contend that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> can not reverse a 40-year trend with a law, because working in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, without documents if necessary, has become part of the lifestyle of thousands of Mexican families. Mexicans who go to work in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, even those taking the most menial jobs, can earn five to 10 times what they earn at home, where the minimum wage is the equivalent of about $ 3.45 a day. The Northern Border College estimates Mexicans working in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> generate about $ 1 billion in foreign income for <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. The Simpson-Rodino law gave illegal aliens who met certain requirements until May 4 to apply for legal status in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The majority of the more than 1.6 million people who applied are Mexican. But <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> immigration officials estimate that half or more of the 6 million to 7 million illegal aliens in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are Mexican. And nobody is reporting either a mass exodus or mass deportations of Mexicans since the May 4 deadline passed. `` Just as we predicted, based on investigations we do at the <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Border </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, nothing extraordinary has happened since May 5,'' <PERSON> Bustamante </PERSON> wrote in Excelsior of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Northern Border College offices from <LOCATION> Tijuana </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Matamoros </LOCATION> have been studying undocumented workers for three years. `` For them, the main factor that determines their willingness to run the risks is the labor market,'' <PERSON> Bustamante </PERSON> wrote. `` As long as they keep hiring, they will continue entering.'' A key intent of the Simpson-Rodino law is to stop the hiring of illegal aliens by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> employers. In the toughest provision of the law, employers who knowingly hire undocumented workers can receive stiff fines and other sanctions. Agricultural employers have until Dec. 1 before sanctioning begins. Meanwhile, the crossings continue. `` The majority of those who cross here are farm workers and they've been given special considerations,'' said Mayor <PERSON> Ernesto </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> <PERSON> Lira </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Reynosa </LOCATION>, south of <LOCATION> McAllen </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Trejo </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> said their city governments have programs to help returning undocumented migrants find work and housing but so far the program have not been necessary. `` There's a tremendous need for workers in <LOCATION> Juarez </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Trejo </PERSON> said, referring to the booming foreign-owned assembly operations that have created a demand for workers. `` There's a real war going on. One company offers a 50 percent discount on cafeteria food and another offers to feed them for free,'' <PERSON> Trejo </PERSON> said. `` We want people to come so they can go to work.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, June 9</NOTE>
