<FIRST>s a BC-APN--ExoticAnimals-Auction Adv12   05-31 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Exotic Animals-Auction, Adv 12,0697</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv12</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 12</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Exotic Animals</HEAD>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DELPHOS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As a flock of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> geese fly northward on their annual spring migration, their honking cries arouse dozens of their kind held in wire cages and orange crates under a tent at a western <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> auction. The tent also shelters badgers, wood ducks, black bears, swans, foxes, prairie dogs, cougars and a large female lion, who growls when someone gets too close. Beyond, in several newly built stalls and pens, is a veritable <PERSON> Noah </PERSON>'s ark of animals from all parts of the globe with foreign-sounding names such as aoudad, binturong, colobus, emu, ibex, guanacos, muntjac, oryx, rhea, watusi and zebu. Within hours, the fate of all will be set by an auctioneer's gavel, their destinations determined by the highest bidder Woods & amp; Waters Auction, held twice a year on the outskirts of this quiet little farm town, bills itself as the largest animal auction east of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. At its three-day sale in April, up to 8,000 animals, including birds and reptiles were sold to breeders, animal dealers, owners of game ranches, meat dealers and hobbyists with a penchant for a particular species, says <ORGANIZATION> Woods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Waters' owner <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Osting </PERSON>. For the most part, the customers were a reticent lot who shunned publicity and people trying to photograph animals were escorted off the premises by a security guard. Osting complains that the media have `` distorted'' their business by only photographing animals that are injured, kept in undersized cages or left in pens without food and water. `` The media want to stir up a story ... to shock readers,'' says <PERSON> Osting </PERSON>, 37, who's operated the family-run auction for five years. `` The only thing the media do when they print this gory stuff is to upset the humane society and the government, which is two people we do n't want upset at us.'' <PERSON> Osting </PERSON> says auctions help the wild and exotic animal industry because they bring the business of buying and selling animals out into public view. `` The intention of the auction is to clean up the business,'' he says. `` We're stepping out into the open, inviting regulation. We're saying, ` As long as you do n't regulate us out of the business, regulate us.''' Animal welfare people contend there are abuses. <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Maroukis </PERSON>, co-founder of Guardians of the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, an Ohio-based animal welfare rights group, says some cages were inadequate, as in the case of three bear cubs brought to the auction in a cardboard box, or too small. An adult black bear, she says, had cuts above his eyes from hitting his head against exposed metal edges when he'd try to stand, and some cages lacked food and water. Osting says some injuries do occur in the transport of animals to the auction. He adds, `` I've heard about foxes in too small a cage. He's at a three-day auction. He probably just came from real nice facilities and he'll probably go back to real nice facilities. After all, the animal is here for just three days. I think they make way too big an issue of it.'' <PERSON> Maroukis </PERSON> says, `` We've tried to work with the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>. They keep saying they have no jurisdiction, but if they do n't, who does?'' <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Castner </PERSON>, an inspector with the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>, says he saw some injuries, but none appeared life-threatening. Auctions are not regulated by the federal government, so inspectors for the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>, which oversees the transportation of animals, can only cite dealers or breeders whose animals appear to have been injured in transit, he says. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> has no control over privately owned animals. When asked about a flock of ostrich-like birds called rheas with bloodied legs, which <PERSON> Osting </PERSON> said probably were injured during transport, <PERSON> Castner </PERSON> replied that the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> also does n't regulate birds or reptiles. `` We ca n't do what we ca n't do. We only regulate the transportation of animals owned by dealers. That's it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 12</NOTE>
