<FIRST>s a BC-APN--PoliticalSeer Adv12-2Takes   05-31 0791</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Political Seer, Adv 12-2 Takes,0813</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv12</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 12</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 2 b&amp;w
photos.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ He's a seasoned practitioner of a relatively new, steadily booming and widely mistrusted profession in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, political consultant, did n't have an entry in the recent presidential primaries, but he has some definite views on why the winners won and the losers lost.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JULES LOH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> sat on the sidelines during the presidential primaries just ended, an unusual place for him in a hot election campaign. But there he sat, like a maestro in the audience, enjoying it, making notes. `` <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>,'' he says, reflecting on the campaign that one writer likened to a demolition derby, `` made some errors that hurt him, ruined him. So he lost, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> won. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> made few errors. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, on the other side, made few errors and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> won.'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> is a political consultant. He is a Democrat and works only for Democrats. He also is a seasoned practitioner of a relatively new, steadily booming and widely mistrusted profession in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. One popular perception of a political consultant is that of a modern-day <PERSON> Machiavelli </PERSON> who knows how to use electronic guile to manipulate a benighted electorate into mistaking form for substance. `` Nonsense,'' says <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, but it is obvious that he feels some of the skills that good political consultants do bring to a campaign were lacking in some of the races this spring. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>'s, for instance. The Republican senator, in <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>'s view, `` failed badly in organizing his campaign and developing his strategy He did n't appoint a strong team. He tried to run it all himself, and you ca n't do that.'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, he feels, would have made a more formidable opponent for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, on the other hand, put together a superb organization. The campaign carried the candidate. People who run a good campaign have the edge. `` <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>? <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> enters the fall campaign much less damaged than <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> was when he entered the'84 campaign. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is beholden to none of the special interest groups that <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON> was identified with. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> ran a simply fine campaign and it paid off.'' That, in short, <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> explains, is the job of the consultant: to give his candidate the edge. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> is 52, trim, with thinning gray hair and gray eyes. Whatever it is that he and his partner, <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, do to gain that edge they are apparently financially successful at it. Their well-appointed suite of offices overlook Central Park in one of <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>'s classiest midtown neighborhoods. In the past five years the <ORGANIZATION> Sawyer-Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> has doubled in size from 20 to 40, reflecting the meteoric rise in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> of the political consulting trade. They even have a trade association, and it has grown from 75 members 10 years ago to 650 today. Its president, <PERSON> Brad </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Leary </PERSON>, estimates that as many as 3,000 professionals in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> may be considered political consultants. <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> also represents a certain coming of age in the state of the art. The consulting fraternity had its origins in the advertising agencies summoned off <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION> by politicians, a practice roundly criticized in the 1968 book, `` The Selling of the President.'' In an ironic turnaround, <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> has expanded into the commercial field using techniques learned in political campaigns. He represents political candidates but also <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Apple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> and a dozen or so others, mainly those dealing with unexpected market changes and stiff competition. Political campaigns require his company's complete attention, <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> says, and mainly for that reason he sat out the primaries. `` We felt we would n't be able to give our commercial work all it deserves. If we do any political work this year it will be in the general election campaign.'' This election year an estimated $ 1.8 billion will be spent on politics with $ 500 million going for TV ads and $ 100 million for political consultants. For that kind of money, politicians must consider a consultants' service as something more than that of a debating coach. True, says <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, but hardly more sinister. `` A political campaign is like a war,'' says <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>. `` In a limited period of time you have to seize certain territory and hold it. It involves strategy and tactics. I work on both levels. `` The strategic team, about 10 people, are experts in various categories who determine how the candidate positions himself, how he contrasts himself with his opponents, which issues in the array of issues he believes in should be the key issues of the campaign.'' It was on the strategic level that <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> stumbled, according to <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>.
