<TEXT>
 `` Although he was very attractive, he began to be seen as opportunistic, changing his strategy. He ran as a defense candidate, then as a <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> candidate, then as a Jewish candidate, then as an economic populist candidate. `` It is very important to develop a single-minded, clear strategy. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> ended up with four or five different strategies which made it difficult for any one of them to be heard.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, for his part, <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> says, `` had such great strength in terms of money, credibility as a sitting governor, and such a first-rate campaign organization it was tough to compete against him.'' Of all the contending Democrats, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> emerged in <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>'s view as the most electable in November The tactical team's job, says <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>, is to figure out how to communicate a candidate's complex agenda, often in 30-second bites. `` Not just for TV spots; the nightly news is done in 30-second bites as well, or less. It's the nature of the business nowadays and it is n't all bad. You can express your position on some pretty complex issues in 30 seconds. `` For example, ` I oppose any further aid to the Contras.' Three seconds. ` If elected, I would ask <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to raise taxes 10 percent across the board to pay off our deficit.' Five seconds. `` The reasoning, the subtleties, come out in the formal debates and the print media. The electorate, in my opinion, has never been better informed about the position of the candidates on any issue and on his or her character.'' The tacticians' techniques, helped along by advanced technology including instant polling, videotape and <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION>, are where consultants show their battlefield savvy. `` You have to be able to take advantage of every opportunity, change your strategy on a moment's notice. Often it's a matter of timing.'' <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> demonstrated this last year in the <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> Democratic primary. <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>'s firm, like nearly all consultant firms, represents candidates of only one party. That race put him up against two others with similar reputations as heavy hitters among Democrats _ <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Squier </PERSON>, representing former Gov. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Y </PERSON>. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, the early favorite; and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Doak </PERSON> and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Shrum </PERSON>, representing then-Lt. Gov <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Beshear </PERSON>, the leading challenger. <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON>'s candidate was <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON>, a political unknown who registered only about 5 percent in the polls and was given little chance to improve. Little chance, that is, until the last two weeks of the campaign. `` Our two opponents began attacking each other with spots accusing each other of all sorts of things, and both advocated a tax increase. `` We discovered, through polls, that the voters disapproved of the negative campaigns they were waging against each other. So we moved in quickly. We said in effect that they were both right in their accusations, and we pushed for a lottery that we had advocated all along instead of new taxes. `` We had the overall strategy but we needed an opening to execute it and that gave us the opening. We exploited it. Call it guerrilla tactics.'' Whatever you call it, <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON> is now governor of <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>. Could any campaign consultant's tactics have saved <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>? `` Absolutely not. <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> was doomed as soon as the <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> episode came out. The most important thing people need to have is trust in their leader, trust in his judgement and his character. <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> sacrificed any trust the people could have had in him.'' <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> was lured into politics from a career as a producer of documentary films in 1970 when he was asked to do some film work for a candidate for governor of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. By 1974, he was into political consulting with both feet. His batting average has stayed at about .750, good enough for the big leagues -LRB- clients include four sitting senators and six governors -RRB- and for an expanding foreign trade as well. His clients also include <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>, president of the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s foreign minister, <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>. He has taken advantage of every technological advance, as have his colleagues, but in his view the most important electioneering change in the past decade has been not in sophisticated technology but the ever-growing sophistication of voters. `` Americans are exposed to commercial advertising more aggressive than ever before, to expanded news coverage because of satellite transmissions, and you just do n't manipulate them. You ca n't. `` TV is like an X-ray machine. Voters can see through false statements or sloganeering instead of substantive debate.
</TEXT>
