<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 12</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Gone Fishing-III</HEAD>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<HEAD>By JOHN KUGLIN</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TWIN BRIDGES, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four world-class trout rivers flow almost by the door of tiny R.L. <ORGANIZATION> Winston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rod </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, whose fly rods are recognized as among the best by hard-core equipment zealots. Money is no object for fly fishermen who seek out the Winston factory in this western <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> ranching town to test cast and maybe buy a $ 305 gossamer-tipped graphite wand or a $ 900 objet d'art in bamboo. `` It's a fact that fishermen sometimes get starry looks when they first touch one of our rods. It's affection,'' says <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>, who bought the established <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> rod maker in 1973 and moved it to <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>. `` A rod communicates with you,'' <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> says. `` When you wiggle a Winston rod it talks back to you with a good message.'' He implied there's little back talk from a mass-produced rod retailing for $ 19.99 in a discount store. `` Our goal is n't to provide everyone with a <ORGANIZATION> Winston </ORGANIZATION> rod, and everyone ca n't afford them,'' <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> says. So the factory makes fly rods at an artistic snail's pace of about 2,000 a year. <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> doubts his 59-year-old company will ever produce more than 3,000 rods a year. <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> and the other <ORGANIZATION> Winston </ORGANIZATION> employees do n't blink an eye if an angler wants to cast half a dozen fly rods on the lawn across the street, or buy one and substitute zebra wood for the standard walnut reel seat. <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON>, who guided for 14 years and fishes all over the world, might even accompany an eager angler to one of the nearby blue-ribbon trout rivers, the Big Hole, <LOCATION> Beaverhead </LOCATION>, Ruby or <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON>. He might even rig his favorite Winston, an 8-foot, 4-weight graphite. `` I like to fish small, dry flies. It's just perfect for that,'' <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> said. Winston has no fixed working days or hours for its five regular and seven part-time employees. `` If one of the trout streams beckons, they are free to go,'' <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> says. `` This provides them with the artistic freedom and inspiration they need to accomplish outstanding work.'' Winston's graphite rods are considered among the world's best. They are coated with a translucent kelly-green finish, and guides are wrapped with matching green thread. Winston wo n't wind a rod with different color thread for a customer or do anything else that `` makes no aesthetic sense or technical sense,'' <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> says. There are 89 models of Winston fly rods in 11 line sizes, three actions, three materials, from 5 -LCB- feet to 10 feet long. Once an angler buys a basic <ORGANIZATION> Winston </ORGANIZATION>, there's an enticing array of accouterments _ maybe a scrimshaw reel seat lovingly carved with a kingfisher, German silver reel banks, your name engraved on the rod. `` Our average customer has three to five of our rods and I've talked to people with a dozen,'' <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> says Almost all of <ORGANIZATION> Winston </ORGANIZATION>'s rods are graphite. The bamboo operation, supervised by partner <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Brackett </PERSON>, may turn out only 75 rods this year. <LOCATION> Tonkin </LOCATION> cane for the beautifully finished, classic rods comes from mainland <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Anglers may have to wait four to eight months for each custom-built rod, whose blemish-free bamboo strips are cut within a tolerance of one-thousandth of an inch. `` Only 5 percent of the bamboo we get goes into our rods,'' <PERSON> Brackett </PERSON> says `` We reject the rest.'' There are a lot of other good, expensive fly rods on the market from companies like <ORGANIZATION> Sage </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Teton </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> & amp; <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Loomis </PERSON> and Orvis. In fact, <ORGANIZATION> Winston </ORGANIZATION>'s graphite rod blanks are made on its own tapers by <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Loomis </PERSON>, a larger rod maker. Some fly rod companies offer `` futuristic materials,'' `` superior tapers,'' `` parabolic action,'' the latest `` breakthrough'' materials. <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> says a rod's design is more important than the material. `` It has to work for the type of fishing you do. At <ORGANIZATION> Winston </ORGANIZATION>, we do n't jump on every new material that comes along.'' <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> says that `` a lot of the people who build fly rods do n't fish enough You ca n't make great fly rods if you do n't use them a lot.'' He himself fishes a great deal, in part because `` you almost always fish in a place where you can rebuild your spirit. When I'm steelheading at times I almost wish a fish would n't come to my hook. When it comes to hooking trout, he believes in catching and releasing them. `` For the marvelous sport they give us,'' he says, `` they deserve our best treatment. You can turn the fish loose, not like hunting when you kill the animal.''
