<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 12</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-APN--Gone Fishing-III</HEAD>
<TEXT>

</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Wy. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fly fisherman does n't have to wear designer labels or own expensive gear to land the big ones. A trout with a brain the size of a pea does n't discriminate between <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bean </PERSON> and <PERSON> Levi </PERSON>'s. But serious anglers nearly all agree that collecting gadgets, perusing catalogs, and spending a snowy winter's day inside a fishing equipment store is part of the ritual. Like one great beauty surreptitiously ogling another's jewels, fly fishermen check out each other's tackle with discriminating eyes. There's a genteel snobbery in showing up on opening day along the <LOCATION> Beaver </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kill </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> sporting an antique <PERSON> Hiram </PERSON> <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> split <LOCATION> Tonkin </LOCATION> bamboo rod, a Wheatley fly box, a few Irresistibles tied by <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> or <PERSON> Elsie </PERSON> <PERSON> Darbee </PERSON>, and a faded but much-beloved red shirt that's survived being stuffed into duffles from <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, and back again by way of <LOCATION> Patagonia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>. In spite of sneaking suspicions that fish get spooked by red, fly fishermen love the color. Big Boy tomato red, American Beauty red, Fourth of July firecracker red. They wear it in crimson felt hats crimped at the brim, in scarlet shirts with elaborate flies embroidered on the pocket, in cherry bandanas tied around sunburned necks on hot days. To many, a splash of red is a talisman. `` CHOOSE ME!'' it says to the submerged fish with poor eyesight. `` See my bright hat? My bright suspenders? Of all the men mucking about in your watery world, I'm the one who will honor you the most. `` You, the big one there, if you pick me I will hang you over my fireplace, display you next to my office bar, maybe just let you go after I take your picture.'' Amid the brown, beige and khaki in a fly fisherman's kit bag there is usually a treasured piece of red. But an angler who wants the works will need a lot of green. If an emperor with no clothes walked into <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON>' Outdoor Shop in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyo. </LOCATION>, and got outfitted in time to be on the <LOCATION> Snake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> for lunch, this is what it could cost him: _ Insulated waders, $ 100 _ Leather boots, $ 85 _ Boot liner, $ 30 _ Fancy shirt, $ 44.95 _ Hat -LRB- preferably red -RRB-, $ 17 _ Fly fisherman's vest, $ 60 _ Graphite fly rod and reel, $ 80 to $ 200 and up _ Aluminum fly rod case, $ 40 _ Leader material, $ 18 to $ 32 _ Floating line, $ 10 to $ 30 _ Clippers, $ 4 _ Flies, $ 1.35 to $ 2.50 -LRB- need at least a dozen -RRB- _ Fly box, $ 14 _ Net -LRB- for optimists -RRB-, $ 14 to $ 30 _ Bamboo creel, $ 40 Then there are lessons: <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON>' instructors charge $ 40 to teach two people for two hours, while an all-day guided session on the Snake runs $ 200 for two, lunch included. If the novice fisherman is really hooked, dreams of bonefishing at Christmas Island begin to dance in his head. That adventure costs $ 1,700, not counting air fare to <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>. Meanwhile, fish are waiting in the Laxa I <LOCATION> Laxadalur </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> King </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salmon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, the Spey, the Dee, and the <ORGANIZATION> Tweed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rivers </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, the Bow River of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> ...
</TEXT>
