<NOTE>$adv12</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 12</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ In an affluent town on the <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, a new subdivision features antique homes that have been dismantled, rebuilt, and equipped with today's conveniences, such as burglar alarms and air conditioning. The price tag: $ 800,000 to $ 1.2 million.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MARK SEAVY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LYME, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An 18th century tavern with trees sprouting through the floorboards seemed destined to be razed in a firefighting drill until it was rescued by a couple of <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> developers who look to the past to find fancy homes for the future. Now it will be restored, with modern conveniences added, and become one of the dozen or so antique homes in an unusual 33-acre subdivision in this affluent town on the <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. Developers <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Broom </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Oberg </PERSON> are scouring the countryside for other vintage homes for the subdivision they call Sterling Meadows. The homes, when finished, will carry a modern price tag of $ 800,000 to $ 1.2 million. Broom and <PERSON> Oberg </PERSON> say they have n't tried to sell any yet. The former owner of the old tavern, they said, sold it to them rather than to the Salem fire department, which was going to burn it down for a firefighting drill. `` The problem is most old houses are accidents of geography,'' says <PERSON> Oberg </PERSON>, 32, of <ORGANIZATION> Essex </ORGANIZATION>, who left a career in finance more than two years ago to become a developer. `` What used to be a convenient location on the main road is now a busy commercial district with a lot of traffic going by and they end up being torn down for a new office building, a new apartment building or one thing or another.'' <PERSON> Oberg </PERSON> says the partnership has purchased five buildings for its subdivision and is still looking for others to fill the seven other lots. Four buildings are now being reconstructed at the site. A concrete foundation is ready for a federal-style home from <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> that dates to around 1800. They expect to complete the development in about three years. The first step is saving the buildings, a painstaking task. The partnership has paid $ 5,000 to $ 20,000 for the relics and spends five to six weeks dismantling them. With a crew of carpenters supplied by <ORGANIZATION> Broom </ORGANIZATION>'s other business, H.B. <ORGANIZATION> Broom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housewright </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a restoration company, nearly everything is saved from frame and windows to mantels and floorboards. Broom and <PERSON> Oberg </PERSON> remain true to each building's original design _ which means, for example, rebuilding six fireplaces in the former <LOCATION> Salem </LOCATION> tavern _ but the structures are outfitted with modern conveniences such as burglar alarm systems and central air conditioning. `` When we rebuild these houses, we're using all the original features and restoring the house as best we can, but we're not building museums,'' says <ORGANIZATION> Broom </ORGANIZATION>, 44, of Lyme, whose office is in a building built in 1770 to serve as a general store for steamships on the <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and the ferry that to this day shuttles between <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Hadlyme </LOCATION>. `` We're building houses that are practical to live in.'' The interiors are slightly modified with ells to accommodate the modern trappings of kitchens and bathrooms. Otherwise the homes are original, right down to the slightly off-center front doors on some. They plan to pave the winding road leading to the development and line it with sugar maples, stone walls and picket fences. Antique lampposts will be re-created, based on a design borrowed from <LOCATION> Deerfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. `` We're trying to create the perfect <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> environment,'' <PERSON> Oberg </PERSON> says. `` We try not to change the details at all and take small liberties with the ells.'' <PERSON> Oberg </PERSON> is quick to dispel notions that the developers are trying to imitate <LOCATION> Sturbridge </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Williamsburg </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>. He says they confine their efforts to homes built between 1700 and 1815 and lean toward those in formal styles, such as federal or Georgian. Similar but smaller subdivisions of five relocated historic homes each are located in rural <LOCATION> Killingworth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, and in <LOCATION> Waitsfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vt. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Oberg </PERSON> criticizes the so-called `` purist'' approach to restoration, which is light on modern conveniences and heavy on dark interior colors `` The result when a so-called purist restores a house is that the houses tend to be dark and use dark colors and that is not quite what everybody would like,'' he says. The Sterling Meadows development has met the approval of town officials, who are committed to 2 - and 3-acre zoning in order to preserve the town's atmosphere About 1,910 people live in Lyme's 33 square miles. Homeowners include former <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lindsay </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, District Attorney <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Holtzman </PERSON>. `` If you're gon na have development of that nature, you could do no better than <PERSON> Skip </PERSON> <PERSON> Broom </PERSON>,'' says Lyme First Selectman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeomans </PERSON>, referring to Broom by his nickname. `` They're as good as any and better than most.'' <PERSON> Oberg </PERSON> and Broom formed their partnership 2 -LCB- years ago after <PERSON> Oberg </PERSON> bought a tract of land alongside a 12-acre parcel Broom already owned. <PERSON> Oberg </PERSON> says he has had a lifelong interest in antique homes while Broom quit a job as an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> about 15 years ago to start his restoration business. `` I had a piece of land I bought as a investment and I always wanted to put antique houses on it,'' says <ORGANIZATION> Broom </ORGANIZATION>, whose company has restored about 80 homes. `` Oddly enough, he wanted to do the same thing.''
</TEXT>
