<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Jacknifed'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Beauvoir </PERSON> In his 26 years, <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Beauvoir </PERSON> has packed wildly diverse experiences onto his musical resume, including stints with the doo-wop Flamingoes, shock punkers Plasmatics and <PERSON> Little </PERSON> <PERSON> Steven </PERSON>'s political Disciples of Soul Even <PERSON> Beauvoir </PERSON>'s appearance paints him as a musical maverick with the wild, white Mohawk he's sported for many years. This personal history hardly prepares a listener for the musical conservatism of `` Jacknifed,'' <PERSON> Beauvoir </PERSON>'s second solo album. `` Jacknifed'' is a soulful contemporary dance album, probably the first to be influenced by the success of <PERSON> Terence </PERSON> <PERSON> Trent </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Arby </PERSON>. The keyboards and guitars simmer but do n't sizzle, leaving room for <PERSON> Beauvoir </PERSON>'s songs to stretch and breathe. Both lyrically and musically, <PERSON> Beauvoir </PERSON> has the smarts to avoid tired cliches. He also avoids anything distinctive that will get his songs noticed. `` Jacknifed'' is the type of record that would float by on the radio without causing any real reaction. Many of the songs, such as `` Standing on My Own Two Feet'' and `` Find My Way Home'' tread familiar themes of a solitary man trying to find his way in a hostile world. <PERSON> Beauvoir </PERSON>, who wrote and produced the album along with playing most of the instruments, has obvious talent. He's still looking for the best way to show the world.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` The Story of the Clash, Vol. 1'' -LRB- Epic -RRB- _ The Clash They once advertised themselves as `` the only band that matters.'' One member of the group was fired for political reasons. The band's first hit single was n't even listed on the cover of the `` London Calling'' album. Who are the Clash? This once-important band dropped so quickly from the public consciousness it almost seems like they've become a trivia question. The time is ripe for a retrospective, and <ORGANIZATION> Epic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION> has obliged with the two-record `` The Story of the Clash, Vol. 1.'' Liking or hating the Clash during their brief prime in the late 1970s and early'80s was almost a political statement in itself. Punk rock set up two hostile camps, one that loved the brash young toughs challenging the musical establishment, the other threatened by them. The band's aggressive working-class politics also left little room for neutrality. This often obscured the simple fact the Clash was a terrific rock band, one that quickly grew past the limitations of primitive punk but never lost the creative spark that went with it. The retrospective, while put together rather haphazardly, makes that point abundantly clear. The set cuts a wide swath through the glorious trash rock of `` Should I Stay or Should I Go,'' the Motown tribute `` Train in Vain,'' the mainstream rock crunch of `` <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> Calling,'' the inspirational near ballad `` Stay Free'' and the adrenalin kick of `` <PERSON> Janie </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>.'' Oddly, the record only includes two cuts from the sprawling three-record `` Sandinista.'' Cuts such as the title track or `` Charlie Do n't Surf'' would have been better than the subpar `` Straight to Hell'' included here from `` Combat Rock.'' The record does n't run chronologically. Side 3 is a tribute to the Clash's infancy and side one sounds like a prototype for <PERSON> Mick </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>' subsequent Big Audio Dynamite group, but the sequencing often seems random. If not, it would have been preferable to hear the band explain it through retrospective liner notes, instead of the rambling reminiscence of a roadie included here. Still, this is an illuminating trip through a time capsule and would make an especially worthy purchase for those who missed the Clash the first time around.
</TEXT>
