<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Cocaine-Heart Adv02   05-31 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Cocaine-Heart, Adv 02,0537</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, June 2, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Electrical Disturbances In Heart Blamed For Cocaine-Induced Deaths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Seemingly healthy cocaine users who drop dead may be victims of the drug's interference with the heart's electrical activity Researchers <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Avakian </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Bracken </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> injected rats and rabbits dosages equivalent to a 160-pound chronic abuser who smokes or injects 1.5 grams or `` snorts'' 3 grams of cocaine a day. Their studies suggest that cocaine causes sudden cardiac death by triggering abnormal heart rhythms, said <PERSON> Avakian </PERSON>, a physiologist-pharmacologist. Many cocaine-induced arrhythmias are temporary but others, called ventricular arrhythmias, kill because they halt the heart's ability to pump. The findings also suggest that while long-term daily cocaine users develop tolerance to the drug's effects on the heart, they are particularly susceptible to sudden death if they stop taking it and then resume. `` Cocaine is not always available, so one might not take it for one or two days,'' <PERSON> Avakian </PERSON> said. `` A brief withdrawal of one or two days can put a user at much more risk, especially during a stress situation like exercise.'' The risk of death from injecting cocaine or smoking its `` free-base'' or `` crack'' forms is particularly high because much more is absorbed into blood, where it can directly affect the heart, he said. <PERSON> Avakian </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bracken </PERSON>, a physiologist, and colleagues set out to explain such deaths as those in 1986 of <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Maryland </ORGANIZATION> basketball star <PERSON> Len </PERSON> <PERSON> Bias </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Cleveland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Browns </ORGANIZATION> football player <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>. As of early 1987, there had been eight such deaths among 49 documented cases of cocaine-induced heart trouble, according to research by Dr. <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Isner </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Avakian </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bracken </PERSON>, who outlined their work at a <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Societies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Experimental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Biology </ORGANIZATION> meeting last month, used 40 rabbits and 300 rats. Some received no cocaine; others got daily doses for eight weeks. Some of the animals were killed 30 minutes after the last injection. Others were killed two days later to simulate withdrawal from cocaine. The hearts were removed and kept pumping in laboratory containers filled with a blood substitute while researchers monitored heart electrical activity, blood flow through coronary arteries, and heart rate, rhythm and contractions. Then the researchers added cocaine alone or cocaine and adrenalin to the blood substitute bathing the hearts. Adrenalin normally is produced by the body during exercise or other physical or emotional stress. Hearts from animals that got cocaine before they were killed showed more disruption of electrical impulse transmission, probably because cocaine acts as a local anesthetic, <PERSON> Avakian </PERSON> said. The studies also showed chronic cocaine use, when combined with adrenalin, constricts coronary arteries, reducing blood flow to the heart. The combination of cocaine-induced arrythmias and the decreased blood flow increases the odds of sudden death, he said. Hearts from animals withdrawn from cocaine for two days were supersensitive to adrenalin and cocaine, suggesting sudden death is more likely in chronic abusers who stop and start again, particularly if they exercise or are otherwise stressed.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for June 2</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880531-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-88 1308EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Explorations-Summary Adv02   05-31 0846</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Explorations-Summary, Adv 02,0868</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, June 02, and thereafter</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: This is the Explorations package for June 2 in summary form.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For a glimpse of elementary science the way it should be taught, but seldom is, turn right after the sea lions at the <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> Zoo. There, in makeshift classrooms ripe with the sounds and smells of ferrets, falcons, porcupines and snakes, 30,000 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> elementary schoolchildren a year get a few hours to experience science the way scientists do: by touching, observing and experimenting. The classes, conducted by the zoo, are among 13 local science education programs cited as exemplary in a new <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> publication, `` Science Education Programs That Work.'' For about $ 300 to $ 400 per class, the program offers science training and materials for teachers, and three to six class visits to the zoo for students in grades Kindergarten through 6. But the program is a rare bright spot in an otherwise dismal landscape of elementary school science around the country. Critics from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Education Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> down say science as taught in many elementary schools replaces children's innate fascination with nature's wonders with mind-deadening facts and predictable textbook exercises masquerading as `` experiments.'' Experts cite several problems: teacher training that often bypasses or plays down science, school systems that stress reading and math scores and consider science a frill by comparison, failure by schools to make use of local resources like planetariums and zoos, and overreliance on textbooks that rarely offer genuine experimentation or grounding in scientific method. The sorry state of elementary science instruction is the often overlooked reason that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> students do so poorly in science later on in school compared with students in other industrialized countries. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> elementary and high school students, especially girls, know less about science than their counterparts did in 1970, according to a study released this year by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> for the Evaluation of Educational Achievement of how students in 24 nations perform in science. According to a report funded by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> last November, the nation's Kindergarten-through-third graders spend an average of 19 minutes per day on science, increasing to 38 minutes in grades 4-6, and only half the Kindergarten-through-third graders get hands-on materials or lab work. And in a recent critique of nine commonly used elementary science texts, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> <PERSON> Nagel </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Materials </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>, private textbook consultants in <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, concluded that programs relying on such texts `` teach students to think of science mainly as a collection of conclusions to be memorized.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>IOWA CITY, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A glowing, green two-inch-high stick figure reproducing the long jump or triple jump form of a <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> or <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Banks </PERSON> is helping <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s elite athletes go to great lengths. The figure on the screen in <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Hay </PERSON>'s biomechanics laboratory at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> is a digital representation of movie film shot at 100 frames per second. It is a computerized projection of horizontal and vertical acceleration, angle of takeoff and body position in the air. `` We're trying to find the answers to some basic questions about jumping,'' <PERSON> Hay </PERSON> said. `` We do a lengthy series of statistical analyses of the data. Out of that we put together a 40 - to 50-page report with a summary of findings and what we think the athlete needs in terms of practice, what the coach and athlete might direct their attention to. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON>, 1988 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Olympic long and triple jump coach, and a coach at <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> for 23 years, said <PERSON> Hay </PERSON>'s research, funded by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Olympic Committee elite athlete project, is prized by jumpers `` They have confidence in him,'' the Olympic coach said. `` Before, we gathered all this data but did n't know what to do with it. We're now giving the athlete and coach direct feedback. Hay's really done a good job of that.
</TEXT>
