<HEAD>Many Smokers Sabotage Benefit of Ultra-Low-Tar Cigarettes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If your ultra-low-tar cigarette tastes better than you expect, you may not be smoking it right _ and may be getting higher doses of tar _ say researchers who studied discarded cigarette butts. Fifty-eight percent of 135 cigarette filters found in ash trays at a shopping mall showed evidence that smokers had at least partially blocked the cigarette's air vents with their lips or fingers, the researchers report. Ultra-low-tar cigarettes depend on those vents to dilute cigarette smoke and reduce the yield of tar. Blocking them raises the tar a smoker consumes, the researchers wrote in June's <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>. `` Smokers block vents to enhance smoking satisfaction. Some do not realize that better taste means increased tar, nicotine and carbon monoxide, thinking that there are special low-tar tobaccos in the cigarette; other smokers are unaware of blocking the vents,'' they wrote, citing previous research. `` Smokers of low-tar cigarettes ... need to be told that, if they do not miss their high-yield cigarette smoke, it may not really have gone away,'' wrote <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Kozlowski </PERSON>, <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Pope </PERSON> and <PERSON> Joann </PERSON> <PERSON> Lux </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Addiction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION>. Their study focused on characteristic tar stains created by vent-blocking. Evidence of extreme blocking appeared in 19 percent, with lesser blockage in 39 percent.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>40 Percent of Women In Study Said No to Sex But Meant Yes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly 40 percent of college coeds in a study report they had said `` no'' to sex when they meant `` yes,'' but researchers say that since most of the women meant what they said, men should n't ignore such refusals. About a third of the women said they had offered this token resistance only once, and 46 percent had used it only two to five times. But since most women reported never offering such resistance, the result `` does not mean that men can safely ignore women's refusals When a woman says no, chances are that she means it ... -LRB- and -RRB- regardless of the incidence of token resistance, if the woman means no and the man persists, it is rape,'' wrote <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> A & amp; M <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> researchers <PERSON> Charlene </PERSON> <PERSON> Muehlenhard </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollabaugh </PERSON>. They gave an anonymous questionnaire to 610 female students, average age 19, at their school. Results appear in the May issue of the Journal of Personality and Social Psychology. Twenty-three percent of the 240 coeds who offred token resistance said manipulative reasons, such as game-playing, anger with the man or desire to be in control, were at least moderately important reasons for resisting. About an equal percentage cited such reasons as fear of appearing promiscuous, fear of catching disease, or uncertainty about their partner's feelings.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Anti-parasite Drug Being Tested In Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Suramin, a drug long used to treat parasite infections, is being tested for the first time as a way to attack cancer. Doctors from the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> used it on 10 people with advanced, spreading cases of cancer of the adrenal gland. Although it did not cure their disease, suramin seemed to slow the cancer by blocking body chemicals known as growth factors. Tumors need these substances to promote their own growth. `` We believe that suramin is the first of a class of growth factor-inhibiting drugs,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Cy </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stein </PERSON>. `` Even if it is not the ideal drug, it is helping us to learn what scheme is necessary to stop tumors from growing by inhibiting their growth factors.'' In two of the patients, tumors were reduced by more than 50 percent, while those in two others decreased by 25 to 50 percent. The disease remained stable in three while progressing in three. <PERSON> Stein </PERSON> said that once the drug was stopped, the cancer recurred rapidly. Doctors are now considering trying suramin on other forms of cancer and combining it with standard chemotherapy drugs. The most serious side effect was nerve damage, which doctors said may limit how long people can stay on suramin. The results were reported at a recent meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clinical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oncology </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Drug-Coated Beads Slow Liver Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tiny beads coated with cancer-killing drugs are being tested to slow progression of liver cancer, a uniformly fatal disease. The treatment, called chemoembolization, uses beads of starch that have been treated with chemotherapy medicines to temporarily dam up the hepatic artery, the major artery that supplies the liver. This deprives the tumor of blood while putting it in contact with drugs. Doctors say the combination can stop the growth of the tumor and sometimes shrink it. In a few days, the starch is absorbed into the body, and blood flow resumes. During the temporary blockade, the liver continues to receive blood through the portal vein. Among 30 patients who received the experimental treatment at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, two had dramatic responses. One had no recurrence of the tumor for 16 months and the other for over two years. In about three-quarters, the tumor shrank significantly or temporarily stopped growing. Dr. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Venook </PERSON>, who outlined the results at a recent <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clinical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oncology </ORGANIZATION> meeting, said the new treatment provides temporary relief from the spread of the disease but is not a cure. `` It is better than anything else around,'' he said. `` Some patients have shown remarkable improvement, but the therapy needs further development.''
</TEXT>
