<HEAD>Trade Minister Appeals For Increase In Imports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONIKA JAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government today urged leading corporations to boost imports of manufactured goods in an effort to reduce <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s massive trade surplus In a meeting with representatives of 151 firms, Minister of <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Hajime </PERSON> <PERSON> Tamura </PERSON> requested the companies `` make further efforts to expand the increase of foreign imports,'' said <PERSON> Atsushi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kawashima </PERSON>, director of the import division of <ORGANIZATION> MITI </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trading partners have called on the country to curtail exports and promote imports in an effort to slash its heavy global trade surplus. <PERSON> Kawashima </PERSON> said imports of manufactured goods rose from $ 55.2 billion in fiscal 1986 to $ 73.9 billion in fiscal 1987, fueled mainly by the rapid appreciation of the Japanese yen. Since September 1985, the yen has risen by more than 100 percent against the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar. The higher value of the yen has made Japanese products more expensive overseas, but has tended to increase the import purchasing power of Japanese. The companies should `` take advantage of the ... yen's appreciation to the greatest extent,'' <PERSON> Kawashima </PERSON> quoted <PERSON> Tamura </PERSON> as telling the firms' representatives during the one-hour meeting at the ministry According to <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> figures, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade surplus last fiscal year totaled $ 76.01 billion, down from $ 89.74 billion in fiscal 1986. The decrease was the first in six years. <PERSON> Kawashima </PERSON> said the government hopes to reduce the trade surplus by another $ 11 billion this fiscal year, which ends next March 31. He said the call for more imports also was made by ministry officials to 151 other firms for a total of 302 companies which represent the core of the Japanese economy. The corporations, including big trading houses such as <ORGANIZATION> Mitsui </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Sumitomo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Itoh </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, were responsible for 60 percent of the total fiscal 1987 import figure, he said. The companies as a group increased their imports last year by 38 percent and hope to increase them by a further 17 percent in fiscal 1988, he said. <PERSON> Kawashima </PERSON> said <PERSON> Tamura </PERSON> also requested the companies to report at the end of the first half of fiscal 1988 on the results of their import expansion programs.
</TEXT>
