<FIRST>u f PM-HomeSales     05-31 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Home Sales,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>New, Single-Family Home Sales Up 4 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sales of new, single-family homes rose 4 percent in April to the highest level in a year, the government said today. In a joint release, the departments of Commerce and of Housing and <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> said new single-family homes were sold at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of of 679,000 last month, up from the March pace of 653,000. It was the third consecutive monthly increase and the highest level since new homes were sold at a rate of 728,000 in April 1987. Despite the recent increases, sales for the first four months of this year are still 9 percent below the same period of 1987, when mortgage interest rates hit nine-year lows. The April climb came atop a modest 1.2 percent rise in March and a whopping 11.4 percent rise in February. However, the increases followed three consecutive declines _ in November, December and January _ which analysts at the time said were caused by the October stock market crash. Some economists had feared that the downturn in housing sales signaled a recession, but since then the economy has proved to be robust and the housing sector has more than recovered. Most analysts, though, believe that sales levels of the last few months will drop by the fall as rising mortgage interest rates push up the monthly cost of owning a home and discourage buyers. Rates on 30-year, fixed-rate conventional mortgages averaged 10.58 percent last week, more than half a percentage point higher than levels in February and March. The increase in sales of new homes was accompanied by a rise in prices. The median, or mid-point, price of new homes was $ 110,500 in April, up 3.3 percent from March. The average price of a new home rose 4.2 percent in April. However, the increases came after two consecutive monthly price declines, which analysts had said reflected the re-entry into the market of first-time home buyers, who normally purchase less expensive homes. Sales increased in all regions of the country in April. They were up 5.9 percent in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, 5.5 percent in the West, 2.9 percent in the South and 2.8 percent in the Northeast. In a separate report last week, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION> said sales of existing homes increased 4.5 percent in April after identical increases of 2.5 percent in March and February.
</TEXT>
