<SECOND>AM-Construction Contracts,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Construction Contracts Fall In April</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release after 6:30 p.m. EDT; time set by source</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Contracting for new construction projects declined 6 percent in April from the previous month, extending a downward slide that began last fall, a report released Tuesday said. The survey, by the F.W. Dodge Division of <ORGANIZATION> McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, estimated the annualized value of all newly started construction projects in April at $ 226.97 billion, compared with $ 242.38 billion in March. F.W. <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> said its seasonally adjusted index of construction contracting fell to 144 in April from 154 in March, a three-month low. The index is based on a level of 100 for 1982. The April drop was the latest in a series of industrywide setbacks that began early last fall, when building activity was 20 percent above its current level. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>, vice president and chief economist for F.W. Dodge, said high vacancy rates in commercial properties, particularly offices and apartments, were responsible in reversing the industry's five-year upswing. He said the situation was not expected to improve in the near term. `` The export boom which is pumping up the 1988 economy is n't much help to the construction industry, and could even prove troublesome,'' <PERSON> Christie </PERSON> said `` As economic activity heats up, rising interest rates imply still lower building later in the year.'' Contracting for residential buildings slid 7 percent in April to an annualized value of $ 109.4 billion, due largely to a decline in apartment construciton, according to the report. April contracts for non-residential building was off 5 percent to $ 76.8 billion from $ 80.86 billion. The value of non-building contracts, which include public works and utility projects, fell 6 percent to $ 40.81 billion from $ 43.59 billion, the report said.
