 Stock prices shot up Tuesday in a post-holiday weekend buying spree that pushed up the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average nearly 75 points. Analysts could not point to any specific developments to account for the rally, but they said sentiment seemed to have grown that interest rates are near a peak for the time being. Anxiety over rising interest rates had weighed heavily on the market in recent weeks. Prices began rising as soon as trading resumed after the three-day break for the Memorial Day holiday and gathered momentum as the day wore on. The Dow industrials rose 74.68 points to close at 2,031.12. That was the widely followed barometer's best gain since a 76.42 rise on Jan. 4 and the sixth biggest increase ever. Four stocks rose in price for every one that fell on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The pace of trading has slowed in recent weeks as investors have shown little conviction on the implications of continuing strength in the economy. While a strong economy could be a boon for corporate profits, some investors have worried that the expanding economy could also reignite inflation. But analysts said Tuesday that traders were heartened the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> had not increased the interest rate it charges on loans to financial institutions. There had been speculation it would do so after the markets closed Friday.
