 against a backdrop of rising commodity prices, including gold, and a drop in the yield of long-term government bonds. The dollar closed in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> at 124.80 Japanese yen, down from Monday's 124.98 yen. In later <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> trading it rose to 125.50 yen, and in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 125.235 yen, up from 124.925 late Friday. The dollar also gained against the British pound in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, where it was quoted late Tuesday at $ 1.8385, compared with $ 1.8478 in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> on Monday and $ 1.8570 in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> late Friday. <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> financial markets also were closed Monday for a national holiday. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the pound fetched $ 1.8353 Tuesday, compared with $ 1.85735 late Friday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Friday, included: 1.73265 West German marks, up from 1.7178; 1.44525 Swiss francs, up from 1.4358; 5.8300 French francs, up from 5.7770; 1,284.00 Italian lire, up from 1,273.13; and 1.2333 Canadian dollars, down from 1.23915. Late dollar rates in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, compared with late Monday's rates, included: 1.7292 West German marks, up from 1.7270; 1.4437 Swiss francs, up from 1.4415; 5.8215 French francs, up from 5.8025; 1.9333 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9335; 1,279.95 Italian lire, down from 1,280.00; and 1.2357 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2378. Gold prices around the world got a boost from big gains in the platinum market. The late bid price in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> was $ 454.80 a troy ounce, up from late Friday's $ 452. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold closed at a bid $ 455, up from late Monday's $ 452.50. Earlier, gold closed in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> at a bid of $ 455.80, up from $ 454.31. On the <ORGANIZATION> New <