<HEAD>Stocks Rally in Big Post-Holiday Gain</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock traders celebrated their return from the three-day Memorial holiday on Tuesday with a buying spree that pushed the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average to its second biggest gain of the year. Analysts said there was no single piece of news to account for the surge, which came on the heaviest daily volume since late January, but they said the market's pessimism had grown so pervasive that a rebound was inevitable. `` Sometimes it's better just to enjoy and not analyze things like this,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Manley </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a portfolio strategist for <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` It's been a bad May.'' The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which fell 10.31 points last Friday, climbed 74.68 to 2,031.12, its highest level since it closed at 2,036.31 on May 4. It was the biggest one-day advance in the market's most widely-followed index since a 76.42-point gain on Jan. 4, the first trading day of the year, and the sixth biggest rise ever. The gain in the Dow Jones industrials was so strong that a voluntary limit on computerized program trading was triggered when the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION>'s rise swept past 50 points in the last hour of trading. But even after the so-called `` collar'' went into effect for the rest of the day, the blue-chip average extended its gain. It was the third time the collar had gone into effect since it was adopted in the aftermath of the Oct. 19 market crash in a bid to curb market volatility. Gainers outpaced losers by nearly 4 to 1 in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed stocks, with 1,211 up, 333 down and 401 unchanged. Volume on the floor of the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> came to 247.61 million shares, up from 133.59 million in the previous session and the highest since 275.25 million shares were traded there on Jan. 25. Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled 271.55 million shares. The pace of trading has been slow in recent weeks as traders weighed the implications of continuing strength in the economy. While a strong economy could bode well for corporate profits, some investors worried that an expanding economy could also reignite inflation. While analysts were unable to pinpoint why the market surged Tuesday, they said several factors may have contributed to the big gain. They cited stability in the dollar and the bond market's resilience in the face of a new surge in commodity futures prices They also cited relief that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> had failed to boost its discount rate _ its interest charge on loans to financial institutions _ as some feared it would after the markets closed last week. <PERSON> Eldon </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grimm </PERSON>, a senior vice president at the brokerage Birr, <ORGANIZATION> Wilson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said there is `` an enormous amount of cash around out of the market'' due to wariness in the wake of last October's crash. `` But every time we get a little rally going, people think they will miss the boat and buy something,'' he said. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> DaPuzzo </PERSON>, manager of retail equity trading for <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said the warm weather over the holiday may have prompted investors to reevaluate the market's prospects and put some cash to work. `` You've got to start a summer rally sometime, and Memorial Day is usually the threshold to the summer,'' he said. Two utility stocks that have a deadline soon for dividend eligibility accounted for more than a third of the trading activity on the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Edison </LOCATION> was up -LRB- at 18 -RCB- on volume of 55.7 million shares, while <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> rose ~ to 23 ~ on volume of 36.8 million shares Among the blue chip issues, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> rose 1 -LRB- to 27 -LRB-, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> rose 2 to 42, <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> rose 4 -LCB- to 112 -LCB- and <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> rose 1 -LCB- to 42. <PERSON> Macmillan </PERSON> fell 2 \ to 70 \ after proposing to spin off its information services company and pay a special dividend to its <ORGANIZATION> Essex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> rose 10 -RCB- to 27 ~ after receiving an offer of $ 24 a share for 61 percent of its stock from a unit of <ORGANIZATION> Gurit-Heberlein </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION> According to <ORGANIZATION> Wilshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION>' index of more than 5,000 actively-traded stocks, the market rose $ 69.66 billion, or 2.75 percent, in value. The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> index rose 4.38 to 148.04. <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's industrial index rose 10.12 to 302.67, and <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; P's 500-stock composite index was up 8.74 at 262.16. At the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the market value index rose 3.69 to 294.19. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market closed at 370.34, up 3.68.
