<FIRST>u f AM-Boeing-737Incidents     05-31 0821</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boeing-737 Incidents,0845</SECOND>
<HEAD>Similarities Between Far Eastern, Aloha Planes Only Coincidence,
Boeing Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to CORRECT cycle designator.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It is only coincidence that a Taiwanese <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 that disintegrated and crashed in 1981 and an <ORGANIZATION> Aloha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> 737 that lost part of its fuselage over <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> in April were built one after the other, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> officials said Tuesday. On April 28, a 20-foot section of the Aloha jet's forward upper fuselage ripped away at 24,000 feet. A flight attendant fell to her death and 61 passengers were injured, but the flight crew landed the plane safely. The Aloha plane was the 152nd 737-200 produced by <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>. Plane No. 151 was a <ORGANIZATION> Far </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> jet that disintegrated and exploded at 22,000 feet over central <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> on Aug. 22, 1981, killing all 110 people on board. The cause of the <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> accident is still under investigation. However, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> has ordered <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines flying older 737s to reinspect the aircraft. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> believes the Far Eastern crash was caused by maintenance problems, spokesman <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Gamble </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airplanes </ORGANIZATION> said. Any similarities between that crash and the <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> accident are `` a series of coincidences,'' <PERSON> Gamble </PERSON> said. At the time of the planes' manufacture in 1969, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> was turning out between two and three 737s a month, <PERSON> Gamble </PERSON> said. He said he knew of no other problems involving 737s made around that time. In an article Tuesday in the Wall Street Journal, <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Cosgrove </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airplanes </ORGANIZATION> vice president and general manager for engineering, also said the consecutive aircraft numbers were coincidence. <PERSON> Cosgrove </PERSON> said that while both accidents involved a section of the fuselage that <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> refers to as `` Section 43,'' there was nothing inherently wrong with that portion of the aircraft. <PERSON> Cosgrove </PERSON> told the Journal the Far Eastern 737 repeatedly was used to ship fish in open containers, and corrosive salt water may have gotten into the cargo hold. The newspaper said Far Eastern officials denied that charge and said fish were shipped only in non-leaking containers. <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Benson </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, said Tuesday <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> investigators also believe leaking salt water from fish shipments was the cause of the Far Eastern jet's corrosion. Gamble said <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> had issued a series of service bulletins on older 737s, including one in March 1978 recommending aircraft owners make additional inspections of fuselage skins for possible corrosion. On July 1, 1981, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> issued an airworthiness directive requiring <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carriers to inspect older 737s. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> had supplied kits to airlines to allow them to replace corroded skin on planes, <PERSON> Gamble </PERSON> said. A kit was delivered to Far Eastern in April 1980, `` which means they had those in their spare parts inventory considerably before that crash,'' but apparently was never used on the plane, he said. <PERSON> Cosgrove </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, to attend a conference on problems with aging aircraft and was not available for comment Tuesday, <PERSON> Gamble </PERSON> said. The three-day conference was called by the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> after the <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> incident to study safety issues involving older aircraft. <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, director of public relations for <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airplanes </ORGANIZATION>, noted the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> also issued an airworthiness directive following the Far Eastern crash requiring inspections of 737 cargo holds. <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Goto </PERSON>, spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Aloha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, said that as a result of the directive, <PERSON> Aloha </PERSON> made extensive repairs in 1983 to the 737 subsequently involved in the April incident. He said the work done on the wings and lower portion of the plane might have helped it stay together long enough to land. The twin-engine 737, which entered service in 1968, is the world's most popular commercial aircraft, with more than 2,000 ordered in five different models. One of the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> airworthiness directives issued after the <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> accident focuses on early models of 737s in which <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> used a cold-bonding process, in which structural parts of the fuselage were laminated together using an adhesive that cured at room temperature. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said he found a number of differences between the two accidents. The Far Eastern plane, for example, was 12 years old and had approximately 33,000 landings, while the <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> jet was 20 years old and had about 90,000 landings. `` As best we know,'' the Far Eastern accident was caused by corrosion in the plane's cargo hold, while the <LOCATION> Aloha </LOCATION> accident involved the top of the plane, he said. `` But again, the appropriate thing is to see what the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> conclude before drawing all these analogies and comparisons,'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> issues service bulletins on its aircraft to customers whenever it learns of a problem or the potential for one. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> and other appropriate regulatory agencies also are notified, he said. He said the <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> believes the issues presented in the Far Eastern case `` were known and addressed and adequately so'' by the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> airworthiness directive.
