<HEAD>Freddie Mac Announces Big Jump in Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mortgage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday that earnings rose 50 percent to a record $ 93 million in the first three months of this year. The corporation, known as <ORGANIZATION> Freddie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION>, buys mortgages and repackages them into securities for sales to investors. Corporation officials attributed the earnings increase to a widening in the difference between what it pays to the investors and what it receives from the mortgages. Also, income taxes were reported at a lower rate because of a drop in the corporate tax rate. For the first quarter, net income was $ 93 million, or $ 5.65 per share of preferred stock and $ 83.06 per share of common stock, up from $ 62 billion, or $ 3.81 per share of preferred stock and $ 52.31 per share of common stock, for the same period in 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Freddie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mac </ORGANIZATION> was created by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1970 to increase the amount of money available for mortgages. Its preferred stock is owned by 3,000 savings institutions who are members of the 12 Federal Home Loan Banks. Its common stock is owned by the home loan banks.
