<HEAD>Icahn Charges Texaco Managers `Blundered'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Financier <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>, whose bid for <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> was rejected last week, on Tuesday charged the oil giant `` engaged in a continuing series of damaging managerial blunders.'' In an amended counterclaim in response to a lawsuit filed by <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> contends <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> `` deliberately concealed information -LRB- and -RRB- made false and misleading statements to its stockholders.'' <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement from its <LOCATION> White </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, headquarters that the counterclaim was `` utterly groundless.'' The company said it would respond in detail through the normal litigation process. <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>, who offered to acquire <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> for $ 60 a share in a bid that values the company at $ 14.6 billion, complained that the company did not tell shareholders it offered him greenmail, which he has said he rejected. He also charged that <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> condoned the misuse of corporate assets in a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> real estate venture. <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> approached him with a third-party buyer willing to pay $ 50 a share for his stake in the oil giant, and said he rejected the offer because it `` smacked of greenmail.'' In the original counterclaim, <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> and his affiliates claimed that <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> and four directors made misleading statements in proxy material distributed to shareholders. The counterclaim charges the acts are `` part of a management scheme to entrench itself to the detriment of the stockholders.'' <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> has launched his own proxy fight in an attempt to win five seats on <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors and has extended his tender offer until <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s annual meeting on June 17. <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> President and Chief Executive Officer <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinnear </PERSON>, who is cited in <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>'s counterclaim along with three others, has been skeptical of <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON>'s ability to finance the buyout. As <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION>'s largest shareholder, <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> controls 14.8 percent of the oil giant's outstanding shares.
