<FIRST>r f AM-DeficitCommission     05-31 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deficit Commission,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commission Hears Recommendations On Congressional Budget Process</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The complex procedures by which <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> approves spending and tax plans are badly in need of reform including adoption of a two-year budget cycle, witnesses told a national commission Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, created by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to recommend ways to solve the government's budget woes, heard a variety of recommendations ranging from decreasing the number of congressional committees involved in budget writing to giving the president authority to refuse to spend money appropriated by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. But all of the witnesses cautioned the commission against spending too much time looking into the budget process, saying this was not the main flaw which has led to record federal deficits during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years. `` Creation of the deficit was the result of a series of policy mistakes and miscalculations, both economic and political, that process changes probably would not have prevented,'' said <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivlin </PERSON>, former head of the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>. `` Fixing the deficit requires having the political courage to face up to the problem and agree on a package of spending cuts and-or tax increases that will correct it,'' she said. The 12-member commission, headed by <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON> and former <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Drew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, was holding its second public hearing with a goal of coming up with a set of recommendations for the new president and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> by Dec. 21. The witnesses Tuesday all recommended switching from the current annual budgets, which have tied up <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in unending debate, to a two-year budget cycle. `` A two-year budget approved in the first year of each congressional term would substantially reduce the current burden of preparing and approving budgets in both the administration and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Niskanen </PERSON>, former member of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisers </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Niskanen </PERSON> also suggested that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had gone too far in restricting presidential power when it passed the Impoundment Control Act of 1974. That law prevented President <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> and his successors from simply refusing to spend money appropriated by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Any such `` impoundment'' of funds would have to be specifically approved by a positive vote in both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. `` In effect, appropriations are now both a ceiling and a floor on spending and there is no way to run a complex organization under these constraints,'' <PERSON> Niskanen </PERSON> said. `` The restrictions on impoundment authority should be recognized as an overreaction to the abuses of presidential authority during the Watergate era.'' <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Bell </PERSON>, former executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said he believed the government would have a `` substantially smaller deficit'' currently if the president still had authority to refuse to spend appropriated money. <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> said that any reforms should seek to make the process more understandable to the general public. `` The present process has descended into almost a cult of mysteries, reminiscent of the pagan cults of 2,000 years ago,'' he said. `` We need to change that so that more Americans can participate intelligently in this critical debate on fiscal policy and national priorities.'' <PERSON> Bell </PERSON> recommended combining many of the budgeting functions now shared by numerous congressional committees, restricting the types of amendments that can be offered to budget bills in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and giving the president the ability to veto individual items in a spending bill, a proposal long sought by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. Ms. <PERSON> Rivlin </PERSON> suggested that the administration should consider consolidating its own budget functions now scattered between the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisers </ORGANIZATION> into a single Cabinet agency responsible to the president for overall economic policy-making. `` The creaky, over-burdened budget process badly needs simplification,'' Ms. <PERSON> Rivlin </PERSON> said. `` The commission could do a major national service by emphasizing this fact and pointing the parties in a constructive direction.''
</TEXT>
