<FIRST>r f AM-HuntBrothers     05-31 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hunt Brothers,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nelson Bunker Hunt Tells His Story</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunker </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> testified Tuesday that inflation and world political events _ and not a plot by him and his brothers to corner the world silver market _ led prices to rocket in the late 1970s. In his first day of testimony in a multi-million dollar civil trial at federal court, <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> essentially repeated assertions made by defense lawyers in their opening statements last February. <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, 62, his brothers <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, 58, and <PERSON> Lamar </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, 55, are being sued by a South American silver concern that claims the <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Tex </PERSON>. brothers conspired to corner the world silver market between September 1979 and January 1980. Lawyers for <ORGANIZATION> Minpeco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SA </ORGANIZATION>, a mineral marketing company owned by the Peruvian government, claim the Hunts and several co-defendants were responsible for the sharp rise in silver prices from about $ 9 an ounce to more than $ 50 an ounce. Minpeco claims the skyrocketing prices caused it to lose more than $ 100 million when the world silver market collapsed in March 1980, with prices falling back to about $ 10 an ounce. But the rotund elder Hunt brother claimed he began investing in silver bullion and silver futures because of `` continuing inflation and certain political events.'' <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, who said he began investing in silver in 1973, said that by the fall of 1979 he was still telling people that `` silver was an overall good investment.'' But 1979 was `` a very unsettling year politically,'' said <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, in a low <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> drawl, noting the Iranian revolution that ousted the shah and took American diplomats hostage in <LOCATION> Teheran </LOCATION>; a continuing increase in oil prices; the Soviet invasion of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and the seizure of the Grand Mosque at Mecca by Islamic radicals. Hunt, whose legendary father, H.L. Hunt, made the family fortune in oil, said as oil prices began climbing _ to about $ 30 a barrel in late 1979 _ he bought more and more silver. But he claimed new commodity exchange rules limiting the number of futures contracts that could be held as well as increasing the amount to be put down on margin accounts `` was a difficult thing for the market.''
</TEXT>
