<HEAD>Producers, Writers Meet to Settle 12-Week Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with talks ending for day with
no agreement. Picks up 5th graf pvs ``The talks...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Striking scriptwriters and television and film producers failed to reach an agreement Tuesday to end the 11-week work stoppage that has shut down most Hollywood production, but they agreed to meet again Wednesday. A negotiating session with a federal mediator present began at 9 a.m. and ended shortly before 7:30 p.m., said to <PERSON> Cheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the 9,000-member <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON> declined to characterize the session. `` We had sidebar sessions and caucuses, but there was no full committee negotiations _ although everyone was present,'' Ms. <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> WGA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman had said earlier that full committee bargaining had been expected to begin Tuesday afternoon. Both sides agreed to resume their meeting at 3 p.m. Wednesday. Ms. <PERSON> Rhoden </PERSON> added that picketing in the strike that opened March 7 would resume Wednesday morning at the Paramount studios in <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>. The sessions are being conducted under the auspices of Commissioner <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mediation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in suburban <LOCATION> Sherman </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oaks </LOCATION>, 20 miles northwest of downtown <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. The talks followed a Memorial Day holiday weekend break during which both sides studied the impact of last week's overwhelming <ORGANIZATION> WGA </ORGANIZATION> ratification of a model contract with 73 independent producers. The talks followed a Memorial Day holiday weekend break during which both sides studied the impact of last week's overwhelming ratification by the writers' guild of a model contract with 73 independent producers. The independent contract, which permits immediate employment of an estimated 400 writers, covers such programs as `` The Cosby Show,'' and `` The Tonight Show with <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Carson </PERSON>.'' The three-year waiver contracts grant the writers' key demand: retention of the present formula for the residual payments that writers get for syndication of one-hour television shows. The union touted a split in management ranks, but alliance spokesman <PERSON> Herb </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> said the 73 independent contracts cover only a few guild members and none of the concerns involved were major companies.
